<HEADLINE>Ambulance radio delays cause safety concerns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897154</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PATIENTS in Scotland are being put at risk because of delays in modernising
radio equipment in ambulances, it was claimed yesterday.
A new microwave communications system has been operating in the North of
Scotland for the past year but has not been extended to southern areas where
most of the vehicles are based.
Mr Alan Devereux, chairman of the Scottish Ambulance NHS Trust, said the old
system was no better than that used by most taxi firms.
``It is about 20 years old and would do credit to a museum,'' he said. ``It is
archaic, inadequate, and potentially very dangerous.
``We are constantly having to patch it up. If you speak to any ambulance crew
in the South of Scotland, this is far more important to them than anything
else. They are often cut off from communication with their base and each other.
``We have had some close-run things. There is no doubt about that. Lives have
not been lost, simply because we have been quick-witted enough to find ways
around problems, but it is really risky.''
Mr Andrew Freemantle, SAS chief executive, has told his staff that the old
system is in a deplorable state. ``We have been continually thwarted by an
apparent lack of understanding elsewhere of the extent of our problem,'' he
said.
Mr Devereux said a decision in principle to cover the entire country by the
same same system had been taken two years ago but this had not been implemented.
A project board on which the SAS was represented had been considering
alternative proposals.
``They have been taking a long time to convince themselves that what we
proposed two years ago is the best possible option. Finding the finance has
also held it up,'' Mr Devereux said.
He said the SAS was now awaiting tenders under a Private Finance Initiative
next month to fund the #10m scheme. Even then, however, it would still take up
to 18 months to implement.
``I am not blaming the Scottish NHS management executive but this is an example
of how slow it is in this country to get things done. It has just gone on and
on and on,'' he said.
A Scottish Office spokesman said: ``We agree that a better radio service is one
of a number of priority measures which could improve the effectiveness of the
ambulance service.
``The Northern region was identified as the priority within Scotland and this
area has been addressed. We are actively engaged in a major procurement
exercise to improve on the radio service throughout Scotland.''
</TEXT>
