<HEADLINE>Army to cut number of planned redundancies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897155</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Army is almost halving the number of serving personnel it intends to make
redundant this year.
In January, it was envisaged that 500 people at various ranks would have to be
made redundant but this has been now reduced to 280, said Armed Forces Minister
Nicholas Soames in a written reply.
He said information on the number of applications for redundancy in the Army
was not available.
A Defence Ministry spokesman said last night that the reduction had nothing to
do with the increased number of troops being sent to Bosnia.
``Compared with the 110,000 Service personnel in the Army the change is very
small fry.''
Applications for redundancy from the RAF and Royal Navy this year out-stripped
Service requirements, Mr Soames disclosed.
A total of 11,540 applied to leave the RAF in 1995 and 3800 the Royal Navy and
Royal Marines. This exceeded requirements by 2940 and 1400 respectively. There
are approximately 75,000 personnel currently serving in the RAF and 50,000 in
the Royal Navy.
During debate on the Armed Forces Bill last night, Labour spokesman Dr John
Reid said he was perturbed by reports of large-scale misuse of drugs in the
armed forces.
``I am even more perturbed by reports that the Government intends to adopt a
softer line on recruitment policy when it comes to those with previous drug
convictions.''
He said: ``Whatever the pressures created by the shortfall of personnel, we
should send no signals to indicate that drug misuse is an acceptable background
to enlistment in the armed forces.
</TEXT>
