<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour backs down on ban</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897156</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Catholic Church last night praised a move by Labour to back off in the row
over anti-abortion campaigners being allowed to make their case at the party's
Scottish conference, which had soured relations with Cardinal Thomas Winning.
Relations between the party and the church hierarchy reached an all-time low
when a fringe group, Labour For Life, was denied the right to operate a stall
at conference. This provoked a breakaway move, led by Monklands East MP Helen
Liddell, by which individual MPs paid for a stall and allowed the group to
distribute their literature.
Nevertheless, the principle of the formal ban caused a rift between the party
and Cardinal Thomas Winning, who twice wrote letters of protest to Labour
leader Tony Blair. Observers read into the cardinal's pronouncements on other
issues - such as Shadow Home Secretary Jack Straw on beggars - signs of his
dissatisfaction over the ban.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson, who is understood to have moved the
successful motion ending the ban at the Scottish executive committee last
weekend, said yesterday: ``I am glad that the executive changed its position
and it is right that, where there is a legitimate debate going on in the party
and in Parliament, all sides should have a fair chance to express a view.''
At next year's Scottish conference, to be held in the new Edinburgh
International Conference Centre in March, Labour for Life will be allowed a
stall to put over its views. All stallholders, however, are being asked to
submit to checks in advance on their intended promotional materials to ensure
that shock tactics do not breach taste or decency.
Last night, Catholic Church spokesman Father Tom Connolly said: ``I am
absolutely delighted. For a party that has insisted for a long time that people
should have the freedom to choose, it was dreadful for them to ban debate, a
total contradiction.
``I think Cardinal Winning will be delighted, as will all freedom-loving
people.''
He cautioned against suggestions, however, that interpreted the cardinal's
subsequent speeches on social issues as being part of any split generally with
the Labour Party. ``We always speak on specific issues without aligning
ourselves with specific parties,'' he said.
The Herald understands that the decision to allow a stall - which does not
alter Labour's pro-choice policy on the abortion issue - was taken on a narrow
three-vote margin at last weekend's executive.
One senior party source called the row caused by the previous ban ``mayhem and
a serious embarrassment to the party''.
</TEXT>
