<HEADLINE>Pact aims to pacify Balkans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS DOUGHTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897157</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
FRANCE announced today that it hoped to crown tomorrow's signing of a Bosnian
peace deal in Paris with an agreement between the main Yugoslav republics to
live together in peace, seen as the key to stability in the Balkans.
Seeking to reassure Bosnia's Muslim-led government that it had done no deals to
win the release of two captured French pilots yesterday, Paris also said
Bosnian Serb leaders wanted by a UN crimes war tribunal must face justice.
Foreign ministers from former Yugoslav republics met today to negotiate a
possible deal on mutual recognition, which could be announced in time for the
ceremonial signing of a Bosnian peace deal tomorrow.
Such a deal, long sought by European mediators, would lower tensions and help
stop the Balkans sliding back into war. It would also represent a diplomatic
coup for Paris, which has taken a back seat to the United States in peace
negotiations.
``We are working on this subject, which is very difficult, but I think that
between the main countries of the former Yugoslavia, the recognitions will be
obtained today, tomorrow, or in the future days,'' de Charette told reporters.
The talks between Yugoslav ministers also concerned possible practical measures
to reassure Serbs in Sarajevo, who fear the deal may force them from their
homes and voted overwhelmingly against it in a referendum yesterday.
European peace co-ordinator Carl Bildt told a meeting of ministers from Europe,
North America, and the Islamic world that he would send a mission to Sarajevo
in the next few days to see how Serbs can be reassured.
However a blunt response came from Richard Holbrooke, the bullish chief US
negotiator who brokered the Bosnian deal at marathon talks in Dayton, Ohio,
last month.
``The so-called referendum has no standing, no consequence, no significance.
Dayton will go ahead unchanged,'' Holbrooke told reporters in Paris after
hosting a lunch with Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic and Serbian President
Slobodan Milosevic.
Major powers and Islamic nations gave their backing to the peace process at
another meeting, calling on the international community to help rebuild
war-shattered Bosnia and for all parties to co-operate with the UN war crimes
tribunal.
Yesterday's release of the two French air force pilots, held by the Bosnian
Serbs since their plane was shot down three months ago, cleared the final
hurdle to the Bosnian peace deal.
Defence Minister Charles Millon said no concessions had been made for their
freedom. France had simply threatened Serbia with the reimposition of UN trade
sanctions.
Nevertheless, Bosnian Foreign Minister Muhamed Sacirbey expressed concern that
Serb leaders Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic might now escape indictments
from the UN tribunal.
De Charette said this should not happen.
``Should those who are to be put before the tribunal . . . appear there? My
reply is yes. It is the duty of everyone to contribute to that end,'' he told
reporters.
The peace deal will split Bosnia almost equally between Serbs and a
Muslim-Croat alliance under a loose central government. The signing will open
the way for the main body of a 60,000-strong Nato-led implementation force to
move in.
French President Jacques Chirac will host tomorrow's full-pomp signing ceremony
with 50 states and international organisations at his Elysee Palace.
Later today, 30 states, including the former Yugoslav republics and their
Balkan neighbours, discussed how to foster long-term stability in the region.
De Charette said membership of the European Union (EU) would be open to all
former Yugoslav republics over time.
Signing tomorrow's peace deal will be Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic,
Croatia's Franjo Tudjman, and Milosevic, the Serbian strongman turned
peacemaker. Prime Minister John Major, US President Bill Clinton, and German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl will also attend.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
