<DOCNO>GH951214-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Down-to-earth Burns Supper</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897161</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN event which appeared to be threatened by problems besetting the Burns
International Festival will go ahead, its organisers said last night.
International Burns Suppers, which has organised celebrations for the bard's
birthday for the last two years, will stage a third on January 25 in Glasgow.
The event has attracted major performers.
The company had hoped to team up with the festival company in the year of
commemoration of the bicentenary of Burns's death to organise the world's
biggest Burns Supper, using satellite links with countries throughout the world.
That association has not come to pass, however, and the organisers are going
ahead with a terrestrial version of the event at the Moat House Hotel which is
expected to attract more than 400 people. The Burns International Festival has
forged links instead with the event staged earlier in the month by Ayr-based
WestSound Radio which is attended by around 1000 people.
Miss Alison Thistle, a director of International Burns Suppers, said: ``We are
disappointed that the event will not be staged at the level which had been
originally planned.''
The performers next month will include actor Tony Roper and musical artists
Mary Sandeman and Capercaillie.
Meanwhile, an appeal has been launched by a local arts trust, which was refused
backing for two events in the festival year, for funds to stage a musical
version of Tam O'Shanter, written by Michael Norris.
The Strathclyde Opera Theatre Trust planned a production of Verdi's Macbeth,
which has been cancelled, but they still plan to go ahead with the musical
version of the Burns' poem.
</TEXT>
