<HEADLINE>Cabinet withholds support for adoption of Euro-time</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897162</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Cabinet yesterday withheld support for a Tory back benchers' Bill seeking
to give Britain an extra hour of useable afternoon daylight but making dark
winter mornings longer. There will be a free Commons vote next month on the
issue.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth led the opposition to the proposal in
Cabinet. The majority of 72 Scottish MPs are against the Bill which was
presented in the Commons yesterday.
``The Government has agreed not to provide any time or assistance to this Bill
whatsoever and I will continue to use every effort I can to persuade colleagues
to have nothing to do with this legislation which I think is misguided,
unnecessary, and would be deeply damaging to Scotland,'' Mr Forsyth said.
Mr John Butterfill (Tory - Bournemouth West) has collected 11 other sponsors,
including Mr John Maxton (Labour - Glasgow Cathcart). Three other English
Tories support Mr Butterfill as do two English Liberal Democrats.
Mr Butterfill claims that the extra hour of daylight in the afternoon would
benefit the whole of the UK and that it is backed by several organisations
including the Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents, Age Concern, the
Police Federation, and the Suzy Lamplugh Trust.
Last night, Mr Butterfill's optimism seemed unfounded despite the fact that he
has some personal Ministerial support. The Bill may get second reading approval
but seems certain to founder in its later stages.
Mr Butterfill has offered a possible compromise - that Scotland should retain
Greenwich Mean Time while the rest of the country changes. But this is thought
unlikely to succeed.
An extra hour of daylight in the afternoon would be welcome but on previous
occasions when the proposal has been put to the test in the Commons MPs were
more concerned about schoolchildren facing an extra hour of darkness in the
mornings.
The Cabinet also agreed yesterday that the Government would support a Private
Bill by Lady Olga Maitland (Tory - Sutton and Cheam) which seeks to increase
penalties for carrying dangerous knives in public without just cause.
Home Secretary Michael Howard said yesterday that the greatest memorial that
could be provided for Mr Philip Lawrence, the London headmaster who was stabbed
to death outside his own school gates, would be to reinforce discipline and
respect for authority.
``It is only by emphasising and reinforcing those values that we can create a
climate in which crimes of this kind become much less frequent.''
The Bill would permit police to arrest anyone carrying a knife without good
reason. It would increase the maximum penalty from a #1000 fine to a six-month
jail sentence.
</TEXT>
