<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cameras prove a success in combating city-centre crime</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897163</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW Scottish Office research has shown that closed circuit television cameras
in town and city centres deter crime, and there is no evidence that crime is
merely displaced to areas outside the camera zones.
The research finding - based on the two years before cameras in Airdrie town
centre and the two years since - was released yesterday to coincide with the
opening of Scotland's latest CCTV scheme, in Paisley town centre.
Ironically, although the system, monitored by Strathclyde Police's Paisley
headquarters, was switched on, an armed robbery in Well Street, which took
place four hours ahead of the official opening, happened in an area not covered
by the cameras.
Scottish Home Affairs Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton yesterday gave
details of the Government's three-year challenge funding of #4m for new schemes.
A competition for the funding will be open to local partnerships which
demonstrate need and the ability to guarantee future running costs. Bids will
require to have police support and, Lord James confirmed, schemes such as those
in Paisley and Glasgow, which have received no direct government cash, will be
eligible to bid for funds to update or expand their systems.
Early research into the Glasgow city centre scheme is also understood to be
favourable. Discussions are, however, underway between the new Glasgow Council,
which will inherit the #250,000 annual running costs, and the various
participants - including major city centre traders and the Glasgow Development
Agency - about future funding.
It was confirmed to The Herald yesterday that a minority of traders have
refused to contribute although they are reaping the benefits from the increased
feeling of safety in the city centre, leading to increased sales. Other
beneficiaries of the cameras, including the new police authority and the
procurator-fiscal service, may be asked to contribute.
The main findings of the Airdrie research, carried out by Dr Jason Ditton and
Ms Emma Short, of the Scottish Centre for Criminology in Glasgow, confirm an
overall crime fall since the installation of the cameras of 21% in the town
centre, compared to the 24 months prior to their introduction.
Within that figure, crimes of dishonesty fell 48%. This included housebreaking,
shoplifting, and theft of and from vehicles, while vandalism and fire-raising
fell 19%.
The police clear-up rate improved by 16% in the 24 months after CCTV and, the
researchers found, there was no evidence to suggest that crimes were simply
displaced either to the immediately surrounding areas or to the rest of the
police sub-division.
In the rest of the police division, the researchers' control area, offences and
crimes fell by only 12%, while those in the CCTV area, in raw data terms, fell
by 35%. The fall in recorded crime throughout Strathclyde in the same period
was 7% while in Scotland as a whole crimes and offences rose 2% in the same
period.
The researchers said they had attempted to find the ``missing'' crimes and
offences by analysing crime figures and patterns in adjacent areas not covered
by CCTV.
Both of the chosen areas showed slight increases over the two years, almost
entirely accounted for by a rise in crimes of possession or supply of drugs,
and to offences committed while on bail.
These crimes respond directly to the level of police activity. Displacement
would have been suggested if there had been a corresponding decline in the CCTV
area, but this was not the case.
In accepting the #220,000 Paisley system from the town's centre management
trust, Chief Constable Sharp said the town's reputation for drugs and violence
was unjustified. Crime generally in Paisley was coming down. ``We should be
moving towards a genuine feel-good factor, so why do we need CCTV on the
streets?'' Dr Sharp asked, adding: ``Simply because crime is still too high. It
is now down to pre-1984 levels, but we can get it down even further.''
Similar drops in crime and increases in detection to those in Airdrie had been
experienced in Glasgow city centre, he said.
Leader comment - Page 18
</TEXT>
