<HEADLINE>Court-martial `doubts' over girl's case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897164</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE case of murdered Glasgow teenager Christina Menzies was raised in the
Commons yesterday as Labour Defence spokesman Dr John Reid claimed there were
inadequacies in the existing court-martial system in delivering justice in
homicide cases.
Speaking in the second reading debate on the Armed Forces Bill, Dr Reid said
that the 16-year-old girl - the daughter of an Army sergeant - was murdered in
Germany in 1993.
It was decided that, although the victim was a civilian, the accused person,
Lance-Corporal Darren Fisher, 23, of Reading, Berkshire, should be tried by
court-martial rather than by a German civilian court. Corporal Fisher was
acquitted.
Dr Reid said: ``There are many, including Christina's parents, the local MP (Mr
George Galloway - Hillhead) and the German authorities who feel strongly that
justice was not served by the acquittal.''
He said there were grave doubts about whether the prosecuting officer had the
necessary experience, especially since the defendant was able to hire a
specialist barrister through legal aid.
There were equally serious doubts about the handling of the forensic evidence.
He said: ``We need to seriously review the issue of courts-martial in these
circumstances and ensure that a case like that of Christina Menzies never
happens again.
``If we can achieve that, then perhaps the experience of this tragic and brutal
murder can be put to some good purpose.''
Armed Forces Minister Nicholas Soames, in reply, insisted that the case had
been very thoroughly investigated.
The prosecution was properly conducted, as was the trial, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
