<DOCNO>GH951214-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How a `Fairy godmother' provided the gift of life for a suffering child Chemical solution to baby's problem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897165</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CHEMICAL found in washing-up liquid has helped save a baby's life.
Laura Halpin suffered from a lung problem after she was born 12 weeks
prematurely and weighing 4lb 13oz.
Without the moisturising effect of surfactant, a chemical found in most
washing-up liquids, she would almost certainly have died.
Research by doctors, partly funded by the Glasgow branch of the charity
WellBeing, first discovered the curative effect of the chemical which is now
widely used throughout the UK and the world.
``But had Laura been born even just a few years ago, she would almost certainly
have died,'' said her mother Marion Halpin, a theatre nurse at Canniesburn
Hospital in Glasgow.
Mrs Halpin's medical history exacerbated the trauma of the emergency caesarean
operation. She had lost a child, Gary, two years ago after a premature birth.
Mrs Halpin, 26, and her husband John, 35, a dental technician, feared the worst
after Laura was born 10 months ago.
Mrs Halpin said: ``We thought the same thing would happen all over again. Laura
was on life-support machines almost from the minute she was born and it seemed
as though the day would never come when she would be able to breathe for
herself.
``Miraculously, the benefits of surfactant had just been discovered and she was
able to profit from it.''
After five weeks, the Halpins were allowed to take Laura home to Lenzie, near
Glasgow, from the Royal Maternity Hospital, Glasgow.
However, the baby was still on oxygen and needed constant care and attention.
Nevertheless, the long-term prognosis is excellent. ``She is as fit and healthy
as any other child now,'' said Mrs Halpin, `though it is a bit weird to think
of her survival being dependent on something you use to wash up dishes.
``We are just delighted that she is here with us - and are aiming to give her
the best possible Christmas she could have.''
Surfactants have been used for some time as a lubricant in commercial
washing-up liquids.
Their medical use was established around three years ago when their
moisturising effects were found beneficial, particularly on premature babies
who had not yet started to produce their own lubricants in the womb.
A spokesman for the Royal Hospital for Sick Children at Yorkhill said that even
three years ago the use of such chemicals was rare.
The surfactants are applied through an aerosol spray through the mouth and into
the lungs, similar to the inhalers used by asthmatics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Knife case man `set out to kill children'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897166</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KNIFEMAN Stephen Wilkinson was a near-genius who set out to kill children in a
``very dramatic and notable way'', a court was told yesterday.
A jury at Leeds Crown Court heard that loner Mr Wilkinson was driven by
paranoid schizophrenia when he burst into a classroom and repeatedly plunged a
knife into three schoolgirls, killing Nikki Conroy, 12, and wounding two of her
friends.
The court heard that Mr Wilkinson, 31, who was judged by Mensa to have a
near-genius IQ of 149, could not have stopped himself and there would have been
more killings had he not been overpowered.
Psychiatrist Peter Watson-Wood said: ``He set out to kill several people in a
very dramatic and notable way, probably children.'' He said Mr Wilkinson had
developed a severe mental illness which had had a dramatic effect on his life
since his late teens, adding: ``His responsibility was impaired very
substantially. He couldn't have done anything to stop himself.''
Mr Wilkinson, of Caversham Road, Middlesbrough, took knives, a replica gun, and
a hatchet to the town's Hall Garth School on March 28 last year. After charging
masked into the classroom and ordering the teacher out at gunpoint, he made the
children kneel in a line before stabbing Nikki, Emma Winter, 12, and Michelle
Reeve, 13.
Dr Watson-Wood de-scribed Mr Wilkinson as normally a ``placid, shy, and
retiring individual'' who believed he was ``God-like'' and persecuted.
Mr Wilkinson denies murder but admits manslaughter on the grounds of diminished
responsibility. He also admits the attempted murder of the other two girls.
</TEXT>
