<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chirac stands firm with Juppe on cuts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897167</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
q MEDICAL experts say the daily dose of transport chaos and labour unrest
brought by the French public sector strikes is driving thousands
to despair.
``The images of social paralysis on the television or in the newspapers is
really distressing people,'' said Henri Grivois, head of the psychiatric unit
at the Paris Hotel-Dieu hospital. ``I tell them to listen to music instead.''
A private psychiatrist said: ``People are getting an overdose of stress. I
have
seen a rise in the number of calls from people I don't know who want to be
treated urgently for anxiety.''
The three-week action is taking its toll on health. One frustrated commuter
told the paper Le Parisien: ``Last week I just cracked - I stayed in bed for
two days, aching all over.''
Paris drugstore owners said they had seen a marked increase in the number of
people asking for sleeping tablets. One GP predicted a rush for tranquillisers
as the added pressures of Christmas shopping and festivities kick in.--Reuter.
PRESIDENT Jacques Chirac said today that there was no turning back on bitterly
disputed welfare reforms while Prime Minister Alain Juppe offered striking
unions new concessions in a bid to lure them back to work.
Ceding more ground to railwaymen and civil servants, Juppe said he could see
no
reason why the public service stoppage, already in its 20th day, should go on.
However the main unions called for a new day of action on Saturday and decided
to extend transport strikes for another 24 hours though some smaller groups
voted to return to their jobs.
``We were not elected to bring about France's decline . . . There is no
alternative,'' Chirac told the Cabinet.
``I have confidence in the government's pursuit of this policy, quite simply
because there is no other,'' he said, urging Juppe to stand firm without
shunning ``dialogue and negotiation''.
Chirac also dismissed criticism of European monetary union, saying: ``This not
a debate over Europe versus jobs. The choice is between deficits and jobs.''
The government says new taxes and health cost controls are vital to wipe out
the social security deficit and thus help France qualify for European monetary
union. Unions want the welfare proposals scuttled.
Extending a new olive branch to striking railway workers, Juppe said talks on
reform of the debt-ridden SNCF state railways could start from scratch, as the
rail unions have demanded.
Juppe also told Parliament he would personally chair a December 21 conference
with unions and employers on jobs, a task he had previously assigned to Labour
Minister Jacques Barrot.
In a bow to civil servants, the deputy head of Juppe's office, Pierre-Mathieu
Duhamel, gave unions a written pledge that there would be no change in state
employees' retirement age or in the way their pensions are calculated - a
pledge that Juppe had granted earlier to train and Paris Metro drivers.
It effectively retracted Juppe's statement to Parliament last month that he
wanted civil servants to work 40 years instead of 37!s for a full pension,
bringing them in line with the private sector.
``There is no longer any reason for the strike,'' Juppe told a Cabinet
meeting,
adding that the situation was being politicised.
However a key union chief denied the strikes were meant to topple Juppe.
``I have not heard a single union leader demand the Prime Minister's head,''
said Louis Viannet, head of the giant Communist CGT union, told France Inter
radio. ``The problem is his policies.''-Reuter.
Paris
</TEXT>
