<HEADLINE>Man cleared of rape bid</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897168</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN serving life for raping a student was yesterday acquitted of a similar
charge.
The jurors were unware that William Stevenson, 28, had previous convictions.
He was on bail accused of attempting to rape a 23-year-old woman in Airdrie
when he attacked the student, aged 22, in Eastbourne, Sussex.
He claimed the student had been a willing partner and he made the same claim
this week when he denied attacking the woman in Airdrie.
Yesterday, a jury at the High Court in Glasgow found a charge against Stevenson
of attempting to rape the woman in Airdrie not proven by a majority after a
three-day trial.
The woman claimed Stevenson attacked her in her bedroom in 1993 after her
father invited him to spend the night on a couch.
Stevenson, originally from Possilpark, Glasgow, claimed the woman invited him
into her bedroom after her father left for work in the morning.
Stevenson was jailed for life at Lewes Crown Court in September for raping the
student after the court heard he had convictions for indecency, theft, and
fraud.
</TEXT>
