<DOCNO>GH951214-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots hit in travel collapse</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897170</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS holidaymakers will lose out on Christmas breaks after a travel company
ceased trading last night.
Bradley and Vaughan of Turnpike Parade, London, who traded as B and V Travel
and B and V Travel and Holidays, specialised in travel to the Canary Islands.
The company had arranged a Christmas programme flying from Glasgow to Las
Palmas and from Manchester and Gatwick to Tenerife.
The Civil Aviation Authority said passengers holding scheduled flight-only
tickets would still be able to travel. Others on fly-drive options or packages
would not.
The CAA is arranging for refunds for all those unable to travel, including
those booked on Oasis International and Air 2000 to the Canaries.
A CAA spokeswoman said: ``Passengers should contact us or their local travel
agent in Glasgow.''
The company, which was not a member of the Association of British Travel
Agents, has had its air travel organiser's licence bond of #63,510 called in.
The bond enables compensation to be paid or to pay for return flights for
stranded passengers.
Up until March this year, 125,000 people received refunds from the CAA after
travel company failures and a further 11,500 were brought home at a cost of
#16m.
</TEXT>
