<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jury warned of realms of fantasy Constable betrayed colleagues, court told</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897171</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE jury who will today decide the fate of a police officer were told yesterday
they might be tempted to think the facts they had heard outlined were from the
realms of fantasy.
Advocate-depute Alan Turnbull told the jury at the High Court in Aberdeen that
it was the type of thing one read about in books, or saw in the cinema or on
television.
It was a temptation to turn a blind eye to the indictment against Grampian
constable Neil Cooper, in the hope it could not be right, but he asked them to
convict him.
He said Mr Cooper, who faces two charges of attempting to defeat the ends of
justice and one of corruptly accepting #6000 and other payments in return for
providing confidential information to a man now serving 15 years for drugs
offences, had betrayed the trust of his colleagues.
``The allegations in this trial are of such a serious nature, such a disturbing
nature, that it is tempting to draw a veil over it,'' he told the jury.
``The relationship between police officers and the rest of society is one that
is at the very heart of the way we conduct our lives. The relationship between
the police and society is what distinguishes our society from a totalitarian
one.''
The two main Crown witnesses have been Ronald Cormack, the drugs dealer, and
his associate, Ian ``Fat Billy'' Smith, who, it has been heard, was a police
informant and friend of both Cormack and Mr Cooper.
Mr Turnbull said Mr Cooper had become ``infected'' by Smith and had been
prepared to take advantage of the trust which existed between him and his
colleagues for the benefit of Smith and Cormack.
He said that if Mr Cooper had acted properly when investigating an offence in
which a firearm was carried involving Smith and Cormack in 1991, Cormack's
drugs career would have been prevented because he would have been in jail.
``By 1993, Cooper is totally corrupted by Smith,'' he said. ``I don't know how
he gets that power but it is obvious he has got influence over Cooper.''
He said that if Mr Cooper was guilty he had always hoped no-one would believe
what Cormack and Smith said and that no-one would take their word against his.
``If he is guilty, he always intended to cynically take advantage of the trust
and confidence which existed in his office,'' Mr Turnbull said.
Mr Kevin Drummond QC, defending, told the jury that Cormack and Smith had lied
in the witness box.
He accused Cormack of being an evil liar whose evidence could not be
corroborated.
``This is a big game for Ronald Cormack,'' he said. ``He is living in a Walter
Mitty fantasy world in which he thinks he can say anything about anyone.
``Ronald Cormack is a paranoid liar. His allegations, under careful scrutiny,
do not stand up.''
He told the jury they were about to make the biggest decision in Mr Cooper's
life and that they had been given a glimpse into the murky world of organised
crime and drug dealing.
``This is a criminal trial in which there is a person on the most grave
charges,'' he said.
He called on the jury to find Mr Cooper not guilty, saying there was not a
shred of evidence to link him with Cormack.
Lord Macfadyen will address the jury this morning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
