<DOCNO>GH951214-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coroner condemns high-speed collision</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897172</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SALES drive for Porsche high-performance cars, which ended when three people
died, was criticised by a coroner yesterday after an inquest jury returned
verdicts of unlawful killing on two of the victims.
Renault 5 driver Karen Dalley, 22, and Devon businessman Derek Redfern, 57, who
was a passenger in a Porsche 911, died when the cars collided near the village
of Llyswen, Powys. A verdict of accidental death was returned on the Porsche
driver, car salesman Gavin Shaw, 30, of Cardiff.
The cars collided near the Llangoed Hall Hotel, which was being used by Cardiff
car dealers Merlin (Cambria) Ltd as a base for a sales promotion on June 11
this year.
The cars disintegrated and burst into flames after colliding at a closing speed
estimated by police at 150mph.
Deputy Powys coroner Geraint Williams said after the verdicts had been read at
the Brecon inquest: ``I have no comment about Mr Shaw's driving that day. It is
clear to me from evidence that, in the Llyswen area, Porsches were being driven
at astronomically high speeds.
``A number of people were driving recklessly or dangerously. I am exceedingly
surprised that there were not more accidents and I'm relieved that only three
people died.''
Ms Hilary Sykes, company secretary of Merlin (Cambria), said after the hearing
that the company found ``some difficulty with some of the comments''.
Dyfed-Powys police said later traffic patrols were unaware of the Porsche
demonstration in the area.
</TEXT>
