<HEADLINE>More present and correct: a matter of management</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DICK LOUDEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>table not available in database</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897173</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRAIDHURST High, which serves the North Motherwell area, is one of only seven
Strathclyde secondary schools to which the region has awarded a Band 1 rating
this year for attendance, writes DICK LOUDEN.
Strathclyde operates a system of seven bands under which it predicts the
absence rate for each school. Band 1, which indicates a ``commendably low
absence figure'', seems an unlikely achievement for Braidhurst High, whose
catchment area encompasses a great deal of deprivation.
Its absence rate of 13.1% may not seem minuscule but, when compared to a
predicted rate of 18.9%, it clearly stands out. And it is only one area in
which the school has succeeded against the odds.
Head teacher Derrick Hannan attributes much of the improvement to management
style.  He adopts a high personal profile and encourages an entrepreneurial
approach which has led to the setting up of a partnership base where there is
an emphasis on working with parents - and getting them involved in their
children's education.
He speaks of the ``astonishingly high work rate of staff at all levels,
including non-teaching staff''. For example, last year Braidhurst won an award
for the cleanest of 600 schools inspected and since then it has continued to
look extremely well-kept.
The senior management team promote a participative style, with teachers serving
on a range of staff committees and feeling they can make suggestions which will
be acted upon.
Hannan describes his school as ``in some ways traditional and old-fashioned''.
Exams for all year groups have been reintroduced, uniform is encouraged, there
are regular assemblies and two prize-giving ceremonies per year, recognising
not only acacademic achievement - but also regular attendance.
These are all factors which can influence and encourage attendance, but what
specific system does is operated to reduce absence? Extra time is provided for
guidance staff and Braidhurst's principal teacher of guidance, John Campbell,
uses print-outs of attendance to discuss individual cases with the four
assistant principal teachers.
The action to be taken is then identified - this can be a letter to parents,
counselling for the pupil, the issue of a monitoring card, or bringing in a
parent. Alternatively, it can involve a role for either the school's attendance
officer, Bill Shaw, or the partnership officer, Janine Barbour.
Shaw reports to the school on a daily basis for cases to pursue, while Barbour
sometimes works with chronic truants, for whom the solution may be a partial
subject timetable supplemented by group activities, leading to phased
resumption of a full timetable. Hannan sees a ``definite correlation'' between
regularity of attendance and results in the SCE examinations. The tone is set
in first year, when parents are informed of targets (academic and otherwise)
which are set for all pupils.
``We have very few youngsters who are not presented for everything,'' says
Hannan. ``An enormously high percentage of candidates actually turn up and,
when they don't, we have been known to knock on their doors and get them out of
their beds.''
</TEXT>
