<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Doctors mystified by boy's flu death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897174</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN eight-year-old Paisley boy has died from flu in what has been described as a
``tragic but rare'' case, it was confirmed last night.
The death of Stephen McKenzie, of Broomlands Street, has mystified doctors
because he had been in good health. Flu deaths usually occur among elderly
people with medical complications.
Stephen contracted flu along with his five-year-old sister Lyndsay last week.
His condition did not appear serious when he went to bed on Friday evening but
his parents found him slumped at the top of the stairs on Saturday morning. He
was confirmed dead on arrival at Royal Alexandra Hospital.
A post-mortem examination on Tuesday confirmed that the cause of death was flu.
Argyll and Clyde Health Board released news of the tragedy last night, urging
parents not to panic.
Three children have died from flu since 1990, two aged under five and one aged
between five and 10. A total of 321 deaths were registered during that period,
mostly elderly people with medical complications.
The boy's parents, Thomas, a production worker, and Jacqueline, a domestic at
the Royal Alexandra, said he had been ill for a couple of days before he died.
They suspected he was suffering from flu. They were said to be stunned by their
son's death.
The couple's daughter has now recovered and is said to be back at St Mary's
Primary School, Maxwellton Road. Both children are reported to have been
prescribed penicillin.
Dr David Sloan, consultant in public health medicine, stressed that fellow
pupils and other children were not at risk from any virulent strain of flu.
He said: ``This exceptional and tragic case could give the public the wrong
idea about the current upsurge in flu.
``The annual influenza epidemic has been of moderate severity and next week
should
Continued on Page 2
Continued from Page 1
see us over the worst of it. The severity of illnesses it causes are no worse
than usual for influenza A.''
He said one of the tragedy's surrounding Stephen's death was that he had
appeared to be healthy. He added: ``We are not sure why it was so severe in
this young boy. Certain individuals are struck down like this and it is
difficult to say why they are susceptible.''
Dr Sloan said high-risk categories included children suffering from conditions
such as chronic lung, heart, and kidney disease, diabetes, and those with
depresed immune systems caused by diseases such as leukaemia or treatments such
as radiotherapy.
Dr Sloan said children in those categories should be immunised every year but
routine jabs for fit children and adults were not recommended.
He said there should not be any rush to immunise children.
He added: ``There is very little risk to ordinary children of serious illness
from influenza and we will soon be past the worst of this year's outbreak.
``Parents should also remember that it takes at least two weeks for the vaccine
to give protection. It is not recommended for children under six months or
older children who have not had the vaccine before. A second dose is needed
four to six weeks later to give adequate protection.
``Most children bounce back from flu but if they are severely affected, parents
should seek medical advice.''
A report will be sent to the procurator-fiscal who may decide to hold a fatal
accident inquiry. There are no suspicious circumstances. It is understood the
funeral will be held tomorrow.
</TEXT>
