<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Case of `dingo baby' unsolved</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897175</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Darwin
A COURT in Australia ruled today that it was unable to determine officially the
cause of death of baby Azaria Chamberlain, who disappeared 15 years ago in one
of the country's most baffling mysteries.
Coroner John Lowndes ruled there was not enough evidence to say either a dingo
took the baby, as claimed by the parents, or that her mother, Lindy
Chamberlain, was involved.
``The only finding I can record is an open one,'' Lowndes told an inquest in
Darwin.
Lindy Chamberlain was convicted of Azaria's murder in 1982 but later acquitted.
Her husband Michael was found guilty of being an accessory and was also
acquitted.
Today's finding, ending a series of inquests, trials, appeals, and special
inquiries, means the case remains unsolved.
The court had been asked to find that a dingo, Australia's native wild dog,
snatched the nine-week-old baby from their tent at Ayers Rock, now known by its
Aboriginal name, Uluru, in 1980.
The parents had also asked to be officially cleared of any involvement in
Azaria's disappearance.
Azaria's body has never been found. Only her bloodstained baby jacket was
recovered.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Policeman stabbed at domestic dispute</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897176</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A POLICE officer was in intensive care last night after being stabbed as he
attended a domestic dispute which ended in a knife-point siege.
Constable Peter Walsh, 35, needed surgery and a 10-pint blood transfusion after
the stabbing at the home of a warring couple in Ousten, near Chester-le-Street,
County Durham, a police spokesman said.
Another officer was slashed across the face with a long-bladed Bowie knife by
the man, in his 20s, who later held his common-law wife and two-year-old
daughter at knife-point for three hours.
After the stabbing at 2am, armed police surrounded the couple's council home
until the man, who had threatened to kill any officer who came near him, was
finally arrested in his back garden. The second officer, who has not been
named, was taken with Mr Walsh to Dryburn hospital, Durham, but was allowed
home after treatment.
Mr Walsh, who is married with two children and has twice been commended for
bravery in his nine-year career with Durham police, was ``stable and
comfortable'', a hospital spokesman said.
q Doctors yesterday called for talks with the Government and police officers in
the light of the stabbing of London GP Anthony Inwald.
GP leaders have told the Department of Health that special secure surgery
premises may be needed for persistently violent patients.
Dr Judy Gilley, deputy chairman of the British Medical Association's GPs'
Committee, said: ``We have been very worried about the increasing incidence of
abuse and violence against GPs for some time and wrote to the Department of
Health only last week seeking discussions on this issue.''
She said a national survey last year revealed that one in four inner-city GPs
had been physically assaulted in their surgery. A total of 83% said they had
been verbally abused.
A 29-year-old woman was remanded in custody for a week when she appeared in
court charged over the stabbing of Dr Inwald. Ms Maria Caseiro, of Kystalls
Hotel, Holloway, north London, was charged with causing grievous bodily harm
following the stabbing at St John's Way medical centre.
q A 44-year-old soldier was fighting for his life after being stabbed in a
frenzied knife attack as he walked through a seaside resort with his wife.
The couple had just left a function in a hotel at Portrush on Northern
Ireland's County Antrim coast in the early hours when the knifeman struck.
He plunged a knife repeatedly into the soldier's chest and stomach before
running off.
The victim, a member of the Royal Irish Regiment, is understood to live in the
town and was named locally as David Reid. He was taken to Coleraine Hospital a
few miles away for emergency overnight surgery.
q A 15-year-old boy yesterday was sentenced to four years' detention for
stabbing a man to death with a penknife. The youngster - who cannot be named
for legal reasons - wept throughout the hearing at Liverpool Crown Court.
The court was told the youngster got into a fight with 25-year-old Paul Jeory
near his home in Blackburn, Lancashire, on March 10, 1995, three days after his
15th birthday.
Witnesses told police that Mr Jeory had accused the defendant's brother of
being a police informer and had then head-butted the boy in the fracas in
Mosley Street, Blackburn.
The boy then stabbed Mr Jeory in the chest with a small pocket knife.
</TEXT>
