<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dreaming of a light Christmas By the twelfth day of festive fare many of us will empathise with the sugar plum fairy, but Dr Christine Fenn and Ann Shaw believe that the best cure is prevention</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christine Fenn</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897177</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MENTION the word Christmas and you think parties, presents, and putting ``Must
Lose Weight'' at the end of it all. It is a time of celebration in the midst of
winter, but the laws of physics still apply, writes Dr Christine Fenn.
Calories IN must balance Calories OUT, otherwise the surplus is stored in the
fat cells around your thighs and hips ......just in case you ever go short of
food in the future.
Not surprisingly, many of us tip the balance and increase our fat stores. This
is because, although our stress levels go through the roof, our calorie needs
go down.
Unfortunately, writing Christmas cards, licking the stamps, making paper
chains, agonising over what size tree to buy and cringing at the thought of
coping with relatives, do not use many calories.
No wonder that we turn to food for comfort - and there is plenty of temptation.
The endless number of office parties, Christmas lunches, and selection boxes
can mean a serious increase in eating. At the end of it all, you have literally
had enough.
You never want to see another mince pie or lump of cheese on a cocktail stick;
yet again the words ``Go On A Diet'' appear at the top of your list of New Year
resolutions. Never fear: help is at hand, and prevention is better than cure.
Most of the calories come from the fat in foods. The trick is to avoid the fat
before it ever gets near your plate, let alone your hips. Turkey is an
excellent low fat meat, and by knowing where the fat is lurking, it is possible
to eat fabulous festive meals which add to the enjoyment, not the calories.
The average man on Christmas day (who spends the day eating and drinking,
opening presents, and boiling over with stress while coping with the family),
needs 2550 calories, with only 100 grams of fat.
The average woman (who buys the presents, cooks the meal and mends the fairy
lights), will need 1900 calories and 74 grams of fat.
n Dr Christine Fenn, FRSH, FRGS, is a freelance nutritionist based in Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bid to get sex charges dropped</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897178</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN eminent Scottish theologian will try next month to have sex-related assault
charges against him thrown out of court.
A hearing will be held to establish whether or not Professor Donald Macleod,
55, of Craiglea Drive, Edinburgh, can have a fair trial.
Professor Macleod, who holds the chair of systematic theology at the Free
Church of Scotland College in Edinburgh, faces six charges alleging sexual
assault involving five women. The charges date from July 1985 to June 1992.
His lawyer will argue next month that none of the six charges should go to
trial.
Professor Macleod is alleged to have assaulted four of the women by putting his
arms around them and kissing them or attempting to kiss them. Two charges
relate to one woman during 1986 in which he is alleged to have interfered with
her clothing and handled her breasts and private parts.
Four of the assaults are alleged to have taken place at the Free Church college
on The Mound and the other two at his home and in a parked car at the Cameron
Toll shopping centre in Edinburgh. The case had already been continued without
plea twice at Edinburgh Sheriff Court but yesterday defence solicitor Mr Eric
Scott entered a plea in bar of trial which will be considered at a hearing on
January 23.
q.Professor Macleod was last night unhappy over speculation claiming he planned
to join the ministry of the Church of Scotland.``It is one of the many options
I have to consider. The Free Church has thrown my life into turmoil. It is one
of many possibilities,'' he said.
</TEXT>
