<DOCNO>GH951214-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deal on Enterprise cut done at hotel dinner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897179</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE 7.5% cut in the budget of Scottish Enterprise was a deal done over dinner
in a London hotel, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth disclosed yesterday.
He told the Commons Select Committee on Scottish Affairs that he met Scottish
Enterprise chairman Donald MacKay and chief executive Crawford Beveridge for
dinner ``and in the course of that dinner the question of the budget did
arise.''
The dinner took place at the Royal Horseguards Hotel, just off Whitehall, on
November 15, and Mr Forsyth yesterday gave some details of the conversation
which led to a reduction of #33m in the Scottish Enterprise budget.
Referring to Mr MacKay, the Secretary of State told the committee: ``He
indicated that if the reduction was more than 7.5% he could not maintain all
the outputs we place importance on. I had in mind to cut by 10%, but I was
persuaded because he was prepared to take a sensible approach and maintain all
the services. That was the right decision to take on behalf of Scottish
Enterprise.''
The SNP's Andrew Welsh demanded to know whether Mr MacKay had volunteered the
cuts.
Mr Forsyth said: ``He recognised that this was a tight public spending round
and he knew there would have to be reductions in his budget. He looked at ways
of meeting the obligations of Scottish Enterprise and decided he could meet all
of these with a reduction of 7.5%.
``Those people who have criticised him are deeply misguided. We should have
people running these bodies who are looking for the best value for money. The
way he (Mr MacKay) went into this is an example for others to follow.''
Mr Forsyth produced an aggressive performance at his annual grilling by the
committee, at which he is challenged by MPs on his public expenditure plans.
He clashed with a number of committee members on the constitutional issue after
pointing out that he had secured a deal giving Scotland 35% per head more money
than England and Wales.
The Secretary of State told the committee he had had a difficult time
justifying his budget, and warned what the difference would be under a devolved
Scottish parliament.
He said there were people in the Treasury who wanted Scotland's funding to be
calculated on a ``needs based'' evaluation, and once again warned about the
tartan tax, stating that ``the present arrangements serve us rather well, and
we would be getting into dangerous waters indeed if we opened that up to
scrutiny.''
In direct clashes with the committee chairman, Kilmarnock and Loudoun Labour MP
Willie McKelvey, Mr Foryth took a robust line.
Mr McKelvey: ``I don't want to get bogged down on this issue.''
Mr Forsyth: ``I think you are pretty well bogged down on it, Mr Chairman.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Report expresses serious doubts over truancy figures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SERIOUS doubts have been raised about the true levels of unauthorised, or
unexplained, absence in Scottish secondary schools.
Attendance and absence tables published yesterday by the Scottish Office showed
that schools with the highest unauthorised absence rates, most commonly
truancy, in 1993-94 had dramatically reduced their figures this year.
But their authorised absence rates, which are explained and do not attract the
same adverse publicity, had increased by almost the same amount.
The one school which most vigorously recorded unauthorised absence paid the
price by having the highest rate.
It rose from 0% to 16% at Linlathen High, Dundee. The school's deputy rector,
Mr Iain Duncan, said: ``We have played it by the book and perhaps we have
suffered because of that. We are in the limelight for the worst possible
reason.''
Scottish Office officials said they had no evidence that the figures were being
juggled. Mr Archie McGlynn, director of inspectors of schools' audit unit, said
such action would not be sensible.
``Schools have produced the figures. They have to believe in them and defend
them,'' he said. There is growing disquiet, however, that schools are
interpreting Scottish Office guidelines on authorised and unauthorised absence
to put the best gloss on their non-attendance figures.
Scottish Office Minister for Education Raymond Robertson said he wanted to know
why there were big discrepancies in attendance and absence rates across
Scotland.
According to the figures, absence in the primary sector was an average of 5% -
equivalent to each pupil being absent for ten and a half days in the school
year - while in secondaries it was 12%, equivalent to 22 days.
Unauthorised attendance in the secondary sector averaged 1%.
The report gives for the first time information about the number of pupils
excluded from school. The authorities which educate the majority of Scottish
pupils do not have a policy of permanent exclusions but of those which do,
Lothian had the highest number, 83 from its secondary schools.
Pupils in Glasgow secondaries lost the most half days because of temporary
exclusions, nearly 35,000 between January and June.
Comeback kids 8
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>I didn't feel like going in</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897181</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARTIN, aged 14, is a third-year pupil who can be classed as a ``casual
truant''. He is a pleasant, soft-spoken boy who does not regard school as a
hostile environment.
I always attended well when I was at primary school. I started dogging it
halfway through first year. It wasn't something I planned - it was just that
some of my pals were doing it and they asked me to join in. One of them did it
nearly every day.
There were other times when I didn't go in because I had forgotten to do my
homework or a punishment exercise. I knew the punishment would be doubled if I
showed up. Once this year, I dogged it three times in a row. It was just that
sometimes, when I got up, I didn't feel like going in.
A few times my big sister wrote a note for me. I got found out because my wee
brother started dogging it too. The school got on to my mum. She was supposed
to see the attendance officer but she made a mistake about the day and she got
a letter instead. She blamed me for getting my brother into trouble, though he
wasn't dogging with me.
I stopped it a couple of weeks ago and I won't go back to it. I want to be a
joiner or engineer - that's why I'm taking craft and design and graphics - and
I'm doing all right, pretty average. I know I've got to attend to get a good
job. It was Wednesdays that I used to dog most. That was the worst day - RE and
modern studies and maths and all that stuff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Threat to EU funding from `real' cuts Fishermen fear result of new budget</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897182</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEARS that this week's public spending announcement masked deep cuts in support
for the fishing industry will be raised at a meeting today between
representatives of the Scottish Fishermen's Federation and the Government.
While the Minister involved, Mr Raymond Robertson, is being questioned about an
apparent lack of support leading to the loss of European aid to which the
industry is entitled, the SNP will be tabling a series of questions in the
House of Commons aimed at prising out information which was lacking during the
announcements of the Scottish Office spending round on Monday.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth made virtually no mention of agriculture and
fisheries spending during his budget announcement to the Scottish Grand
Committee on Monday. The only reference was to spending on agriculture,
fisheries, and food being part of the UK announcement issue on Budget day on
November 28.
That intimation, which even leaders of the Scottish Fishermen's Federation did
not receive at the time, concentrated heavily on increases in UK spending on
the Common Agriculture Policy and domestic spending on farming. It did say that
#12m per year had been earmarked for the decommissioning of vessels over the
next two years.
But it added that: ``It has been decided that the EU grant schemes for
fisheries processing and marketing, port facilities, and aquaculture production
under the Financial Instrument for Fisheries Guidance will not be launched in
England.''
It added that the national harbour grant scheme was ending immediately and said
that next year only #500,000 of grants would be available under the European
PESCA scheme, which aids hard-hit fishing communities.
Mr Bob Allan, chief executive of the SFF, had to ask the Government yesterday
for a copy of the November statement, and he said it was unclear just how it
related to spending north of the Border - something he would be pressing Mr
Robertson on today.
SNP leader Alex Salmond, whose Banff and Buchan constituency is the heartland
of the fishing industry, sensed earlier this week that the trend of public
spending was away from fishing in the direction of support for spending on the
Common Agricultural Policy, and he has tabled a series of Commons questions
about the level of structural support for fisheries past and present.
He said last night: ``With 14% of the European fishing fleet, the UK receives
only 2% of EU funding. Something is afoot here. It is just a question of how
far it affects Scotland.
``Obviously, given the rumours that are spreading about further cutbacks in
structural assistance, there is the danger that Scotland's fishing industry
will yet again be blocked from financial assistance from Europe as a result of
Westminster's intransigent policy.''
He said this had already happened with aid for fleet decommissioning and
upgrading, and there was now a serious problem with participating in the PESCA
scheme because the Government was insisting that cash-strapped local
authorities, rather than the Scottish Office, provided the matching funding
without which European money is frozen.
``I want clear answers to the questions I have tabled so that we can assess
whether, yet again, Whitehall will be setting an empty place for Scotland at
the European table,'' he said.
Mr Allan said it was far from clear what the current spending round implied for
the fishing industry, and he would be putting some hard questions to the
Minister today.
``Until we hear what they have to say I am keeping my powder dry,'' he said.
``I would be very, very concerned if an already bad situation was made any
worse.''
q Tory Euro-rebels are planning to mount a challenge to the Government in the
Commons next week over the ``appalling deal'' struck over the Common Fisheries
Policy.
This could mean another cliffhanger for the Government, with the Conservative
majority now reduced to five.
Mr Tony Marlow, MP for Northampton North, said that he and others who lost the
Tory whip and then regained it, would be tabling an amendment for a debate,
probably to be held on Tuesday.
This will call for the ``re-establishing of control over our own waters'' to be
a manifesto commitment at the next General Election.
Labour said last night that it would be tabling its own amendment in a bid to
inflict another embarrassing defeat on the Government over Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Keeping fit can rub you up the wrong way</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Dr David Delvin</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Man Alive</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897183</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Q. I try to keep myself fit, so I go out and do a spot of jogging several times
a week. But I have noticed that on longer runs a very odd thing happens. The
skin of my chest begins to get very sore as it rubs against my rugby shirt, and
then my nipples become awfully sensitive and eventually start to bleed. I'm not
turning into a woman or something, am I?
A. Definitely not! You're simply suffering from the famous condition of
``jogger's nipple''. This is caused by constant friction on the areola, which
is the disc around the nipple. In the days when I used to run half-marathons, I
often finished up with two rather embarrassing red circles on my singlet - due
to bleeding.
The remedy is to put lashings of Vaseline on the nipple area before you go out
jogging. Alternatively, use two strategically positioned pieces of sticking
plaster.
Q. To settle an argument with my wife, is alcohol good for a man's heart, or
not?
A. Recent research suggests one or two glasses of red wine per day may (and I
stress the word ``may'') help protect both men and women against heart
diseases. Despite what the Government claims, the case is very much ``not
proven'' at the moment. But it could be one reason why the French are much less
likely to get coronaries than the British is the fact so many of them like a
couple of glasses of vin rouge on a daily basis.
However, it's important to realise there's no convincing evidence as yet that
the findings about red wine can be extrapolated to cover other kinds of
alcohol, like whisky or pints of heavy! Furthermore, please bear in mind
there's no doubt regular high levels of alcohol intake (as opposed to a couple
of glasses a day) are strongly associated with chronic illness and a short
life.
Q. A man who had had an affair with a highland woman wrote to you a couple of
weeks ago, and you advised him he stood very little chance of catching HIV from
her. I think this is most irresponsible advice! We should all be aware of the
fact heterosexual fornication can and does lead to Aids.
A. It can indeed, sir, but let's look at the statistics. In all the years since
Aids began, how many Scottish males do you think have contracted HIV through
``straight'' (ie heterosexual) intercourse? The answer is just 163. That's
right: 163. While these are tragic occurrences, they are mercifully rare ones.
Furthermore, over half of those exposures (86) took place abroad - the great
majority of them being in Africa.
So while we all need to be vigilant about Aids, the truth is that the risk from
``straight'' sex in rural Scotland is still pretty low. The highest HIV rate is
in the Lothian Health Board area, where there are 102 known cases per hundred
thousand people.
Tayside comes second with 59 per 100,000, while Greater Glasgow is a long way
back at 34/100,000 and Grampian far behind that at 13/100,000. In the rest of
the country, the incidence is still minute, at about nine per 100,000.
Q. I passed black motions this morning and it gave me quite a scare. But I've
heard this can just be due to drinking wine. Is that so?
A. All adults should be on the look-out for black motions, because the symptom
often indicates internal bleeding. However, black stools can also be caused by
drinking red wine (not any other kind of plonk) and by taking iron tablets. So
if you had some claret or red Burgundy or whatever the night before this
episode, you have nothing to worry about. If you didn't, consult your doctor
immediately.
MAN ALIVE / Dr David Delvin
</TEXT>
