<HEADLINE>Plea to end armed forces ban on homosexuals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897184</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Commons last night heard a plea for a lifting of the ban on homosexuals
serving in the armed forces.
Mr Alan Howarth (Stratford-on-Avon), who caused political controversy when he
defected from Tory to Labour on the eve of the Conservative conference in
October, insisted that sexuality should have no bearing on people's eligibility
to serve their country - a view which has been contested by Service chiefs.
His plea came as Armed Forces Minister Nicholas Soames opened the second
reading debate on the Armed Forces Bill, which is introduced every five years
to renew the forces' discipline Acts.
Mr Howarth challenged the Minister: ``Will you accept that homosexuals are just
as likely as anybody else to be highly competent and professional members of
the armed services and that their sexuality should have no bearing on their
eligibility to serve their country, and will you legislate to that effect?''
Labour's Harry Cohen (Leyton) attacked the ban and told the House that the MoD
review on homosexuality in the forces ``has already been seriously compromised
and has already come dangerously close to being an exercise to encourage
hostility toward existing serving homosexuals''.
Mr Soames insisted that the views of the MoD and senior military officers ``are
not in any sense homophobic or judgmental.
``They are to do with military discipline and good order and the immensely
strong and truly genuinely-held feelings of thousands of people in the armed
forces.''
On measures contained in the Bill, Mr Soames told the House it would:
q.Introduce reforms to the procedures of courts-martial.
q. Extend the time limit allowed to service personnel to take cases to
industrial tribunals.
q.Allow flexibility in dealing with ``those whom it would be preferable to
retain'' but who refused to take part in drugs tests.
THE Army is almost halving the number of serving personnel it intends to make
redundant this year.
In January, it was envisaged that 500 people at various ranks would have to be
made redundant but this has been now reduced to 280, Mr Soames said.
</TEXT>
