<DOCNO>GH951214-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lothian green belt warning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897185</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth yesterday told Lothian Regional Council
there must be a tightening of policies to safeguard the green belt from
unnecessary development.
He was commenting on changes he was proposing to the region's Structure Plan,
intended to guide development in the area to the year 2005.
Mr Forsyth said his proposed modifications did not alter the main thrust of the
plan, which had been submitted to him earlier this year.
A Scottish Office report recommended an Edinburgh green belt study was required
to confirm boundary lines.
The report added that where land was required to implement any changes, there
had to be obligations placed on potential developers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Grandparents say gypsy child is not missing Ben</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897186</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE grandparents of missing Ben Needham last night told officials that a child
found with gypsies in Greece was definitely not their grandson.
Chris and Eddie Needham watched video footage of the six-year-old boy, taken
into custody by police from a gypsy camp, in the hope of recognising Ben who
vanished four-and-a-half years ago.
However, they were in no doubt their search was not yet over. ``It obviously
wasn't him,'' said Mr Needham. ``He was dark skinned and dark eyed and so
obviously not English.''
Greek police last night issued a statement saying they were now sure the child,
who was first discovered by a private detective in the northern town of Veroia,
was not ``Baby Ben'' who, at two years old, went missing while playing on a
beach a few yards from his grandparents' holiday house on the island of Kos.
The boy, who had been the focus of enormous media attention since he apparently
told investigator Stratos Bakirtziz that he had been given to the gypsies
because his parents did not want him, would now be released to return home, a
spokesman said.
Mr Needham, 47, who has never given up hope that blond, blue-eyed Ben will be
found, said: ``I never felt that this kid was him. But you never know what
might happen.''
The couple, who are staying on the holiday island of Kos, were about to speak
to Ben's mother, Kerry, who was waiting for news at her home in Foxhill,
Sheffield.
``I hope she will be OK,'' said Mr Needham. ``She's never come to terms with
it. That's why she could not come out to Greece.''
The family would go on searching until Ben was found, he said. ``You never get
used to it but after four-and-a-half years the disappointments get easier.''
There have been numerous false sightings of Ben, including other reports that
he has been seen with gypsies in northern Greece. Two months ago, the Needhams
travelled to Salonika when a headmaster thought a boy in his school answered
Ben's description.
Mr Stratos Vakirtziz, who had said he was 100% sure he had got the right boy
and was claiming the #30,000 reward for finding Ben, told reporters the police
had the wrong one.
``This child is not the one I saw. The gypsies must have hidden him and brought
this boy forward,'' he said.
Police chief Ioannis Panousis dismissed the claims. A birth certificate
provided by the boy's family was authentic and the child's father, now in a
Greek prison, confirmed he had left his son with them.
Greek police were always sceptical that the child, who did not have Ben's blue
eyes or distinctive birth mark, could be the one they sought. ``We went by the
book on this one because it attracted so much international attention.
Otherwise, we would have closed the case much earlier,'' a spokesman said.
Long torment 15
</TEXT>
</DOC>
