<DOCNO>GH951214-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man sues over handcuffs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897187</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN is to sue police after claiming that he was injured by a new style of
handcuff.
Paul Thomson, 25, of Dougrie Drive, Castle-milk, Glasgow, claims that as a
result of being clamped in the new rigid quick cuffs he was treated in hospital
for damage to a nerve and muscle in an arm and bone damage to an elbow.
His solicitor, Mr Alan Miller, told Glasgow Sheriff Court yesterday that
Thomson was taken to Aitkenhead Road police station in agony because of the
cuffs. He said that when Thomson complained his fingers were turning blue, an
arm was forced behind his back, resulting in his having to go to hospital next
day.
Thomson admitted being in possession of a pepper spray which he had bought in
America.
Sheriff J M Smith admonished Thomson and ordered forfeiture of the spray.
q A prisoner, who tried to bite off a pair of uncomfortable handcuffs, appeared
in court in Tewkesbury, Gloucestershire, yesterday, accused of damaging them
with his teeth. Michael Lippet, 18, was conditionally discharged for a year and
ordered to pay #16 compensation for the damaged cuffs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish health budget unveiled</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897188</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH Boards were told yesterday how much they would get from the #2800m being
made available for next year's hospital and community health services budget.
Although Scottish Health Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton said this was a
record level of funding - it represents an increase on paper of 3.11% - it will
leave hospitals with less to spend in real terms.
Official sources have acknowledged that the overall NHS budget for Scotland,
#4200m, represents an increase in real terms of 0.2%.
However, this growth is taken up largely by the primary care budget - the other
main arm of the service.
This leaves the hospital and community health services to find their required
efficiency savings target of 3%, or #83m.
The overall cash increase, 6.11%, would enable health boards and NHS trusts to
meet the costs of pay and price increases, demography, and medical advance.
All efficiency savings - including #18m expected to result from management
costs - were to be reinvested in the service for the benefit of patient care.
Lord James said: ``The additional funds will enable an increase in acute
inpatient and day case activity of around 5%, which equates to about 53,000
cases. It will also enable the service to meet Patient Charter commitments,
reduce waiting times and make progress on our three health priorities of mental
health, cancer, and cardio and cerebro-vascular disease.
``NHS trusts' capital expenditure will, with private finance initiative
projects, represent a record level of capital investment in the NHS in
1996-97.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plan emphasises new heritage priorities</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897189</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COTTISH Natural Heritage is to be given a revised remit to reflect changes in
its priorities and the level of Government funding allocated to it.
Set up only three-and-a-half years ago following a merger between the Nature
Conservation Council for Scotland and the Countryside Commission for Scotland,
it suffered a 10% cut in its budget this week of almost #5m in the public
expenditure spending round. Concerns were already being expressed last night
that SNH's recreation, access, environmental education, and reserve management
functions might fall victim to the reorganisation.
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth told the House of Commons yesterday, in
response to a parliamentary question, that he had accepted the main proposal of
the report of the study group that a revised policy document, The Way Ahead,
should be prepared by the first half of next year.
Mr Dave Morris, Scottish officer of the Ramblers' Association, said last night
that he was ``very alarmed'' by the announcement.
He added: ``Ian Lang, when he was Scottish Secretary last year, promised SNH
#120m over the next three years. That has already been reneged on by Michael
Forsyth.''
Mr Steve Sankey, head of policy at the RSPB, said he supported the emphasis
placed by the review on European directives, Natura 2000 and the Bio-diversity
Action Plan.
However, he expressed concern about the potential loss of national duties, such
as the designation of Sites of Special SScientific Interest.
The study group on SNH, comprising senior officials of the then Scottish Office
Environment Department and SNH, was set up last May. Its findings include the
following recommendations:
q SNH should be more selective in choosing issues on which it spends its
advisory effort.
q Ministers should have the option to review spending on environmental
education.
q None of SNH's activities identified in the report is considered to be wholly
unnecessary or inappropriate but some may be deemed to be of insufficient
priority at a time of constrained resources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>customs raid in Highlands</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897190</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Customs raid
in Highlands
TWO Customs and Excise raids in Inverness-shire have taken the total of goods
seized from bootleggers in Scotland to more than #150,000 in a Christmas
crackdown.
Several vehicles have also been confiscated in a purge on shoppers who travel
to Europe to buy their duty-free goods in bulk and sell them at a profit in
this country.
Fraud fine
A FORMER councillor who defrauded almost #2000 in expenses was yesterday fined
#200 at Aberdeen Sheriff Court. Stuart Burnett, 46, defrauded Grampian Regional
Council of the money while he represented the Summerfield ward in Aberdeen. Mr
Burnett, a Labour councillor, repaid the money to the local authority.
Driver hurt
MR Thomas Drever, 45, of Morgan Street, Dundee, is ``serious'' in hospital
following a crash near Luthrie, Fife, yesterday. Mr Drever was trapped in the
wreckage of his car for almost an hour before being cut free by firemen and
taken to Dundee Royal Infirmary.
#1m lure
AN office block costing #1m is to be built in Alness, Easter Ross, in an
attempt to attract business to the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fears for historic site if wind farm goes ahead</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897191</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of Scotland's top archeological scientists warned yesterday that a proposed
``green'' #12m wind farm could spell disaster for a historic site that has
aroused interest from experts all over the world.
Dr Brian Moffat has spent the past 10 years excavating a medieval hospital at
Soutra Aisle in the Borders and has guided more than 100,000 visitors round the
site. He says the tours, which help cover half his #250,000 a year costs, are
in danger of being drowned out by the noise from 30 huge propeller-driven
turbines on nearby Dun Law hill.
Tonight, Dr Moffat will be one of the speakers at a meeting in the village hall
of nearby Oxton, to debate the wind-farm project. Representatives of the
community council, the Hertfordshire-based wind-farm company Renewable Energy
Systems, the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds, and the Society for the
Preservation of Rural Scotland, are also expected to attend.
Opinions at the meeting are expected to be divided but community councillor
David Murray, 74, who is fiercely opposed to the project, said yesterday: ``The
wind farm will be on one of the most visible spots in southern Scotland. The 30
towers will straddle the main A68 road and be clearly seen from the Cheviots,
Edinburgh Castle, the Pentlands, and the Fife hills. It is a dreadful prospect.
``Our village is about three kilometres from the wind farm site and all the
feedback I am getting from people who live near these things is that you don't
discover the drawbacks until they are up and then it is too late.''
Renewable Energy Systems, a subsidiary of the giant Sir Robert McAlpine group,
has already put up six wind farms in England and Northern Ireland.
Dr Moffat says: ``Similar developments in northern England show that people
within five kilometres are subjected to a continual whirring noise. The
propeller blades alone are 44 metres in diameter.
``I am deeply worried that the noise would make it impossible for me to conduct
my tours properly and my project depends on the revenue.
``Soutra Aisle was a hospital between the twelfth and seventeenth centuries,
originally run by Augustinian monks for the sick and travellers up the main
east coast route. What we have discovered on the site has produced information
about the diseases and treatments of the past that is relevant to medicine
today. It has resulted in ground-breaking research in DNA profiling and
analytical chemistry and fourteenth century human DNA from Soutra is currently
being analysed by microbiologists at Portsmouth University.''
Work at Soutra is opening a wealth of information about long-forgotten cures.
One programme of waste analysis from the drains indicated that the monks were
using opium for treatments and it was presumed they were importing the drug.
Later, traces of a special strain of poppy - never previously thought to have
been grown so far north - were discovered in a nearby field and it was realised
that the opium had been produced at the hospital.
A spokesman for Renewable Energy Systems said yesterday: ``You obviously can't
hide the wind farm but it won't dominate the landscape. Power stations can be
just as obvious. We do not believe that the noise at Dr Moffat's site will be
significant. Visitors will be able to hear it but it will not drown his talks.
``We will be putting a case to the local community in the village hall on
Thursday night and hope to secure their support. We expect to submit a formal
planning application to Borders Regional Council early next month.''
</TEXT>
