<HEADLINE>Attack on HMSO sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor,  Our Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897192</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was accused yesterday of being driven by ideology when it
announced its intention of privatising Her Majesty's Stationery Office,
established 200 years ago to print parliamentary and Government papers.
Public Services Minister Roger Freeman said if both Houses of Parliament
approved he hoped the sale could be completed by next summer, lifting the
inevitable uncertainty which had affected the staff.
He said the market for HMSO's work was shrinking. Job losses were likely unless
new sales opportunities could be taken. A small residual body would stay in the
public sector and keep the HMSO title with responsibility for administering
Crown and possibly parliamentary copyright.
Mr Freeman promised Mr Martin O'Neill (Clackmannan - Lab.) that he would look
at ways of protecting employees' pension rights.
Mr Tam Dalyell (Linlithgow - Lab.) warned that under a privatised company there
was a danger of leaks of important documents like the Budget.
</TEXT>
