<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hospitals in cost-sharing talks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897193</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
TALKS between two hospital trusts about cost-sharing have caused speculation
about a merger. It could be the first large one of its type in Scotland.
Managements of Victoria Infirmary and Hairmyres Hospital, near East Kilbribe,
which is about to embark on a #50m rebuild paid for through the Private Finance
Initiative, have been discussing joint arrangements to make economies.
One union leader warned last night that the courtship could set the trend for
centralised hyper-hospitals driven by the commercial sector's drive to get the
maximum profit from Private Finance Initiatives.
Lothian Health is already under pressure to increase the capacity of the
PFI-backed replacement for Edinburgh Royal Infirmary, probably at the expense
of St John's Hospital in Livingston.
Mr Alistair Mack, director of medical services at the Victoria, yesterday
denied rumours, noted by a doctor in a letter to The Herald, that the staff
from the infirmary's accident and emergency department were to be moved to
Glasgow Royal Infirmary. He said the Victoria's department was now the busiest
in Glasgow and the most efficient in Scotland.
Mr Mack admitted that the trust had been in talks with the Hairmyres management
but insisted that the talks were at a basic level and that there were no
proposals.
On the possibility of a new joint hospital replacing both existing ones, he
said: ``It is difficult to say. Lanarkshire's hospital rebuilding plans are not
very clear. They still have a long way to go.''
Mr Jim Devine, senior organiser with Unison, expressed concern at the
possibility of a finance-driven restructuring being forced on the NHS so soon
after an organisation that had established the existing 47 trusts.
``My understanding is that, while they have not yet reached the stage of
marriage, the Victoria and Hairmyres are very much in courtship. How far behind
will the engagement be?
``The obvious avenue for this is the PFI initiative - a commercial backer might
see it as more attractive to replace the two with a new hospital somewhere
between the two existing sites.
``This goes beyond any expectation of hospital mergers within health board
areas. Here we have two trusts on either side of a health board boundary which
could become one. If you take the wider picture, you can see a line of five
hospitals - the Southern General, the Victoria, Hairmyres, Stonehouse, and Law
- which private operators might see commercial advantage in replacing with
two.''
``We would be very concerned if this were to become a model for the health
service of the future, driven by the profit motive.''
</TEXT>
