<DOCNO>GH951214-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP attacks increases in road fuel price</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897194</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SNP leader Alex Salmond has attacked the Government's increase in road fuel
duties over the past three years, describing it as a ``London levy'' on
motorists and the economy north of the Border.
His attack comes as two of Scotland's main bus operators confirm that fares are
being increased to help offset the increase in the price of diesel fuel
announced in the Budget.
Addressing a news conference in Aberdeen yesterday, Mr Salmond said Scotland's
sparse population and large number of rural communities - where petrol prices
were among the highest in the UK - had been hit hardest by Government increases
in road fuel taxes.
Mr Salmond said a Government decision to increase road fuel taxes in successive
Budgets by 3% and 5% in real terms since 1993 amounted to increases above the
rate of inflation on five separate occasions since.
He claimed the measure had cost drivers covering a Scottish average of 10,000
miles ayear an extra #150.
Mr Salmond said a lack of public transport meant drivers in rural areas of
Scotland covered 70% more miles than drivers in urban communities.
He added: ``What is needed to protect the Scottish environment is better public
transport - in both urban and rural areas - not the London levy, the only
purpose of which is to squeeze yet more Government revenue out of Scotland.''
Clydeside Buses, one of Scotland's biggest local bus operators, announced that
its fares would increase by an average of 4.5% from January 7 to help offset a
22% rise in its fuel bill.
Stagecoach, another of Scotland's main local bus operators, said fare rises of
2.1% announced earlier this week on services in the Highlands, Grampian, and
Tayside areas were also down to the Budget increases in diesel.
Lothian Region Transport, Strathclyde Buses, and Scottish CityLink, said they
shared the concern and disappointment of other bus operators at the increases.
</TEXT>
