<DOCNO>GH951214-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Regulator launches lottery inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897195</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE lottery regulator launched an inquiry yesterday into allegations by Richard
Branson that he was offered a bribe to drop his bid for the franchise.
Mr Peter Davis, director general of Oflot, said the inquiry would centre on Mr
Branson's comments on a Panorama programme on BBC1 that Mr Guy Snowden, an
executive with GTech, one of the shareholders of Camelot, the successful
bidder, had tried to offer the bribe.
Mr Davis said: ``I am appointing a senior and independent figure to conduct an
investigation into these allegations and report to me. It is my duty to ensure
that those involved in the operation of the national lottery are fit and proper
to do so.''
Mr Branson said: ``We would welcome a genuinely independent investigation into
the events that occurred and the allegations on the Panorama programme, as long
as we could be assured it was genuinely independent.''
A spokesman for GTech said: ``Mr Snowden and GTech welcome Peter Davis's call
for an independent inquiry. On Monday, Mr Snowden wrote to Mr Davis and
Virginia Bottomley requesting an urgent investigation of the matter and he has
promised his full co-operation.''
Mr Tim Holley, chief executive of Camelot Group plc, said: ``We welcome the
announcement by the Director-General of the Office of the National Lottery that
he is to launch an inquiry. We look forward to fully co-operating in the
investigation.''
Meanwhile, a poll has shown that three-quarters of those questioned want a
windfall tax on Camelot and the same number would like to see a non
profit-making organisation taking over.
A majority also want the money raised through the lottery to be handed out in a
different way, with a larger share for good causes such as education and the
NHS.
The confidential poll was carried out by Mori but leaked to the Daily Express.
The survey of 1800 people is part of the polling company's regular research,
which is then sold to commercial clients.
</TEXT>
