<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Directors `knew arms were being sent to Iran'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897196</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DIRECTORS of the company at the heart of the arms-to-Iran affair were well
aware of the true destination of the weapons they were shipping, a committee of
MPs was told yesterday.
The former chairman of BMARC's parent company, Mr Gerald James, said it was
``common knowledge'' among the directors, who included former Cabinet Minister
Jonathan Aitken, that they were supplying components for naval guns to the
Tehran regime.
Mr James was giving evidence to the Trade and Industry Select Committee which
is investigating how the firm sold components to Singapore, with Government
approval, when they were apparently destined for Iran - a breach of Government
guidelines.
Mr James told the committee he had learned of the true destination of the
weapons only after his firm Astra Holdings acquired BMARC from the Swiss arms
company Oerlikon in 1988.
He said he had been told at a board meeting by Major General Donald Isles, who
had stayed on the BMARC board after the takeover and who was in charge of the
Project Lisi contract to supply Singapore.
However, he said he had been assured by General Isles, a former weapons
director at the Ministry of Defence, that the contract had the approval of the
Ministry of Defence.
Mr James said Project Lisi was discussed at every BMARC board meeting, some of
which were attended by Mr Aitken, and that Mr Aitken should have known where
the components were really going.
``If he was sitting listening, he would know,'' he said.
He admitted there was no reference to Iran in the minutes of the meetings which
had been written in a ``circumspect'' manner.
Mr William McNaught, BMARC's former managing director, dismissed Mr James's
claims as ``a pack of lies''.
He told the committee he had never been informed that the weapons components
were for Iran - although he said the size of the contract made it clear that
they were for onward sale from Singapore.
Mr James, however, told the committee he had discovered ``covert operations''
were being run by people within BMARC and that the firm had a ``secret order
book''.
He claimed other firms had used BMARC premises to store equipment while
companies such as British Aerospace, Marconi, and Royal Ordnance had been using
BMARC headed notepaper.
``We had a range of people working within the company who were clearly working
with the intelligence and security services,'' he said.
</TEXT>
