<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seasonally adjusted figures a grim Christmas present for unemployed, claims TUC Mixed reaction to fall in jobless</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897197</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT in Scotland fell again last month, but yesterday political
reaction was sharply divided as it became clear that the month-by-month
reduction had slowed considerably.
The fall in the seasonally adjusted figure was 700, putting the number claiming
unemployment benefit in Scotland at 195,000, or 7.8% of the workforce. The UK
as a whole fared better, with the claimants' total dropping by 20,400 to
2,244,500 - the lowest figure since May 1991.
Although the Scottish total has recorded yet another fall, there was a rise in
the unadjusted figure - the actual number signing on with no weighting for
seasonal variations.
This prompted Mr Bill Speirs, deputy general secretary of the Scottish TUC, to
claim that the figures were a grim Christmas present to Scotland from the
Government.
``The marginal drop in the seasonally adjusted figures conceals the growing
problem of rising unemployment in those parts of the country where it is
already a major crisis,'' he said.
The union organisation argued that it showed the Secretary of State's decision
this week to cut the budget for job creation at Scottish Enterprise and
Highlands and Islands Enterprise was a disgrace.
Scottish National Party employment spokeswoman Anne McNair said it gave no
Christmas cheer to Scots, particularly the hundreds of workers at Yarrow's and
Motorola who are being made redundant this month.
Scottish Industry Minister George Kynoch stressed that unemployment had been on
a downward trend for almost three years, falling by 55,500 since December 1992,
and now below 200,000 for six consecutive months.
He drew attention to an export survey published last week which showed Scottish
exports at record levels, and added: ``This confirms, once again, that the
Government's economic policies are enabling Scottish business to achieve
significant success in world markets.''
However, Labour's Scottish employment spokesman, Mr John McFall, said it was
scandalous for the Government to try to present a rosy picture on employment
when the number of unemployed young people aged 16 and 17 had risen.
The employers' organisation, the CBI, was positive, with its assistant director
in Scotland, Mr Alan Mitchell, welcoming the fall and noting that Scotland's
unemployment level remained below the national average.
He added that the cut in interest rates, also announced yesterday, could only
represent good news for business and employment prospects in 1996.
Although any drop must be welcome, the drop for the last six months was under
1% for the first time in years. During the first four months of the year, the
six-monthly figure never fell less than 3%.
The overall figures mask large regional variations. The travel to work areas of
Aberdeen, Galashiels, and Skye and Wester Ross, all have unemployment rates of
under 4%.
However, Cumnock and Sanquhar - which comes - remains the highest at 15.7%,
followed by Sutherland at 13.8%.
Only South Tyneside fares worse in the men's job stakes with 22.9% unemployed.
In all, Scotland has 10 of the 40 worst blackspots, including Forres, Wick,
Sutherland, Alloa, Invergordan and Dingwall, Girvan, the Western Isles, Irvine,
and Dunoon nd Bute.
The disparity in Scotland between men and women continues to be marked, with
male unemployment 10.8%, and female unemployment 4.1%, giving an average of
7.8%.
Employment Minister Eric Forth said the drop was further evidence that
Britain's flexible and deregulated labour market, tight control on public
spending, and low taxes were delivering economic growth and jobs.
Meanwhile, the increase in average earnings in the year to October was 3.25%,
unchanged since July.
</TEXT>
