<DOCNO>GH951214-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A clear case of comeback kids</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Barclay McBain, Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph table not available in database</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897198</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Or not? Education correspondent Barclay McBain studies the new school
attendance figures
JOHN STREET Secondary, a Glasgow inner-city school serving areas of
deprivation, had the second highest rate of unauthorised absence - commonly
called truancy - when the 1993-4 attendance and absence figures were published
nearly a year ago.
When asked about the figures, headteacher Stewart McLachlan confidently
predicted that the school would make a massive improvement when the 1994-5
statistics were published.
This happened yesterday, and he was right. John Street's unauthorised rate has
fallen to 6%. Its authorised - or explained - absence increased from 15% to
20%. A similar thing has happened at Castlebrae Community High in Lothian,
whose catchment area is one of the most deprived in the region and which had
the highest unauthorised absence, 17%. That has fallen to 3%, while the
authorised proportion has risen from 12% to 21%.
What does it all mean, particularly for parents and school board members, at
whom the latest report is mainly aimed?
To begin with, there was no Scottish Office guidance about what constituted
authorised or unauthorised absence for 1993-4. According to headteacher Willaim
Crosbie, Castlebrae's exceptionally high unauthorised rate for that year was
partly due to the way in which it had dealt with unexplained absence.
It had treated any case on which it did not have documented evidence as
unauthorised absence, and this distinguished it from other schools.
But the explanation goes deeper. Mr Crosbie said yesterday: ``The most
important statistic of all is that our overall attendance has gone up by 5%.
This is a product of our school development plan, which sets out to create a
more positive ethos in the school.
``The children are gaining a greater belief in themselves and in what we can do
for them. I have always believed that turning attitudes round would take years
but now that it has taken hold it will continue.''
And at John Street yesterday Mr McLachlan told a similar story: ``We realised
that we had been playing a harder game. If there was no note from the parent we
automatically marked the pupil absent without permission. We did the same if we
had any doubts about the validity of an absence note.
``Now we have relaxed the system. Any contact from a parent is taken by us as
authorising the absence. Our actual attendance rate is only up by 1% but the
balance between authorised and unauthorised absence has clearly shifted.''
In January the Scottish Office issued guidelines for authorised and
unauthorised absence for the figures published yesterday. This year Linlathen
High, which serves deprived areas on the outskirts of Dundee, has paid the
price of applying rigorously high standards to what constitutes unexplained
absence by stacking up the highest unauthorised rate, 16% - compared with 0%
last year.
By strictly following up on unexplained absence, headteacher Paul Taylor - said
to be a caring and punctilious rector - appears to have bucked the general
trend in authorities of classifying as authorised as much absence as possible.
According to yesterday's figures, unauthorised absence across Scotland is 1%
and authorised 10% in the secondary sector.
Mr Taylor is off with flu and in his absence Neil Logue, a Tayside region
assistant director of education responsible for Dundee, said: ``We have to
treat statistics cautiously but in no sense would we be complacent about
absence. An overall absence rate of 21% is not something we can sit back and
say we are happy about.
``It will give us pause for thought. We must ensure that any injury that occurs
to a school that is already working hard against all forms of social
disadvantage is not left unsupported.''
</TEXT>
