<DOCNO>GH951214-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Kinks pull out of concert</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897200</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DISAPPOINTMENT has hit Edinburgh's huge five-day Hogmanay celebrations - the
largest festival of its kind in the world - as headliners the Kinks yesterday
withdrew from the event.
The pull-out came as it was revealed that a last-minute deal has had to be
struck to secure the event in its present form. The problems occurred because
the sponsorship target from big business for the capital's celebrations had
fallen #99,000 below the level expected.
Last night, Lothian Regional Council officials were putting a brave face on the
short-fall and agreed to chip in another #33,000 to the event's budget.
A similar sum is to be put in by Edinburgh District Council and by Lothian and
Edinburgh Enterprise Limited. The whole five-day event is expected to cost
around #590,000.
Meanwhile, Unique Events, organisers of the Hogmanay concert in Princes Street
Gardens, said the Kinks, whose hits have included Lola and Waterloo Sunset,
cancelled because their lead singer, Ray Davies, was stranded in Australia with
a perforated ear drum.
However, Ms Faith Liddell, of the company, said she was confident another big
name band would be lined up to take over from the Kinks.
Four thousand tickets for the event, which also includes Big Country, Edwyn
Collins, and the Scottish Fiddle Orchestra, have been sold.
</TEXT>
