<DOCNO>GH951214-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Results on knife curbs welcomed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897201</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S tough laws on carrying knives are leading to more prosecutions,
Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth said last night.
The Carrying of Knives (Scotland) Act, introduced as a Private Member's Bill by
Ayr Tory MP Phil Gallie, resulted in 561 successful prosecutions in 1993-94.
With very few exceptions, the Bill made it an offence to carry a knife or
sharply-pointed object in a public place and placed on the carrier of the knife
the burden of establishing that he had good reason for carrying it.
The issue has been highlighted by the fatal stabbing in London of headmaster
Philip Lawrence.
Of the 561 prosecutions in Scotland, 207 - or 37% - resulted in a custodial
sentence, of which 84 were between three and six months, and eight were in
excess of six months.
Mr Forsyth said he thought this suggested that the range of penalties the Act
made available to the courts to deal with ``this insidious crime'' was pitched
at the right level.
He added: ``The Bill became law at the end of May, 1993, towards the end of
Strathclyde Police's Operation Blade. These two intitatives together had a
considerable effect on reducing the levels of knife-related crime in the areas
where it was most prevalent at the time, namely Strathclyde and Glasgow.''
THE Commons was warned yesterday against a ``knee-jerk reaction'' to the fatal
stabbing of the London headmaster.
The caution came before a Tory backbench Bill for action in England and Wales
to crack down on knives, backed by the Government, was presented formally in
the Commons.
Liberal Democrat Paul Tyler said: ``We have got to be very careful that we
don't adopt a policy of reacting at such speed that we then do so in a way that
is defective.''
The Offensive Weapons Bill, sponsored by Lady Olga Maitland (Sutton and Cheam -
Con.) later gained its unopposed formal first reading among a range of other
backbench measures to be debated this session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
