<DOCNO>GH951214-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lecture bill likely to be #26,000</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897202</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR officials on Lothian Regional Council yesterday admitted to being more
than a little embarrassed over a late demand from agents acting for former
Russian president Mikhail Gorbachev for a #50,000 lecture fee.
Mr Gorbachev delivered the lecture in Edinburgh two years ago as one of a
series organised by the council. It has not been the council's policy to pay
any of the speakers.
A full council meeting in Edinburgh yesterday agreed to opt for an out-of-court
settlement likely to cost the council #26,000 rather than to continue disputing
the claim for payment by First Artist Corporation which arranged Mr Gorbachev's
UK tour.
During the meeting, Conservative councillors claimed there had been
incompetence by officials over the arrangements as there was no documentation
on the question of fees. However, they did not blame the current chief
executive, Mr Tom Aitchison, who was not in charge at the time.
Lothian convener Eric Milligan said the settlement recommended by regional
solicitor Gerry Welsh was the best course of action, although the matter left
``a sour taste'' in his mouth. He stressed that the Gorbachev lecture had been
different from the others in the series as it had involved dealing with an
intermediary over the arrangements.
In his report, Mr Welsh said the council's position had been weakened because
no communication had been sent to First Artist Corporation expressly denying
legal liability.
The region's Labour leader, Councillor Keith Geddes, said this was ``a moment
of some embarrassment for the council''. Lothian officials had acted in good
faith but had perhaps shown a touch of naivety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Student Loans Company now over its problems, MPs told</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897203</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE problems of the Glasgow-based Student Loans Company have been resolved, MPs
heard yesterday, following a disastrous start which saw thousands of students
unable to receive their loans and the sacking of its chief executive.
The Public Accounts Committee was told by Sir Tim Lankester, permanent
secretary at the Department of Education and Employment, that the company was
achieving its targets for cost reductions, and had overcome its initial
problems.
``I think the problems are largely behind it. There certainly were some
weaknesses in internal systems in the company in the early years. But I believe
that they have now been rectified,'' he said.
``No doubt that this project was poorly planned and poorly implemented. But it
was an operational matter for the company. When the company became aware of the
problem I believe they did take urgent action.
``But by that time in a way it was too late. The system had exploded and
required a tremendous effort to get it back on track.''
The committee was told how in 1994 the company had struggled to cope with
thousands of telephone calls as students applying for loans tried to obtain
information to help them complete their application forms. Earlier this year,
the company's chief executive, Mr Ron Harrison, was sacked.
The number of students receiving their loans on time was now running at 93%,
with only 7% of applicants experiencing difficulties.
Sir Tim told the committee the idea of student loans had become accepted. ``My
impression is that it has become acceptable. Students no longer regard it as an
evil that has been imposed upon them,'' he said.
He also disclosed that although the company was cutting back on issuing company
cars to new employees, a third of the 300 people who work for the company were
eligible for private health insurance.
q The maximum for student loans is to rise by 2.6% for students in Scotland,
the Scottish Education Minister, Mr Raymond Robertson, said last night.
The move is in line with the rates announced for students in England and Wales
last month.
Full-year students studying away from home will be allowed a maximum loan of
#1645 for 1996-97, compared with #1385 in 1995-96.
However, the main rate of grant for students living at home and away from home
is reduced accordingly, as grants are replaced by loans in line with Government
policy.
</TEXT>
