<DOCNO>GH951214-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Briton suspected of suicide mission</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>FOREIGN DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897205</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Briton suspected
of suicide mission
CAIRO: A Briton is among 56 suspected Muslim militants arrested in raids by
security forces across Egypt over the past week.
Akram Abdelaziz Mahmoud al-Sharif, described as a naturalised Briton who works
as a driver and is married to a British woman, is said to have been one of the
leaders of a suicide unit which had planned blasts in Egypt. Large quantities
of weapons and money, some transferred from London, were said to have been
seized.
BBC man killed
DUSHANBE: A BBC journalist has been shot dead in the former Soviet republic of
Tajikistan. The body of Mohydin Alempour, 50, who had worked for the BBC's
Persian language service for five years, was found on a university campus in
the capital Dushanbe with several bullet wounds in the chest.
Reeve goes home
NEW YORK: Superman actor Christopher Reeve went home with his wife and children
after six months' treatment at a rehabilitation centre. Reeve has been
paralysed since he was thrown by a horse in May.
Sex case raised
PARIS: The European Court of Human Rights is to review a case brought by three
British homosexuals given prison sentences for causing one another bodily harm
during sado-masochistic orgies. The European Commission of Human Rights has
found that their right to privacy had not been interfered with and referred the
case to the court, which generally follows the Commission's rulings.
Kabul in crisis
KABUL: More than 500,000 people in the war-ravaged Afghan capital Kabul face
disaster this winter unless a blockade denying vital fuel and food is lifted,
the UN has warned. Its co-ordinator for humanitarian affairs, Alex Thier, said
most Afghans could not afford the supplies they need to survive.
New life found
COPENHAGEN: Danish scientists claim to have found an entirely new life form
living on the lips of a Norwegian lobster. Symbion pandora, which looks like an
animated cold sore on the mouth of its host, is composed mostly of a funnel
with a round mouth. However it is not only a species but forms an entirely new
phylum, or level of biological classification.
Four get life
GREEN BAY: Four Wisconsin men have been sentenced to life in prison for
throwing a fellow worker to his death in the pulp pit of a paper mill because
he told police one of them planned to steal a #1.50 extension cord. Two others
have yet to be sentenced.
Police chief jailed
RIGA: The 87-year-old former head of the security police in Latvia, Alfons
Noviks, will spend the rest of his life in jail after being convicted of
genocide. Noviks led the NKVD security police in 1940-53, when thousands of
people were jailed, deported, and killed in Stalinist purges.
Code for Santa
TORONTO: Canada has given Santa Claus his own postcode for Christmas. More than
one million letters sent each year to Santa at the North Pole, Canada, will be
sped on their way if they carry the code H0H 0H0.
</TEXT>
