<HEADLINE>Labour leaders postpone decision over councillors facing accusations of nepotism Judgment on Monklands delayed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political CorrespondentFRANCES HORSBURGH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897206</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR has postponed until the new year the day of reckoning for Monklands
councillors facing accusations that nepotism brought the party into disrepute.
It had been expected that the results of an internal party investigation into
the saga would be placed before the National Executive Committee in London
yesterday.
Instead, the committee was told that the investigators, headed by party
chairwoman Diana Jeuda, still had been in Lanarkshire right up until Tuesday
and the report had not been yet been written.
A statement issued by both the London and Scottish headquarters of the Labour
Party said simply: ``The chair of the party reported that the inquiry into
Monklands was only completed last night.
``It is a serious situation and the report will require careful and detailed
consideration. As a written report is not yet ready it was not possible to
consider the result of the inquiry in any detail or for today's NEC to reach
any conclusions or recommendations. A full report will, therefore, come before
January's NEC, where decisions will be made.''
However, Labour sources confirmed yesterday that the final report will include
recommendations of disciplinary action against some of those involved. ``It is
inevitable that the report will recommend disciplinary action in some cases.
The case was complicated, it was serious and it requires, where appropriate,
some tough action,'' a source said.
Although the report will be an internal Labour document, party officials say it
is unavoidable that it will be made public. ``It will remain a confidential
document until the NEC considers it. After that, it will be impossible to keep
such a thing confidential.''
The delay pushes the internal party report back nearer to the expected
publication of an official Scottish Office inquiry into the affair, conducted
by Mr William Nimmo-Smith, QC.
This led to accusations by political opponents yesterday that Labour was
putting off the inevitable row. ``The continuing uncertainty will be unwelcome
not only to Labour Party activists, but also to the wider electorate in the
Monklands area,'' said Scottish Tory deputy chairwoman Annabel Goldie.
``There will be surprise that after all this time the Labour Party has not been
able to deal definitively with the situation.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said: ``It looks to me as if Labour are simply
postponing the evil day when they have to face the fall-out from what their
councillors have been doing over a prolonged period. Sooner or later, they are
going to have to come clean.''
However, Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said there was nothing
sinister about the fact that the written report had not yet been concluded, and
he said their own inquiry and the official investigation by Mr Nimmo-Smith
meant the matter was effectively sub judice.
He added: ``Opponents will make accusations against us whether we say anything
or not, but the truth is there are occasions when even politicans should remain
silent.''
SCOTTISH local authority leaders look set to back proposals to give the Local
Government Ombudsman sweeping new powers to investigate the conduct of
councillors which were put forward in a report last week, (writes Frances
Horsburgh).
A full meeting of the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities in Edinburgh
tomorrow will finalise its response to the options put forward by the joint
Scottish Office/Cosla task force of officials.
It supports the Ombudsman being allowed to pursue complaints involving the
actions of individual councillors and being able to investigate
maladministration relating to the appointment of officials.
Cosla also favours an extension of the Ombudsman's powers to cover personnel
and contractual matters.
The task force was set up at the suggestion of the Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth following the allegations over Monklands and ``jobs for the boys''
claims over the the new North Lanarkshire Council.
</TEXT>
