<HEADLINE>It's the pits for Murray Walker</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897207</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ITV is to screen Formula 1 motor races from 1997 in a deal which has stunned
the BBC.
The agreement, reported to have cost the independent companies up to #70m, is
for five years beginning from the Brazilian Grand Prix in March 1997.
ITV says it also includes screening the FIA International Touring Car
Championship and the Formula 3000 International Championship.
The BBC admitted the news was a surprise. Commentator Murray Walker heard the
announcement on his car radio as he drove home from a lunchtime speaking
engagement.
Having lost the FA Cup Final to ITV from May 1998, the BBC has now had to
concede another prime sporting spot.
In a five-year deal, ITV each season will broadcast all 16 Grand Prix races
live on Sundays together with a highlights programme.
A spokeswoman for BBC Sport said: ``We are extremely shocked. We had no notice
of a deal and were not given an opportunity to put in a bid.
``Our distress is further deepened by the fact that Grand Prix motor racing was
nurtured and developed by BBC TV.''
The news could spell the end of the line for the voice of motorsport, Murray
Walker, who has commentated distinctively on the sport since 1949.
The 72-year-old former advertising executive has been the TV frontman since
Grand Prix became a regular feature in 1977.
He said last night: ``The news was a shock not only to me but to everybody on
the BBC Grand Prix team. I knew nothing about it although I knew the contract
would be coming up for renewal.''
An ITV spokeswoman said: ``We have not even decided who will prepare the
programmes for us, let alone who will present them. The contract has only just
been signed.''
The ITV deal was negotiated with Mr Bernie Ecclestone, president of the Formula
One Constructors' Association. The former boss at Brabham is one of the most
important men in motor racing and negotiates deals around  the world.
</TEXT>
