<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Musician admits lover said he was leaving her</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897208</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MUSICIAN yesterday confirmed that her 62-year-old lover told her their sex
session in the back of his car on the night he died was to be their last,
because he was leaving her.
But Mrs Pollyanna Peate denied having a row with Mr Brian Phillips or attacking
him, insisting: ``He died having sex. I'm sorry, but that's how it happened.
I've got nothing to admit.''
Chester Crown Court has heard that, over a period of 10 years, the couple had
regularly had sex in a lovers' lane after rehearsals with Frodsham Silver Band
in an affair they hid from their marital partners but which was ``an open
secret'' among their fellow musicians.
Mrs Peate, 34, of Runcorn, Cheshire, a euphonium player, denies the
manslaughter of Mr Phillips, a bass trombonist, on the night of November 15,
1994.
The prosecution says she attacked him, striking him at least four times after
he tried to end their affair, and that Mr Phillips, who had suffered a coronary
in 1972, died of a heart attack as a result.
Mrs Peate, a mother-of-two, confirmed yesterday that Mr Phillips had told her
in the car that it was to be the last time they would have sex together.
But, under cross-examination from Mr Mervyn Hughes, QC, prosecuting, she added:
``He was always saying silly little things. It came to the point where I didn't
take much notice.''
Mr Hughes: It was an important announcement that you became very upset about.
Mrs Peate: No.
You sat up and asked him what he meant. After 10 years he was bringing the
relationship to an end. - No.
He was throwing you over. - Nothing like that happened at all.
You lost control and became hysterical. - No.
You began to hit him around the head. - Nothing like that happened. He died
having sex with me. I wouldn't hit him.
She agreed that when Mr Phillips died she went home and pretended nothing had
happened, chatting with her 12-year-old daughter.
Mr Hughes: During the course of the night you gave not one moment's thought to
Brian Phillips or indeed to Mrs Phillips?
Mrs Peate: I was thinking of him. I was a bit upset and trying to keep myself
calm.
She said she had been frightened and was trying to cover her tracks.
Earlier, Mrs Peate told the court of her attempts to revive Mr Phillips in the
tight confines of the car.
``We were making love,'' she said. ``He collapsed. He just fell on top of me. I
said something like `Brian, what's the matter?' ''
She said he did not respond and she hit his back while she was underneath him.
She eventually managed to struggle from under him and turned his head sideways,
still calling his name.
``I was patting his face with my fingers but I got no response. I pressed twice
on his back and the second time he took one deep breath and he seemed to be
breathing again.''
She said she managed after several attempts to turn him on to his back, but
when she put an ear to his chest could not hear any breathing.
``I pressed on his chest to see if I could get any response but I couldn't get
any. I breathed into his mouth. His chest rose but I couldn't get anything. I
had no first aid training.
``I was a bit upset by then. I was cradling him, holding his hand and crying.''
She continued: ``I couldn't leave him without his trousers on. I had to make
him respectable. I found his trousers and got them on him eventually, with
difficulty.
``I made sure he was decent, and made sure I was thinking straight and my
emotions were intact. I made sure I was decent, put my dress on, made sure all
the car windows were wound up, got my instrument, and went.''
The jury is expected to retire today.
</TEXT>
