<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Phone plant cuts `no shock'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897212</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE loss of 550 jobs at Motorola's mobile-phone plant in West Lothian has come
as no surprise to those connected to the electronics industry.
The industry is notorious for hiring temporary staff - on contracts as short as
one week. Its use of employment agencies to find such recruits, and even pay
their wages, is also rife.
Motorola was adamant yesterday that the axe was not wielded at Easter Inch,
near Bathgate, because of a slump.
Alarm bells still sounded because the axe's fall coincided with a quarterly
survey by employers' federation Scottish Engineering which, for the first time
in five years, showed a fall in orders in the electronic sector.
It found 36% of electronics firms had registered a fall in orders, and recorded
a 16% dip in confidence.
The results were contradicted by numerous parties, including the Scottish
Electronics' Forum, which represents major firms, and Scottish Industry
Minister George Kynoch.
Mr Stewart Dunlop, a research fellow at Strathclyde University's influential
Fraser of Allander Institute, put the job losses and survey in perspective.
He saw no reason for Motorola's cuts other than the seasonal nature of its
business, with production concentrated in the lead-up to Christmas. He was
adamant the electronics' sector was continuing to grow.
Scottish Electronics' Forum spokesman Sam McEwan said Motorola's losses were
not a shock and added that the survey contradicted what the industry was saying
- that ``they have never been busier''.
Scottish Engineering chief executive Howard Jordan said seasonal trends
appeared to be dictating the fall in orders for the electronics sector,
traditionally the strongest and most consistent in the engineering industry
since 1990.
Ironically, Motorola, a member of the federation, did not return the
questionnaire for the quarter to December.
A spokesman said yesterday that a large number of weekly-contracted staff had
been taken on to deal with Christmas demand, with cellular phones one of this
year's top-selling gifts.
He added: ``Now we have built up stock, we are stopping the contractors' staff.
They knew they were on a short-term contract up to Christmas and none of our
staff of over 2000 is concerned.''
Melville Craig Selection, involved in temporary staff recruiting, declined to
comment.
Industry Minister George Kynoch said: ``The survey is at odds with our own
close contact with firms in the sector.''
Jobs continued to be created ``at a very high rate'' and he pointed out to
three inward investment announcements in the last month alone which will create
4000 jobs.
A Scottish Enterprise spokesman said Motorola had more than 2000 permanent
employees and was ``well positioned'' to meet expansion forecasts over the next
five years.
q.THE battle for the title of Scotland's other national drink was effectively
settled yesterday when the maker of the main rival to Irn-Bru went into
receivership.
The efforts of Rivets Iron Brew, made in Dundee by Meri-mate, to win business
from A.G Barr, the Glasgow-based soft drinks company which makes Irn-Bru, ended
abruptly yesterday, putting 80 jobs in jeopardy.
q.ONE hundred people at Polaroid UK's camera production plant at Vale of Leven
Industrial estate in Dumbarton are to lose their jobs before Christmas.
</TEXT>
