<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How this little piggy romps home</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>William Russell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>review</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897213</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS little pig went to market, this little pig stayed at home, this little pig
- well he was an orphan called Babe who believed his role in life was to be a
sheepdog, or more accurately a sheep pig, and he is my tip for the winner in
the Christmas movie box office stakes.
Based on Dick King-Smith's The Sheep Pig, Babe is an enchanting tale about an
orphaned talking piglet who thinks he is a sheepdog. When Babe's collie foster
mother, Fly, who has taught him the ways of the dog, is incapacitated on the
day of the big sheepdog trials guess who comes to the rescue of kindly Farmer
Hoggett? Babe, of course.
Having gone expecting little, because talking animals can be dire, as anybody
who remembers Francis the talking mule knows, it proved a case of leaving the
cinema crying ``Oui, oui oui'' all the way home. Adults will get as much
pleasure as children from this funny, stylish, inventive film written and
produced by George Miller, who gave the world the Mad Max movies, which just
goes to show how infinite is the variety of man.
Made in Australia, and directed by Chris Noonan, the film mixes real animals -
some 22 piglets were needed to play Babe because piglets grow up so quickly -
with animatronic birds and beasts created by Jim Henson's Creature Workshop. If
anybody can tell when the fake takes over from the real thing they are a better
man than I, Gunga Din. The only thing that jars is the animals' voices, which
tend to be an awkward mid-Atlantic mix designed, I suspect, for that vital
American market made up of people who cannot understand plain English. Babe,
for instance, spoken by Christine Cavanagh, is pure American bratpacker,
whereas Miriam Margolyes's Fly is more Mummerset. This bizarre linguistic mix
could have been a serious flaw, but, as one gets used to it, a never-never land
in which the fantasy thrives is created and in the end it is only slightly
irritating.
Not that Babe lives in dreamland. His world is a harsh one in which little pigs
lose their mothers in the natural course of events when they are turned into
sausages or a nice pot roast. It is a fate the spunky Babe, who is forever
getting into scrapes, will face in time, except he is lucky and escapes the
abattoir.
The animals, ranging from a headstrong gander called Ferdinand to a motherly
sheep called Maa, who teaches Babe manners - if you want to get a sheep to do
something, ask politely - and a jealous collie called Rex who objects to Babe
upsetting the natural order of things are nicely characterised. Most delightful
of all, is the trio of singing field mice, who perform in the margins of the
movie, warbling away like bucolic Andrews Sisters.
Kenneth Branagh's In the Bleak Midwinter is a diverting story of actors at work
and play which he has both written and directed. Maybe the characters are
two-dimensional, maybe they are cliches, but then actors are not as other folk
- without a role to play, somebody else's words to speak, they are often
insubstantial creatures - and Branagh has assembled his mixture of dreadful old
theatrical jokes and biting insights into what it is like to put on a show with
great skill.
Shot in black and white, and packed with some ripe pieces of character acting,
it is a blatant homage to the world of Ealing, but why not? There are worse
things to do than that.
Michael Moloney, in sparkling manic form, is an out-of-work actor whose sister
wants him to help save a local church in a village called Hope from developers
by staging a Christmas show in it to raise funds. With a little help from his
agent (Joan Collins), he assembles a cast of assorted thespians who agree, on a
profit-sharing, if there are any, basis to do Hamlet. We see the auditions, the
rehearsals and the performance when that magic moment occurs and these oddballs
become the characters in the play.
Richard Briers, as an elderly repertory actor, whose life has been one long
round of Agatha Christie and French Window plays, is hilarious as he seizes his
first chance to do a Shakespeare. He gets to play Claudius opposite - this
being an ``experimental production'' - a Gertrude played to the hilt by John
Sessions, a camp pantomime dame, ``Own tits, will travel''. The rest of the
performances are admirable, except for Jennifer Saunders whose Hollywood
producer is so dreadful she should be tarred, feathered and ridden out of town
on a rail. In the Christmas stakes this is a good one for grown-ups.
There is no denying that Three Wishes, directed by Martha Coolidge, has its
heart in the right place and is a seasonable offering. Set in a small American
town in 1955, it tells how Korean war widow Jeanne (Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio) is having problems rearing her two small sons, Tom (Joseph
Mazzello) 11 years old, lousy at baseball and discontented, and Gunny (Seth
Mumy), five years old, cute and suffering from cancer. One day out in the car,
avoiding a straying dog, she knocks down a vagrant (Patrick Swayze) and, full
of remorse, invites him to stay until his injured leg gets better.
We are in the feel-good world of Frank Capra, although Capra would have got
things moving a little faster than Ms Coolidge, whose touch is distinctly
leaden. Since it is Capraland, when Swayze turns out to be far from what he
seems, it is no surprise - angels come in many guises. The moral is be happy
with what you have. Mastrantonio is charming, the boys are believable, and
Swayze is watchable as the man from yonder, but one does wish occasionally one
were somewhere else.
Not, however, at The Tie that Binds, in which childless Moira Kelly and Vincent
Spano adopt mysterious, maladjusted, abandoned six-year-old Janie whose real
parents, Daryl Hannah and Keith Carradine are homicidal hippy maniacs. Having
accidentally lost their darling daughter they set about recovering her by
slaughtering everyone in sight. Nauseatingly violent, carelessly scripted this
dismal directorial debut for screenwriter Wesley (Wolf, Arachnaphobia and Cape
Fear) Strick is one to miss at any season.
It would not be Christmas without a cartoon fairy story, and there being no
Disney offering, Richard Rich's The Swan Princess, a garish, mildly amusing
variation on Swan Lake, will have to do.
But the dreadful, overly familiar songs by David Zippel and Lex de Azevedo made
me think there might be something to be said for Andrew Lloyd Webber.
Seekers after fairy tale magic, although not the variety for children, will
find it in abundance in Jean Cocteau's 50-year-old La Belle et La Bete. The
newly-restored negative, despite a couple of worrying jump cuts where
presumably deterioration had gone too far, presents his spellbinding tale about
the beast in man in as perfect a state as it is ever going to be. A masterpiece.
William Russell discovers that ham acting from an unexpected quarter could
become the boxoffice sizzler of the season
</TEXT>
