<HEADLINE>Romanian plane crashes killing 49</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897214</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Verona
UP TO 49 people on board a Romanian aircraft were killed tonight when an engine
caught fire shortly after take-off from Verona in northern Italy.
``One engine caught fire. It was seen from the tower,'' said marketing director
Dorin Dainu of the Romanian company Banat Air in Bucharest.
The number of people on board was in doubt as Banat officials gave crew numbers
varying from five to eight.
A local government official in Verona told Italian television: ``It doesn't
seem there are any survivors. It's a case now of identifying the remains.''
Police and fire brigade officials said the plane, a Russian-built Antonov 24,
had been on a regular thrice-weekly charter run to Bucharest from Verona's
Villafranca airport.
A fire brigade spokesman said the plane plunged to the ground about 900yd
beyond the airport and crashed in a vineyard near the village of Caluri.
He added that at least 31 of the passengers were believed to have been Italian
and the rest from former Yugoslavia and the Netherlands. The crew was Romanian,
said a regional official.
A fierce blaze, fuelled by the plane's full tanks, reduced it to blackened
wreckage spread across several hundreds of yards of snow-covered fields. The
largest piece that could be seen was the tail.
A row of coffins covered by plastic sheeting was laid out nearby. Hundreds of
onlookers crowded the narrow, muddy roads near the site and police struggled to
keep them back.-Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
