<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE Political Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897215</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Continued from Page 1
attention from the good news of a quarter point cut in the base rate to 6.5%.
Mr Clarke's move, backed by Bank of England Governor Eddie George at their
monthly meeting, had been widely expected after his cautious Budget failed to
deliver the stimulus which City analysts said was needed to boost slowing
economic growth.
The size of the cut disappointed business leaders and left them asking for more
but it prompted a reduction in home loan rates, which came down by the same
amount.
They had already been trimmed two weeks ago in anticipation of the base rate
cut and no further decrease was expected by industry experts.
The Halifax, Britain's biggest lender, set the ball rolling by announcing that
its basic home loan rate was being cut to 7.49% from 7.74% - its lowest level
since 1966.
Abbey National, the second biggest lender, and Nationwide, the second biggest
society, were among those that followed suit.
Presenting a united front at a news conference at the Treasury, Mr Clarke said
both he and the Governor, who were at odds over rates during the summer when Mr
George unsuccessfully argued for them to be raised, had both gone into the
meeting with a 0.25% cut in mind.
They said it was a genuine move towards a more gradualist approach to interest
rate changes in a new low inflation environment rather than the sort of messy
compromise that was behind the last 0.25% move in February 1994.
At that time, Mr Clarke had wanted to cut rates by 0.5% and Mr George wanted
them left on hold.
Mr George said: ``I am very happy that we were in a situation to advise that we
thought a quarter point was a sensible, prudent move.
``I am delighted.......that we have been able to move to a situation where we
will, I hope, be able to move in smaller steps in the future because I think
that's a very big further phase in the stabilisation of the economy.''
Opposition politicians attacked Mr Clarke's base rate move as an admission of
failure.
Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown said rates were being cut because the economy
was weak not strong.
``With business investment stagnant after three years of recovery, this cut can
only strengthen the economy if it is combined with the measures Labour has
proposed to increase long-term investment in industry, skills, and
infrastructure,'' said Mr Brown.
Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman Malcolm Bruce said: ``The cut in interest
rates is an acknowledgement of how slowly the economy is now growing - probably
a mere 1% annually at present, hardly a tribute to Government economic policy.''
CARELESS remarks by Chancellor Kenneth Clarke to a Commons committee yesterday
wrecked the Government's ``triple whammy'' of good news, lower interest rates,
falling unemployment, and rising High Street sales.
He claimed the poorest 10% of the nation have ``very good accountants.''
Mr Clarke later tried to rescue this situation on BBC TV claiming that his
remarks to the Treasury Select Committee on the effects of his Budget had been
taken out of context and the statistics did not validate the concept that the
poorest 10% are less well off.
But today the Chancellor's colleagues are left with another political mess when
they might have hoped that the economic figures yesterday indicated that people
are going to feel better off next year.
Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown was quick to exploit the situation. ``Only the
top 10% of earners in this country have very good accountants. All the Tory tax
changes have benefited those at the top while the middle and lower income
Britain has suffered.''
The Chancellor told the committee that the statistics about the bottom 10% of
the nation ``drive me up the wall. They are rather an unrealistic guide. The
statistics don't work for this bottom 10%.
``If you look at their purchasing, their purchasing has soared. Some of these
people you get in the bottom 10% are people who declare they have no income,
but they actually people with very good accountants.''
He went on to point out that the less well off drink more and smoke more than
the average of the population. ``Tobacco tax features higher in the budgets of
the poorest 10%,'' he said, ``they just smoke a lot.''
The Chancellor's remarks to the Treasury Select Committee caused anguish among
the beleaguered Tory back benchers who, some of whom said last night that the
quarter per cent cut in the basic cost of borrowing is too timid.
Later on in BBC Newsnight, Mr Clarke insisted that he has produced all the
economic indicators to provide for a stable steady recovery which will feed
through to voters' spending power in the new year. ``I have reduced tax and
spending and set Government borrowing on a downward course. We are producing a
stable economic recovery.''
He insisted that his growth forecast for next year will be about 2#f%. ``It is
miles above 2% already. British unemployment is now down to 8% and interest
rates are falling to the lowest level for several years.''
