<HEADLINE>Forsyth  faces  propaganda claims</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897218</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rocketing publicity budget at the Scottish Office since Mr Michael Forsyth
took over as Secretary of State is to be questioned in the Commons. Opponents
claim civil servants have been forced into political roles.
The Scottish Office last night denied that media monitoring activities,
previously carried out by Conservative Central Office, had been off-loaded on
to the taxpayer, but it accepted that a swifter and more extensive service in
this area was being market-tested using a private sector company.
Mr Forsyth has taken on two full-time political advisers, journalist Gerald
Warner and the former media head of the Scottish Conservatives, Ms Jacqui Low,
on full salaries. Both are experienced professionals.
This contrasts, say critics, with the previous practice of appointing younger
staff prepared to take the job on as a foot on the ladder of political
ambition. Mr Forsyth has cranked up the level of activity since taking office
to the point where an outside company is now carrying out media monitoring on
behalf of the Scottish Office.
The SNP leader, Mr Alex Salmond, is tabling a series of Commons questions
about
what he sees as ``propaganda at the taxpayers' expense'', raising the whole
issue of the way in which Mr Forsyth has created a ``Ministry of Propaganda''
at St Andrew's House.
However, Ms Liz Drummond, head of the information directorate at St Andrew's
House, said last night: ``When people criticise the alleged politicisation of
the information directorate of the
Continued on Page 2Continued from Page 1
Scottish Office, they are not in fact criticising Ministers.
``They are criticising the integrity and professionalism of the civil servants
involved. I have been a government information officer for over 25 years and I
have served both Tory and Labour Ministers - the last Labour Minister being
the
late John Smith at the Department of Trade. I have tried to serve them all
while maintaining true political neutrality.''
Mr Salmond is tabling questions in the House asking about Scottish Office
media
monitoring and how long these arrangements have been in place. He is also
asking about the awarding of any outside contracts, their duration, and their
value.
Mr Michael Russell, SNP chief executive, said last night: ``The issue is one
of
Government interference. It is quite clear that every statement from the
Scottish Office has to be stamped with a health and credibility warning
because
civil servants are now being subjected to political interference. Michael
Forsyth is politicising government in Scotland in an unprecedented way and
further endangering Scottish democracy.''
The issue has already been raised by the Shadow Scottish Secretary, Mr George
Robertson, who questioned the outlay on political advisers but was told this
brought the staffing ``up to complement''.
At Monday's meeting of the Scottish Grand Committee, Mr Forsyth then rebuffed
critics by pointing out the staffing of the leader of the Opposition's office
from public funds.
</TEXT>
