<HEADLINE>Radiating warmth in water of life</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897219</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHISKY purists who cringe at the thought of a dash of fizzy drink in their dram
are in for a shock - Japanese scientists say 2000 joules of radiation, a dose
strong enough to kill 250 people, can make bad whisky taste good.
Perhaps envious of the quality of Scotland's Water of Life, Japanese scientists
have been conducting research to make cheap whisky and bad wine taste better.
Not content with a drop of water, they turned to gamma rays.
Mr Hiroshi Watanabe, joint head of research at the Japan Atomic Power Company's
research facilities in Takasaki, said: ``With whisky, what the radioactivity
does is promote the blending process and that takes away any aftertaste.''
</TEXT>
