<HEADLINE>Angry mob torches shops and cars after protest over death of man in police custody Looting as riot erupts in Brixton</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RAMPAGING mob looted shops and started a number of fires last night after a
protest about the death of a black man escalated into a riot on the streets of
Brixton, south London.
Shops and cars were torched as a gang of about 100 black and white youths
stormed along Brixton Road, pulling clothes and electrical goods from the
shattered windows of shops.
About 50 police officers in riot gear formed a line across the road to stifle
pockets of trouble and prevent anyone entering the area - the scene of massive
rioting in 1981.
One report said two shots were fired as the centre of the demonstration moved
into the area of the Ritzy cinema and a police motor cyclist was said to have
been pulled from his machine by a crowd of at least 10 rioters.
As a police helicopter hovered amid a pall of black smoke that hung over the
streets, other officers sealed off a two-mile area around the centre of Brixton
and both Brixton and Stockwell tube stations were closed.
At one point, police charged a group of around 10 people who were throwing
missiles through the window of the Body Shop. One youth was pulled to the
ground and another was led away with his hands in the air.
On the other side of the street, a group of black youths shouted ``Killers,
killers'' at the police.
The man whose death sparked the riot was Wayne Douglas, 26, who was arrested
last week, suspected of aggravated burglary.
He was said to have broken into a flat in Brixton, threatened the family inside
with a knife, stolen bread and then made off. He was chased into a nearby
children's playground where, after a struggle, he was arrested, sources said.
The Police Complaints Authority said Douglas was taken to Brixton police
station where he suffered a fatal collapse. A post-mortem examination revealed
he had been suffering from heart disease.
A spokesman for the authority said: ``Tests are still continuing.
``The police contacted the PCC immediately and an investigation was launched
under the control of Edward Wignall, a member of the authority. Inquiries are
being conducted by Detective Superintendent Paul O'Nion and an appeal for
witnesses has been launched.''
As the rioting took place, a group of around 50 youths armed with baseball bats
arrived in Ferndale Road, where no police were present, and smashed the windows
of an Adidas sports shop.
They ripped metal barriers from the windows and smashed their way into the
store, grabbing armloads of expensive trainers, sweatshirts and sports gear.
The looting went on for around 15 minutes as frenzied youths made repeated
raids on the shop, running off with goods to a house nearby.
Two women passers-by were mugged and one was wrestled to the ground in the
frenzy which lasted about 15 minutes.
A squad of riot police arrived just as the last looters left the scene and
grabbed one white youth.
Police grabbed the youth as he left the shop with a box of trainers under his
arm.
Five officers pulled him to the ground and beat him with batons. He was
handcuffed and led away.
A police spokeswoman later said three police officers had been injured during
the scuffles and taken to hospital.
One, understood to be the motor cycle rider, has a broken shoulder, she said.
She said seven civilian casualties had been reported so far, and police were
still dealing with sporadic pockets of trouble in the area around Brixton town
centre.
She said there had been unconfirmed reports of petrol bombs being thrown and
gunshots being fired.
Asked about the presence of police in riot gear from the beginning of the
demonstration, she said: ``Officers were wearing protective clothing because we
had reports of missiles being thrown.''
She could not say how exactly the trouble flared, but added: ``We gave them
every opportunity to move off peacefully but they hadn't done so.''
One eye witness said he saw the officer pulled from his motor cycle after
hearing a group of youths saying ``let's get him''.
``There were about 10 or 15 of them and he was stranded on his own after the
units pulled out,'' said the witness, who asked not to be named.
The blackened motor cycle was later towed away by an armoured police vehicle.
By midnight, with dozens of cars ablaze and several hundred riot police
flooding into the area, the violence had spread from the initial flashpoint on
Brixton Road.
Pockets of trouble flared in numerous different streets with youths attempting
to smash shop windows and set fire to more cars and business premises.
The Scotland Yard spokesman said: ``It does not seem to be worsening at the
moment although there are still a lot of people on the streets.''
</TEXT>
