<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rowallan interdict move</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE former wife of the fourth Lord Rowallan has been granted interim interdict
preventing her former husband from molesting her. The civil case follows an
incident at an equestrian centre in November after which Lord Rowallan was
charged with assault and a report submitted to the procurator-fiscal.
Legal advisers for Lord Rowallan are preparing to defend the action and Glasgow
solicitor Paul Burns said: ``My client denies all the allegations made in the
initial writ and we will be defending the action with all vigour.''
He added: ``It is quite normal procedure for a sheriff to grant interim
interdict in cases like this without hearing all the evidence and submissions
and I would stress that no inference should be drawn from it.''
The alleged assault took place at Muirmill Equestrian Centre, where Lord
Rowallan and his present wife were watching her 19-year-old daughter Sophie
participate in a showjumping event. His former wife Sandrew Philomena Corbett,
who lives in the village, also was at the event.
Sophie was badly injured when she was thrown from a horse which subsequently
fell back and crushed her. She sustained fractures to her hips and legs.
In the initial writ lodged at Ayr Sheriff Court, it is alleged that Lord
Rowallan struck Mrs Corbett on the head and knocked her unconscious.
The writ states: ``At 5.30pm on November 12, the pursuer (Mrs Corbett) was
standing outside the arena area speaking to some friends.
``The defender (Lord Rowallan) walked to the pursuer and struck the pursuer on
the back of the head. The pursuer was knocked unconscious and fell to the
ground.''
</TEXT>
