<HEADLINE>Savary's savouries ease the overnight to Euston</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRAVELLERS on the sleeper from the Highlands to London were treated to a bite
to eat yesterday by millionaire Peter de Savary.
The flamboyant owner of the Carnegie Club in Sutherland boarded the train and
produced a banquet on fine china from an elegant Edwardian wicker    hamper.
Mr de Savary, his personal assistant, Ms Alyson Thompson, and several other
hungry passengers on the 8.30pm overnight train from Inverness to Euston were
served with Scottish smoked salmon, pate, dips, cheese, and biscuits, all
washed down with champagne.
It was the second time the former America's Cup yachtsman had found himself in
charge of the catering on the sleeper.
Last month, British Rail staff refused to serve food on the #95 service because
the head porter had taken ill. Mr de Savary sneaked into the closed buffet car
and dished out snacks and drinks, leaving cash in the till to meet the bill.
At that time, ScotRail described him as ``impatient'' and said he was ``out of
order''.
Yesterday, he said: ``After all the trouble on the last occasion I decided to
be safe and bring along a little snack for myself and anyone else who wanted to
join me.
``Generally speaking, the sleeper service is wonderful but, occasionally,
things do go wrong, so it is important to take precautions.''
Normally, the official menu during the 12-hour journey includes soup, melon,
beef stew, Thai-style vegetables, and cheesecake.
A ScotRail spokesman said: ``Mr de Savary is a valued customer who was entitled
to feel upset at the unfortunate mix-up on his last trip.
``He was making a point, and we can see the funny side of that, but I do not
think he would be very pleased if one of his guests turned up at Skibo Castle
with a carry-out.''
Mr de Savary's Carnegie Club, at Skibo Castle, is set in 7500 acres on the
shores of the Dornoch Firth.
It opened in April after a #17m refurbishment and already more than 200 of the
world's rich and famous have paid the #2000 a year fees.
The castle was rebuilt early this century by the Fife-born American steel
magnate, Andrew Carnegie, who called it his ``heaven on earth''.
</TEXT>
