<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>10-year-old boy who died from brain haemorrhage was ferried between four hospitals Scanner delay inquiry call</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897223</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday demanded a Government inquiry into the case of a 10-year-old
boy who died after he was moved between four hospitals after collapsing at home.
Nicholas Geldard was moved between three hospitals in Greater Manchester before
being driven 45 miles through a snowstorm to a fourth hospital in Leeds.
By the time a scan confirmed he had a brain haemorrhage, doctors were unable to
save him.
Nicholas, from Offerton, Stockport, collapsed at his home last Thursday and was
taken by ambulance to Stockport Infirmary.
His mother, Mrs Cath Geldard, said it took 20 minutes for an ambulance to
arrive. At the hospital, Nicholas was seen by a nurse, but not a doctor, she
claimed.
Mrs Geldard said a decision was taken to give Nicholas a scan at another local
hospital, Stepping Hill.
However, the ambulance transfer took an hour - making Nicholas too late for the
scan. The scanner at Stepping Hill operates only between 9am and 5pm and by the
time he got there the unit was closed.
Doctors decided to carry out the scan next day but when the boy's condition
deteriorated it became clear they could not wait.
Eventually, he was given a scan at Hope Hospital which confirmed that a slow
bleed was putting pressure on his brain.
An operation was vital but there were no paediatric intensive care beds
available.
The only bed that could be found was at Leeds General, 45 miles away. By the
time Nicholas reached the hospital, after an ambulance drive through a
snowstorm, he was dead.
Mrs Geldard said: ``We are very, very angry. You put your life in the hands of
the health service yet Nicholas was fatally let down.
``This shouldn't happen ever again. It was a nightmare.''
Nicholas's funeral will take place in Offerton tomorrow.
Labour's Shadow Health Secretary Harriet Harman said yesterday: ``This is an
absolutely ghastly case. It's clear that the resources Nicholas needed to give
him a fighting chance of living were not there for him.
``By the time he got to Leeds, it was too late. I will be asking the Secretary
of State to set up a full Department of Health inquiry, because you can't look
at something like this involving four hospitals on a local basis.''
Her remarks were echoed by Stockport MP Ann Coffey, who took up the case after
speaking to the family.
``There are two serious issues here. One is why a very expensive scanner paid
for by public subscription is not available after 5pm, and the second is the
unavailability of intensive care beds.
``In the north-west, we have some very fine hospitals, very fine doctors, and
very good facilities. But if because of the way the internal market operates
you can't use these facilities, it raises questions about planning and the use
of resources.
``I want this to be investigated at a very high level. It's not enough just to
look at each part of the jigsaw.''
Stockport Healthcare NHS Trust and Stockport Acute Services NHS Trust said in a
joint statement: ``This is a distressing set of circumstances in which every
effort was made by both trusts to avoid the ultimately tragic outcome. We offer
our deepest sympathy to the family of Nicholas Geldard.''
The trusts said a ``full inquiry'' would be held. Preliminary inquiries had
indicated that ``good clinical practice was observed at all times''.
The statement said it had to be remembered the boy's condition was not static
and for some time he appeared to be improving.
Shortly before midnight, his condition deteriorated suddenly and calls were
made to a number of hospitals in an effort to find an intensive care bed. The
first to become available was at Leeds General.
``By 12.40, a bed was secured at Leeds, conditional on a scan being carried out
before he could be admitted,'' said the statement.
The scan at Hope Hospital confirmed he had suffered a brain haemorrhage.
The statement went on: ``At all times Nicholas was under the care of Stockport
Healthcare NHS Trust, he was continually looked after by senior staff members
and indeed during his transfer to Hope Hospital, Manchester, and to Leeds
General, Nicholas was accompanied by a consultant anaesthetist, a paediatric
registrar, and a senior nurse from Stepping Hill.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Leak caused shutdown at Dounreay</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOUNREAY's main reprocessing plant was closed down after an unplanned release
of radioactivity into the air on November 22, the same day as the ballot papers
in the referendum on reprocessing foreign reactor fuel were sent out to the
20,000 voters in Caithness.
The results of that referendum are expected today but yesterday management was
stressing that while the emission breached Dounreay's own self-imposed limits,
it was well with-in the legal limits laid down by the regulatory authorities.
No radioactivity had escaped into the workplace and the release from the
chimney had posed no risk.
A meeting of the Dounreay local liaison committee on November 28 was not told
of the the release and the subsequent shutdown. The first indication came in a
letter to last week's edition of the Orcadian newspaper from the Orkney-based
Campaign Against Dounreay Expansion. On Monday, Dounreay's director, Mr John
Baxter, sent an internal message to the workforce explaining the situation.
He wrote: ``There has been some media interest in the temporary shutdown of
D1208 waste plant and D1206 reprocessing plant. I therefore wanted you to be
aware of the facts, which are: the on-line monitoring system in the ventilation
stack activated on November 22. This was due to discharge levels being above
our self-imposed, and very conservative, daily limit.
``Our discharges usually average about 10% of the authorisation which we are
fully entitled to utilise. The discharge involved an insignificant release of
radioactivity which was well within our discharge authorisation. There was
therefore no increased hazard to either site personnel or the public. In order
to investigate the circumstances, D1208 was shut down and D1206 operations were
stopped as a consequence of this.''
Remedial work was proceeding and although the incident was not one which
Dounreay had been required to report to its regulatory bodies, they had been
kept informed of the situation, Mr Baxter said.
Dounreay spokesman Ian Shepherd told The Herald yesterday that the incident had
not been reported to the local liaison committee because it had been very
minor. There had been no intention to conceal anything.
The reprocessing plant involved in the incident is currently in the middle of a
three-year programme reprocessing fuel from the Prototype Fast Reactor as part
of decommissioning work. It would not be involved in the controversial
contracts to reprocess spent fuel of American origin from 33 research reactors
across Europe. If the US Government approves the proposal and if the HM
Industrial Pollution Inspectorate approves the plant's proposed discharge
levels in the new year, the work would take place in the Materials Testing
Reactor D1204.
Anti-nuclear activists yesterday, however, were anxious to link this incident
to the foreign reprocessing contracts and the referendum. Mr Kevin Dunion,
director of Friends of the Earth Scotland, said: ``It is true this incident
took place in the PFR reprocessing plant but it should be remembered the MTR is
considerably older.
``It would appear that Dounreay did not want information about this incident to
be published during the referendum. But it is of concern that Dounreay can pick
and choose which incidents it publishes. This may be consistent with the
absence of any proper public consultation on the plant's activities but it
undermines the Scottish people's democratic right to know what is happening
there.''
</TEXT>
