<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What's left, they wonder, in the clear-out of family silver</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``WILL it be the Mace next and the despatch boxes?'' enquired Mr Dennis Skinner
(Bolsover - Lab). There was not, as he also remarked, a lot of the family
silver left.
The remarkably smooth Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster, Mr Roger Freeman,
who resembles one of those chaps who used to appear in Brylcream hair-oil
adverts, had just announced another privatisation. Her Majesty's Stationery
Office was to go under the hammer, and Mr Freeman was encountering some
difficulties because this excellent organisation prints parliamentay and
Government publications with great efficiency.
``I want a guarantee,'' demanded Mr Skinner, ``that the contract will not go to
Haymarket Press, your gaffer's firm.''
Mr Freeman, though he has a splendid title himself, is merely deputy to the
imperial Deputy Prime Minister, Mr Michael Heseltine, whose wealth was founded
on publishing ventures.
Mr Skinner also wanted a guarantee against Mr Rupert Murdoch and, had time
permitted, probably could have added extensively to the list of media barons of
whom he disapproves.
There was, though, a faintly elegiac note in his denunciation. We seemed to be
nearly at the end of a long road. The Government had privatised almost
everything and Mr Skinner had denounced each step along the route. He has to
hold something in reserve in case it managed to privatise the NHS before
demitting office. It had sold off #80bn worth of public assets, Dennis mused,
and much good it was doing it.
Mr Derek Foster, emerging from years of Trappist silence as Opposition Chief
Whip, eloquently described Mr Freemam as ``an honest man fallen among thieves.''
This was a remark difficult to reply to either as a compliment or a criticism,
and Mr Freeman did not try.
A reasonable number of Tory MPs sang the praises of the private sector, but Mr
Patrick Cormack (Stafford South - Con.), a Westminster buff who has written
books about the place, said that he and others on the Government back benches
were ``not necessarily excited'' about this development.
With a majority of five and falling, even mild criticism must set ministerial
alarm bells ringing. Labour MPs, viewing the Government's activities with the
habitual suspicion of Oppositions, expressed their own alarm at Mr Freeman's
unwillingness to say that the Commons would have a free vote on the proposal -
this being not just any old privatisation but one that could affect the speed
with which they are served up the multitude of papers that facilitate, or at
any rate record, their work.
As a House of Commons matter, this privatisation would seem to be suitable for
a free vote but ``that is not a matter for me,'' said Mr Freeman. Technically,
he was right but, if the Governmment had decided to give democracy its head,
the Chief Whip would doubtless not have minded him passing on the good news.
Although a capable performer, the Minister was unable to dismiss the charge
that ideology was behind the move. A Labour MP suggested that the HMSO should
be allowed to borrow on the market and widen its commercial activities while
remaining in the public sector.
Mr Freeman replied that this Govermment could not and would not countenance a
public body subsidised by taxpayers' money competing with the private sector.
MPs will be given a chance to debate the matter at more length next week. The
Government has settled on Wednesday, the last sitting day before Christmas when
many Members may feel more inclined to head for the Yuletide fireplaces of home
than stay and try to dishevel the immaculate Mr Freeman.
</TEXT>
