<HEADLINE>Student wins court victory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897226</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Student wins
court victory
STUDENT Ade Onibiyo yesterday won permission to bring an urgent challenge at
the High Court in London against the Home Secretary's decision to deport him
to
Nigeria.
Lawyers for the 19-year-old said, as a member of a family of prominent
pro-democracy activists opposed to the Nigerian regime, he would be in
imminent
danger if he was sent back. His father, Abdul, 53, was deported seven weeks
ago and has not been seen or heard of since.
Dentists' protest
THE protest by senior dentists at Glasgow Dental Hospital was discussed
officially by the hospital trust board yesterday for the first time. They were
shown a letter from the Dental Division, representing about 50 consultant
dentists and other senior staff, intimating that they had passed a vote of no
confidence in the trust's chief executive, Dr Doreen Steele, because of what
they describe as a confrontational management style.
Pupil fined
A 16-YEAR-OLD who is studying for four Highers at Larbert High School in
Stirlingshire was fined #200 yesterday for having a flick-knife with a 5in
blade. Falkirk Sheriff Court heard that police were called to a petrol station
by staff, searched Stephen Connacher, of Larbert, and found the weapon.
Bridge plunge
AN outside pursuits instructor is recovering in Stirling Royal Infirmary after
breaking his legs in a fall from Dochart Bridge, Killin, Perthshire. Mr Ian
Mackinnon, 23, of Ardtullaich, Ardeonaig, near Loch Tay, is described as
``comfortable'' after the accident on Friday. He is the son of singer Mary
Sandeman.
College fire
A FIRE caused #500,000 damage at Kilmarnock College yesterday. Fourteen
classrooms were destroyed. Principal James Flynn said: ``We do not know what
caused the blaze but there is nothing to suggest that it was started
deliberately. About 1500 pupils were evacuated safely.'' Police inquiries are
continuing.
Pringle vote
PRINGLE of Scotland knitwear workers yesterday rejected overwhelmingly the
firm's refusal to concede any part of a pay and conditions package submitted
last week. The GMB union announced that a ballot of employees in Hawick,
Galashiels, and Berwick produced 710 against the firm's stance, and 352
accepting a pay freeze. The union has sought a 5% pay rise, a minimum #4 an
hour for lower paid workers, and an extra day's holiday.
Green for gone
TWO sets of temporary traffic lights worth more than #3000 have been stolen
from road works on the A68 at Drygrange and Earlston in the Borders.
Jobs cut
NINETEEN of the 32 employees at Gleneagles Spring Water Company Limited, near
Blackford, Perthshire, will be made redundant next month.
Hospital plan
A #30m expansion at Ninewells Hospital, Dundee, has been given the go-ahead by
the Scottish Office.
</TEXT>
