<HEADLINE>Union tackles contractor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNISON yesterday launched a campaign against Pall Mall, an NHS contractor with
which it is in dispute at hospitals in East Kilbride, Middlesex, and Essex.
Advertisements will be placed in the national and trade press drawing attention
to the company's alleged record of refusing to abide by the TUPE transfer of
undertaking regulations, especially at Hillingdon Hospital in Middlesex, where
56 staff have been sacked for refusing to accept pay cuts averaging between #25
and #35 a week.
Many of those sacked were Asian women. Some had worked at the hospital for
nearly 30 years.
Porters at Hairmyres Hospital, East Kilbride, are holding a strike ballot, the
result of which should be known a week today, over non-payment of back pay and
a refusal to recognise the union.
The union has also published a report called Pall Mall: The Unacceptable Face
of Contracting, detailing the company's alleged record in the NHS. This will be
used to brief MPs, the NHS executive, the Commission for Racial Equality, and
the Private Contractors Association.
Unison's head of health, Mr Bob Abberley, said Hillingdon and Hairmyres were
just two of the places where Pall Mall had attempted to impose pay cuts soon
after winning contracts, hitting some of the lowest paid workers in Britain.
``We want the NHS itself and other contractors to say publicly that such
treatment of staff is unacceptable - and for Pall Mall to realise that their
commercial future will be affected if they refuse to change their ways,'' he
said.
Pall Mall's managing director, Mr Robin Oakley Smith, maintained that his
company was recognised throughout the NHS as an excellent employer. He denied
that there was a dispute at Hillingdon, where everything was operating
``absolutely normally''.
The vast majority of staff had signed new contracts ``at a very competitive
local rate of pay of #3.58 an hour''.
Unison said the 56 dismissed staff were taking their cases to an industrial
tribunal.
</TEXT>
