<HEADLINE>Tartan brain drain warning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tartan brain
drain warning
A TAX-RAISING Scottish Parliament with no firm commitment to business and
industry could produce a tartan brain drain and drive away foreign investors, a
senior Scottish industrialist warned yesterday.
Increasing taxes by even 3p in the pound would lead to increased wage demands
and higher costs, forcing the high fliers in the engineering and electronics
fields to move abroad, according to Mr Howard Jordan, chief executive of
Scottish Engineering.
Nolan hearings
THE committee on standards in public life, the Nolan Committee, is to hold
public hearings in Edinburgh next month as part of the its study into local
public spending bodies.
Economic key
CRIEFF'S local economy would be boosted by more than #9m a year if 500 houses
were built, Perth and Kinross District Council was told. A report by
Scott-Moncrieff Ltd identifies lack of housing as a key factor in stopping the
town's growth.
Assault on baby
A FATHER who wrenched his four-and-a-half-month old son's arm so badly that it
broke was sentenced to three years' probation at Edinburgh Sheriff Court
yesterday. The 21-year-old chef had earlier admitted assaulting the boy in a
house in Dalkeith, Midlothian.
Armed robbery
POLICE are hunting two masked men who held up a finance office in Dumbarton
High Street at knifepoint on Tuesday.
Theft charge
A MAN has appeared in court charged with a robbery at a nursing home. Mr Owen
McGreevy, 30, of Wauchope Square, Edinburgh, appeared in private at Edinburgh
Sheriff Court yesterday.
Fire inquiry
POLICE were yesterday investigating a blaze in Rosie O'Grady's bar in Princes
Street, Falkirk. Part of the town was sealed off after residents reported an
explosion.
Turkey warning
TRADING standards officers are worried that new metric food weight labels may
lead to undercooked turkeys being served up, increasing the risk of food
poisoning. Turkey should be cooked for 44 minutes per kilo.
Road death
A 60-YEAR-OLD man has died after being knocked down in Crookston Road, Glasgow
yesterday. Mr Hugh Connaghan, of Cairnhill Circus, Crookston, died at Southern
General Hospital.
</TEXT>
