<HEADLINE>West outraged by China's second harsh sentence on dissident writer `Traitor' Wei gets 14 years</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHARLENE FU</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Beijing
WEI JINGSHENG, China's boldest advocate of democracy and human rights, was
convicted today of trying to overthrow the government and sentenced to 14 more
years in prison.
The Beijing Intermediate Court found the Nobel Peace Prize nominee guilty of
sedition for organising art exhibitions and writing articles criticising the
communist government.
Wei, 45, was first sent to jail in 1979 for his writing. He was released in
1993 and immediately resumed working to draw international attention to China's
human rights record.
He disappeared into police custody in April last year and was held for 20
months without charges. Today's trial and sentencing took less than five hours.
The sentence is the harshest blow yet to China's tiny dissident community, and
brought immediate condemnation by Western governments and Wei's relatives.
``This is an outrage,'' said his sister, Shanshan. ``There is no factual basis
for such a verdict.
``The Chinese Government is shameless. They operate like an organised crime
group that pays no attention to the law.''
She was speaking in Washington, where she is lobbying the US Government to
increase its human rights pressure on China.
At a news conference with several members of Congress, Shanshan said her
brother was not the only one affected.
``It is also a question of defending thousands of dissidents in China, and
fundamental rights of freedom of expression of over one billion Chinese
people,'' she said.
Although human rights groups have championed Wei's cause and called for his
release, not one Western government has threatened China with economic
reprisals to gain fair treatment for him since he was detained 20 months ago.
The Foreign Office expressed ``dismay and concern'' at the sentence, saying Wei
had been harshly treated and that it would make its views known to the Chinese
authorities.
The human rights group Amnesty International called Wei's trial ``a mockery of
justice''. France, Germany, and the US joined in condemning the sentence.
In Hong Kong, pro-democracy activists in Hong Kong waved large pictures of Wei
outside China's representative office in the British colony.
Some residents said Wei's fate added to worries about their future after Hong
Kong is handed back to China in 1997.
Wei's brother, Xiaotao, said he believed Wei would appeal, but most appeals in
China are rejected.
Foreign reporters and diplomats were barred from the court building today by
scores of police who patrolled the perimeter in heavy fog and snow.
Wei Xiaotao and another sister were the only family members allowed into the
courtroom. It was the first time Wei's family has seen him since he was
detained.
Their concern about his health was heightened when Wei told the judge he felt
ill and the court took a 30-minute recess.
Shansan said she feared Wei might not survive his sentence because he has
serious heart problems and high blood pressure.
It will be Wei's second stint in jail. He was sentenced to a 15-year term in
1979 after writing powerful essays warning that China's attempts at economic
development would be meaningless without democracy and human rights.
Wei is not the first of the activists from the 1978-                79
Democracy Wall movement to be given a second jail       term.
His associate, Ren Wanding, is serving a seven-year term for making
pro-democracy speeches during the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests.-AP/Reuter.
Leader comment ..................18
</TEXT>
