<HEADLINE>Tribute paid to airmen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHARLENE FU</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897230</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Toronto
HUNDREDS of people last night attended a memorial service honouring seven
British airmen killed when their plane crashed into Lake Ontario during the
Canadian International Air Show in September.
A letter of condolence from Prime Minister Jean Chretien was read at the
service at St Paul's Anglican Church.
Those in attendance included Canadian military officers, police involved in the
recovery of the wreckage, and 30 officers from the airmen's home base, RAF
Kinloss.
Killed in the crash were Flight-Lieutenant Dom Gilbert, 31; Flight-Lieutenant
Glenn Hooper, 25; Flight-Lieutenant Nick Brooks, 26; Flight-Lieutenant Bernie
Worthington, 37; Sergeant Gary Moxham, 32; Sergeant Richie Williams, 28; and
Sergeant Craig Barnett, 32.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
