<DOCNO>GH951214-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turkey given EU deal with strings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897231</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
EURO-MPs yesterday voted to approve a money-spinning Customs union between the
European Union and Turkey, but only on condition that Ankara improves its
record on human rights.
After years of negotiations, the EU breathed a sigh of relief after the
Strasbourg legislature gave reluctant consent to a deal dogged by complaints
that the Turks are too undemocratic and intolerant of dissent, especially with
the Kurds.
MEPs of both main groupings, the Socialists and centre-right Christian
Democrats, insisted on strings to ensure that the pact was accompanied by
Turkish efforts to respect individual and minority rights.
Socialists' leader Mrs Pauline Green said they would vote in favour, but
without enthusiasm.
``Those of us who vote in favour do so not because we believe that present
conditions in Turkey make her an appropriate partner whose democracy has stood
the test of time,'' she said, arguing that a No vote would have harmed people
in Turkey who were fighting the cause of democracy.
Mrs Green urged Ankara to co-operate on Cyprus now that the island is in line
for EU membership, and to resolve the Kurdish problem by means of a settlement
recognising the rights of minorities to their own language, culture, and
traditions.
British Tory MEPs voted with the Christian Democrat-led European People's Party
in favour of the deal, but joined the Socialists in demanding safeguards for
human rights.
The vote was 343 in favour to 149, with 36 abstentions.
EU External Relations Commissioner Hans van den Broek said the deal would
benefit both the EU and Turkey economically. ``It's quite easy to see that if
you remove all the tariff and non-tariff barriers to exports, that will lead to
a great increase of trade in Turkey,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>More union concern about Higher Still</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897232</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER teachers' union has expressed doubts about whether the 1998 target for
implementing the Higher Still reform of upper secondary schooling can be met.
The Scottish Secondary Teachers' Association has agreed to co-operate with the
development programme, but now says its members' involvement will depend on
their continued concerns being answered.
These include resources for staff, how courses are to be assessed, and worries
about taking classes with pupils at different levels. The union also wanted
clarification about the production of course and shorter unit materials.
The Educational Institute of Scotland will continue its boycott of Higher Still
after concluding that the timescale for implementation was unrealistic because
of unsufficient resources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Upgrading of school is opposed by council</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897233</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are no educational or financial grounds for Dornoch Academy - Scotland's
first opted out school - being allowed to upgrade from its present two years to
full six year secondary status, Highland Regional Council's education committee
resolved unanimously yesterday.
The committee had been asked to comment on the current application by Dornoch
to Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth for permission to begin progressive
upgrading by adding a third year in May. It backed a report from director of
education Mr Allan Gilchrist opposing the application.
Highland Regional Council is billed monthly for the money the Scottish Office
pays to Dornoch Academy in annual recurrent grant. In the financial year to
March 1995, the grant totalled #387,367. Mr Gilchrist's report concluded that
if the 49 pupils currently attending Dornoch Academy were sent to the council
run Golpsie High School or Tain Royal Academy, it would save the council over
#310,000.
Mr Gilchrist recalled Mr Forsyth's own comments during the debate on the Self
Governing Schools Bill when, as Education Minister, he talked of how the
Secretary of State would consider an application to change a school's
characteristics.
Mr Forsyth had said: ``If one factor is that the school has only been
self-governing for, say, two years, that will certainly weigh with him. Indeed,
he will generally regard that as a very strong argument against making any
further substantial change in the school for the time being.''
Meanwhile, Highland Council is facing the prospect of having to close 28
schools as financial shortages and the demands of a Government finance watchdog
start to take effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Weigh to go</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897234</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOCTOR Cherie Martin has helped thousands of women confront their own fatness,
and stop dieting. For this South African born doctor, now based in Glasgow,
launched Weigh Ahead, a revoluntionary new concept in weight control, writes
Ann Shaw.
Her message is simple: Forget diets - they don't work. Listen to your body.
Find out why you over-eat.
Now she has just written a book, Naturally Slim (Transworld Publishers, #6.99).
Dr Martin tells how she went on her first diet as a 12-year-old when she
weighed 11 stones; she knows from bitter experience that dieting doesn't work.
A victim of the diet/binge cycle, she was in her final year in medical school
and browsing through her local bookshop one afternoon when she came across a
book that was to transform her life. It was called Diets Don't Work by Bob
Schwartz.
``I got outraged as I read about the multi-million-dollar diet industry that
would like to keep us dieting. I was amazed to read that only two out of every
hundred people are successful at dieting.''
She read that 13 years after she began her first diet.
``I wept as I realised it was not my fault. The years of eating misery had
started because when I went on that first diet, I had started down a road which
would lead me further and further away from what I really wanted. While
searching for freedom from my food and weight obsession, I was constantly on a
diet and this only caused an increase in my food and weight obsession. A sense
of relief poured over me, as I read the book. Suddenly, I saw that there was a
way out at last.''
She believes you've got to confront the reasons why you over-eat: is it
loneliness, boredom, stress, or fatigue? Only when you've uncovered the key
factors to your own unhealthy eating patterns and confronted them will you
begin to change your lifestyle. You've got to learn to eat like a naturally
slim person, and that's to eat when you are hungry.
In Naturally Slim, Dr Martin reveals how she stopped dieting, lost 70 pounds,
and, more importantly, her obession with dieting.
A trained therapist, she helps you to discover the links between your eating
and your emotions. For those who are serious about their excess flab this book
makes an excellent start to the New Year.
AND here's more good news for those who were worried about the need to diet for
Christmas. It really is a waste of time. Heresy? No, says Dr Richard Cottrell,
editor of Weight Control, a collection of papers on obesity written by leading
medical experts.
``It's impossible to overeat in two or three days and put on weight. Say you
normally eat 2000 calories and you double it over Christmas. The amount of
weight gain would be too small for you to notice.''
But what if you over-indulge for two or three weeks? He admits then you will
put on a few pounds, but emphasises that's not the real problem.
``It's steadily over-eating, day after day. That's what puts on all those extra
pounds which turn into stones over the years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jury to hear fresh evidence of personality disorder and battered woman syndrome Wife who killed wins retrial</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897235</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN, who became the focus of a campaign demanding justice for battered
women driven to kill, yesterday won the right to a retrial after her original
conviction of murdering her violent, drunken husband was quashed.
Mrs Sara Thornton, who served six years of a life sentence before being
released on bail last July, will remain free pending the retrial at Birmingham
in the new year.
The Court of Appeal held fresh medical evidence, showing Mrs Thornton had a
personality disorder and suffered from battered woman syndrome, should be
considered by a jury to determine whether she suddenly lost her self-control at
the time of the killing.
Her lawyers had asked the appeal judges not to order a retrial but to reduce
her murder conviction to manslaughter through provocation. They argued the
evidence showed she was an abused woman at the end of her tether when she
suddenly snapped, plunging a kitchen knife into ex-policeman Mr Malcolm
Thornton as he lay drunk on a sofa.
But Lord Taylor, the Lord Chief Justice, sitting with Mr Justice Hidden and Mrs
Justice Ebsworth, said: ``We are firmly of the view that the question of
whether the appellant did lose or may have lost her self-control at the time of
this killing is essentially a matter for a jury to decide. It is not for us.''
He said that, despite lawyers' objections that the ordeal of a retrial would
not be fair and would be impracticable because of press coverage, the public
interest required the issue to be determined. The court was confident that a
fresh jury ``will be able fairly to try the case solely on the evidence they
hear''.
Mrs Thornton, 38, of Atherstone, Warks, was jailed for life at Birmingham Crown
Court in February 1990. Her original appeal was rejected in 1991. It was that
appeal which led to changes in the way courts apply the law on provocation and
several other women convicted of domestic murder have since been freed as a
result.
Mrs Thornton was bailed in July following Home Secretary Michael Howard's
decision to refer her case back to the Court of Appeal.
Mrs Thornton had denied threatening to kill her husband on occasions before the
fatal day - June 13, 1989. She told police she only intended to frighten her
husband with the knife. At her trial, she said the stabbing was an accident.
Mrs Thornton's trial defence was diminished responsibility, not provocation,
although that issue was left to the jury.
At Mrs Thornton's first appeal, the court rejected argument that the law was
too rigid in insisting that, for the defence of provocation to succeed, it had
to be shown that the provocative words or conduct caused ``a sudden and
temporary loss of self control''.
Lord Taylor reaffirmed the principle and said even someone suffering from
battered woman syndrome could not rely on provocation unless there was sudden
loss of self-control at the time of the killing.
``We conclude that the fresh evidence and the clarification of the law cast
doubt upon the basis of the jury's verdict in this case. We cannot therefore be
sure the verdict is safe and satisfactory,'' said Lord Taylor.
The judges quashed the conviction, ordered Mrs Thornton to be recharged within
two months, and said the retrial should take place as early in the new year as
possible.
After being released on bail, Mrs Thornton left the Law Courts in central
London without making any comment.
</TEXT>
