<DOCNO>GH951214-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#73m aimed at saving wildlife</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE Environment Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897236</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS to protect 116 of the UK's most threatened and declining species were
welcomed by Green campaigners yesterday.
Conservationists, however, warned the Scottish Office that it would have to
give the report its full support, especially in the light of its cut of #5m
this week to the budget of Scottish Natural Heritage.
A spokeswoman at St Andrew's House pointed out that, while SNH had suffered a
10% cut in its budget, the Scottish Office itself had had its budget cut by 12%.
The Joint Study Report on SNH, announced yesterday, had found that the agency
was able to make ``substantial efficiency savings without in any way affecting
its work'', she added. The proposals by the UK Steering Group Report on
Bio-diversity would cost more than #9m to protect species, along with a further
#73m spent on their habitats by 2010.
Some of the indigenous Scottish species targeted by the report include the
corncrake and capercailzie. The report is also concerned about the song thrush
and the skylark which, while not in danger of extinction, have had their
populations cut by 50% in the last 25 years, largely because of the change in
land use.
The group's report also identifies 14 key habitats which now require action to
protect them, from native pinewoods and hedgerows to limestone pavements and
coastal lagoons.
One aim is to ensure the return of the otter to almost every county in Britain
by 2010.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman says love affair cost her job</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897237</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WOMAN feared she would lose her job after her affair with her married boss
ended.
An industrial tribunal heard that Mrs Jennifer McMillan had an affair with boss
Mike Dale and a colleague had been axed a year earlier when her affair with the
same man ended.
Mrs McMillan, 25, claimed she was forced to quit her #17,000-a-year job as
senior supervisor as she was effectively demoted when she went back to work at
Saztec Europe Ltd's Ardrossan plant after her affair with Mr Dale ended, the
Glasgow tribunal heard.
Mrs McMillan met former colleague Ruth Donnachie and discovered Mr Dale had
been trying to win her back. She said that explained events at work.
The tribunal heard that Mrs McMillan had been given a company car, the one
formerly used by Ms Ruth Donnachie, but she lost the use of it when she was off
sick.
She also claimed she was threatened with a pay cut and given a menial task to
do when she started back with no responsibility for any staff. She had
previously been supervising almost 50.
The company said she was given a highly technical job to do on her return, her
pay wasn't cut, and she still had the title of senior supervisor. It was Mrs
McMillan who offered to return her car while off sick, which was for pool use
during office hours.
Mrs McMillan's father, Mr Peter Monaghan, who represented her at the tribunal,
said Mr Dale's relationship with Ms Donnachie ended in bitterness when he
discovered she was seeing a younger man, her sister was sacked shortly
afterwards, and she was made redundant on May 13 last year.
Mr Monaghan said Mr Dale had told the tribunal the two affairs were ``howling
mistakes''. Mr Monaghan said: ``It raises questions of his abuse of power
within the company. Certainly it appears that the careers of three females were
ruined because of his behaviour.
``Mr Dale abused his power and used general manager Mrs Ann Barlow to squeeze
Jenny out of Saztec as excess baggage. As a result, she resigned from her job.''
Solicitor Martin Stephen, for the company, said Mrs McMillan was a willing
participant in the affair.
Mr Dale had admitted he still had feelings for Ms Donnachie but said she was
made redundant for genuine reasons and he played no part in the dismissal of
her sister. He denied any involvement in the alleged change in Mrs Barlow's
attitude to Mrs McMillan.
The tribunal will issue its written decision later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
