<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ian Campbell</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897238</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR IAN Campbell, the former convener of Highland Regional Council, died at his
home on Skye last week at the age of 75. He had suffered from motor neurone
disease.
Mr Campbell had represented Skye in local government for more than 25 years,
first on Inverness County Council and then on Highland Regional Council. He was
elected to represent North and West Skye on the regional council at
reorganisation in 1974 and quickly became chairman of its roads and transport
committee.
He was elected convener at the beginning of the second council in 1978 and
again in 1982. He held the position until 1986 and was subsequently awarded the
OBE for his services to local government. He bowed out of the council in 1990.
Mr Campbell received part of his education at Inverness Royal Academy and went
on to graduate from Edinburgh University. During the war he served as a captain
in the Royal Army Service Corps before going home to run the family hotel at
Sligachan, its land, and other business interests.
On hearing of Mr Campbell's death, Duncan McPherson, the present convener of
Highland Regional Council said: ``Ian was a good friend and colleague for more
than 20 years. He was a real statesman and was so well thought of that he was
elected to serve for two terms as convener of the regional council. During his
time, he offered clear leadership and sound guidance to the authority. He was a
great ambassador for the Highlands.''
Mr Campbell is survived by his wife Fiona, two sons, Alan and Ian, and his
daughter Catriona.
</TEXT>
