<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dr Hector MacLean</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dr Hector MacLean MC; born September 30, 1912, died December 6, 1995
THE people of the Small Isles of Eigg, Muck, Rum and Canna buried Dr Hector
MacLean last week at the age of 83. A loved and respected figure, he had served
as their general practitioner for 39 years but had spent the last five and a
half years in retirement on Eigg, the island whose embrace he never sought to
leave.
Dr MacLean had come to the practice in 1952 and did not retire until April 1,
1990 when he had reached the age of 77. He had postponed his retiral in an
attempt to secure a guarantee that his successor would also be based in the
islands rather than on the mainland working out of a health centre in Mallaig
as had been suggested by Highland Health Board. One scheme had been for a
doctor from the mainland health centre to visit once a month by helicopter.
A test of wills ensued after the health board made clear they would not take
steps to replace him until he announced his retirement. These were the rules.
It was a Catch 22 situation but Hector MacLean was not to give up easily,
despite coming under enormous pressure from the authorities. His determination
was fuelled by a deep concern for the island families he had served for nearly
four decades in what remains one of the most isolated and difficult of
practices. ``Better an old doctor, than no doctor,'' he believed.
At the end of December 1988 he explained at greater length: ``I just cannot see
how adequate primary care can be delivered to these islands from the mainland.
The islanders can be singularly uncommunicative by telephone, and although I
have spent 37 years trying to educate them to use the doctor based here on the
Small Isles, I have failed. If they are not going to trouble me, they are not
going to trouble a doctor on the mainland. One old lady recently dislocated her
shoulder, but it was two days before she decided to call.''
Although the board agreed after he had announced his retirement that a
replacement did not have to be based in the islands, failure to establish the
health centre meant that Dr MacLean got his way. After an interim period with a
locum, the present GP Dr Chris Tiarks arrived on Eigg to take over the Small
Isles practice 1991.
The MacLean side of Hector MacLean's family had Hebridean connections, but
Hector MacLean was raised    in Hamilton. He studied medicine at Glasgow
University, graduating in 1935. During the war he served in the North African
campaign where he was decorated for bravery, being awarded the Miltary Cross.
On ``demob'' he secured a hospital appointment in Dumfries but in 1952 he
headed to the islands for his last professional posting. He married and had
three sons.
Comprising four islands separated by open water, the practice carried enormous
physical difficulties. Even today the Small Isles is not served by a car ferry
and the doctor then as now could not rely on public transport. Lawrence
MacEwen, who along with his brother owns and farms the island of Muck,
remembers Dr Maclean's visits to the island:
``I would be 12 when he first came to Muck. He used to come by canoe and you
would see him walking up the shore with the canoe on his head, always carrying
a brown rucksack on his back and always wearing a kilt. It was quite a sight.
He would come about a dozen times a year and visit everybody on the island
whether they were sick or not. He was always talking about the weather. I think
that was his real interest. When we went over to Eigg he always seemed to be on
the pier either with his fishing rod or playing the pipes, welcoming people to
the island.''
Dr MacLean was also to become an outspoken critic of the controversial ``Laird
of Eigg'', Keith Schellenberg who took over ownership in the 1970s and only
sold out to the German artist Maruma this summer. Dr MacLean's departure at
least is lamented, as Angus MacKinnon, a native of Eigg made clear yesterday.
``I was away when he arrived first but I got to know him when I was at home on
holiday and he was tending my mother and my father. I came home in 1965 and he
was always about, often with his pipes, just part of the place. He was a sound
man, a man of great integrity; the wee man in the kilt.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Long torment in the search for young Ben</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897240</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Yet another false sighting in Greece of abducted Ben Needham means one more
bitter disappointment for his family, but they will never give up the search,
reports Kirsty Scott
AT TIMES it must have seemed as if the torment could get no worse. Then there
would be another telephone call, another vague sighting of a small blond-haired
boy, and the trail would be picked up and followed before it ran cold, like all
the others before it.
When British toddler Ben Needham disappeared on the Greek island of Kos in July
1991, his family could never in their worst nightmares have thought they might
still be searching for him 4!s years on.
Yet, this week, they were involved in a fresh investigation after news that a
private investigator had found a boy he claimed to be Ben living with a group
of gipsies in northern Greece.
The blond-haired youngster apparently told the investigator that he was given
to the gipsies because his parents didn't want him. Police released the boy
yesterday after complaints by the gipsy family, and later establishing that he
was not Ben.
It had sounded promising, but so had many of the 180-odd other sightings and
reports which the Needhams have dealt with over the years and which have all
but destroyed this working-class Yorkshire family.
Ben was just 21 months old when he vanished from a remote farmhouse at
Herakles. He had been out of sight and out of earshot for only a few minutes
when the family realised something was wrong. A car had been seen on the
isolated track to the house and a group of gipsies were camping nearby.
Ben will now be six, and in the years since his disappearance, his
grandparents, Eddie and Christine Needham, have split up three times, and his
young mum, Kerry, has reportedly attempted suicide three times.
Speaking from Sheffield yesterday before the establishment of the gipsy boy's
identity, Kerry Needham had said she was keeping an open mind about the latest
sighting. In Kos, where Eddie Needham is ironically following up another
sighting of a similar youngster, he had told reporters: ``It would be the end
to everyone's nightmare if it was Ben.''
Yet while the discovery of Ben would end the agony of not knowing,
psychologists say the family would face a new series of problems.
Dr Malcolm Hill, director of Glasgow University's Centre for the Study of the
Child and Society, said Ben will almost certainly not recall his original
family.
``There would be major difficulties in adjustment. He would have identified
with his original family at 21 months, but the following years would have given
him a stronger identification with the new family. He might just have a very
hazy recollection of a previous life, but it is likely to be extremely hazy. He
will be identifying more than 95% with the new family.
``Presumably he will be speaking a different language. It's not likely to be a
very straightforward situation. It may well be the people he knows as his
parents would try to hang on to him and as far as he is concerned the original
family would be complete strangers trying to take him away. It's likely to be
very distressing and confusing.''
Dr Hill said the Needhams would need to reconcile the Ben they remember with a
different child. ``The family's problem would be their need to understand
what's happened to him. They will have retained this image of the child they
lost and they will be expecting a bigger version of that. He has been immersed
in a different family and a different culture and for the Needhams it would be
hard. How do they adjust their expectations?''
Dr David Warden, a senior lecturer in psychology at Strathclyde University,
believes any reunion would be harder for the parents than the child. Children,
he said, can often adjust to a new situation quickly and smoothly.
``The parents have gone through a continuing trauma for all these years and
they would bring a great deal of emotional baggage to any new situation, which
would convey itself to the child. They would just have to be very patient.''
Dr Hill believes that if Ben is ever returned the Needhams face a long, slow
process of healing before they become a complete family again.
``I think it would take a long time. He is going to have a lot of anger about
it. In a sense, he would have had two traumatic experiences. When he was
abducted he would have been very angry and upset about it; that's worked
through now in some way, but it will be buried within him. Being reunited with
his real family would be a double trauma.''
The Needhams insist that they prepared themselves for the fact that if they
ever find Ben he will be a different boy from the one they knew. They had also
prepared themselves to accept that this latest child was not Ben and that their
search would have to go on.
``You don't say hard luck, we can't find you,'' Christine Needham said
recently. ``You never give up, never - because he's our kiddy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Duchess of Norfolk</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RODDY MARTINE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lavinia, Duchess of Norfolk, LG, CBE, Lord Lieutenant of West Sussex; born
March 22, 1916, died December 10, 1995
THE Hon Lavinia Mary Strutt was born at Kingston Hall, Nottingham, the only
daughter of the 3rd Baron Belper. Her mother, the Hon Eva Bruce, was a daughter
of the 2nd Lord Aberdare, and six years after Lavinia's birth, having divorced
Lavinia's father, she married Lord Dalmeny, heir to the 5th Earl of Rosebery.
The duchess was therefore a half-sister of the 7th Earl of Rosebery, whose
Scottish home is Dalmeny House at South Queensferry, West Lothian.
The Strutt family had made their fortune in the Derby spinning business, and
the family title was earned through business acumen and political patronage.
Lavinia was educated at Abbotts Hill, Hertfordshire, where she developed a love
of sports, playing tennis at Wimbledon in later years, and rapidly becoming a
first-class horsewoman, winning point-to-points on her stepfather's horses.
In 1937, she married the 16th Duke of Norfolk, KG, GCVO, GBE, TD, PC, who was
responsible for the ceremonial arrangements for both the coronations of 1937
and 1953. At the first ceremony, prior to their marriage, the duchess was
recruited to hold the canopy over the Queen's head. For the rehearsals of 1953,
the duchess stood in for the young Queen Elizabeth.
The Duke and Duchess of Norfolk were married at Brompton Oratory, Knightsbridge
in 1937, shortly after the coronation. At the time, their union caused much
comment since she was Protestant and the Fitzalan-Howards of Norfolk ranked as
one of England's oldest Roman Catholic dynasties.
Throughout their marriage, however, they shared a common obsession with
breeding horses. In 1974, Ragstone won the Gold Cup at Royal Ascot, Moon
Madness won the St Leger at Doncaster in 1986, and Sheriff's Star won the
Coronation Cup at Epsom in 1989. Celtic Swing, not owned, but bred by the
duchess and trained by her daughter, Lady Herries, was unbeaten in top races
throughout the 1994 season, and earlier this year won the French Derby.
Following the birth of four daughters, it became apparent that there would be
no son to inherit Arundel Castle, the family's home near Chichester in Sussex.
Since the castle and dukedom would pass to another branch of the family on his
death, the 16th Duke decided to build a second home nearby. This Georgian-style
new house was named Arundel Park, and being much easier to live in that the
hill-top castle with its dark corridors and 150 rooms, was soon after occupied
by the family.
From 1959 until 1990, the duchess served as Lord Lieutenant of West Sussex, the
first woman to be appointed to such a post. In this role, she willingly
undertook up to 600 public engagements every year, at the same time becoming
actively supporting over 100 charitable organisations.
After the duke's death in 1975, she secured the survival of the family's
private cricket ground, modelled on the Oval, as a memorial to her husband. The
Arundel Castle Cricket Foundation has so far enabled more than 80,000 young
cricket enthusiasts with no home grounds to play the game. Indoor practice
sheds costing #500,000 have recently been donated by the philanthropist John
Paul Getty.
Lavinia, Duchess of Norfolk was a formidable organiser with an ability to
charm. In 1990 the Queen created her a Lady Companion of the Garter, the first
non-royal woman to be thus honoured.
She is survived by her daughters. On the duke's death, Lady Anne
Fitzalan-Howard, in the Celtic tradition, inherited the fifteenth-century
Scottish Lordship of Herries of Terregles in her own right. In 1985 she married
Sir Colin Cowdrey CBE, the cricketer.
Lady Mary Mumford is a lady-in-waiting to HRH Princess Alexandra, Lady Ogilvy,
and Lady Sarah Clutton lives in Sussex. Lady Jane is married to Michael Ancram,
MP, Minister of State, Northern Ireland Office, and heir to the 12th Marquis of
Lothian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Arthur Mullard</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897242</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Arthur Mullard, comedian; born November 10, 1910, died December 11, 1995
THE Cockney comedy actor Arthur Mullard, who has died at 85, got a taste of the
big time in his sixties with the 1970s ITV sitcom Yus My Dear, in which he
starred with Queenie Watts. He loved the experience and rumbled: ``What d'you
fink of that then? After 30 years a bleedin' star is born. I always knew I'd
make it to the top one day and now it happens when I've reached the age of
retiring.''
In the course of his career he had been a ``feed'' for some of the great comic
talents - Eric Sykes, Tony hancock, Bennie Hill, Frankie Howerd, and Spike
Milligan - hosted the Midweek Show on BBC Radio 4, and growled his way through
50 years of showbusiness life. This year he was still working for radio
commercials advertising everything from TCP to beer. Typically he commented:
``My voice is aht on it's own.''
The former boxer with a face like a bashed turnip worked with the most talented
and proved he could star on his own too. Born on the Essex Road in north London
and brought up in Peabody Buildings, Islington, Mullard had been a soldier, a
boxer, and then returned to the army for the Second World War before he
discovered a talent for comedy.
In 1978 Arthur and comedienne Hylda Baker were in the pop charts with You're
the One that I Want, the craziest-ever cover version of the song made famous by
John Travolta and Olivia Newton John in the film Grease. The unlikely duo even
appeared on Top of the Pops.
Despite fame Arthur never left his council flat in Islington where he and his
wife Flo had brought up three children. She died from a drugs overdose in 1961
after suffering several serious illnesses including polio, meningitis, and
ulcers.
During his career Mullard appeared in more than 400 films. He was the voice of
Butch the dog in Walt Disney's remake of 101 Dalmatians. His last film
appearance was in Confessions of a Plumber's Mate with Robin Askwith. He was
also a regular on Celebrity Squares.
Around his home patch he was known as the ``Dook of Islington'' where his 6ft
2in bulk and that distinctive bruiser's face brought him respect. He was a
working man through and through. ``I took up boxing professionally. Makes you
something of a philosopher. You bash them and they bash you and what's it all
for?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Racism rears in the ranks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897243</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Patrick Brogan underlines the difficulty the US Army faces in rooting out
racists
ON Thursday, December 7, three white soldiers stationed at Fort Bragg, in
Fayetteville, North Carolina, spent an evening drinking together and then drove
to a black part of town looking for black people to harass. They met a young
couple walking home and shot them both dead.
The three are in the 82nd Airborne Division, one of the most famous units in
the American army, and their horrified commanders have discovered that they
were notorious Nazis and white supremacists, who loathed blacks and Jews and
never made any secret of their racist notions.
Last April, two recently retired soldiers blew up a federal office building in
Oklahoma City, killing 169 people. They were allegedly motivated chiefly by
detestation of the Government rather than by outright racism, but the two
strains in the American far-right movement are close enough together. The worry
is that racism and Nazism are much more common in the armed forces than anyone
suspected.
Just after the Second World War, President Harry Truman desegregated the US
armed forces. It was one of the key moments in the slow, agonising and still
incomplete integration of black Americans into the mainstream. There had been
black soldiers before then, but only in separate, all-black units, with white
officers. It was all rather like the old Indian Army. Black troops had done
well in combat in all the wars since the Civil War, but they were not allowed
to fight with, let alone live alongside, white Americans.
Since then, the armed forces have become the most thoroughly integrated sector
in the United States. There are many more blacks, proportionately, in the
services than in the general population, including many of the most ambitious
and better educated of them: the Army has long been a way for black boys from
the ghettoes to escape from poverty.
The most celebrated example is General Colin Powell, who was born in the Bronx
and joined the Army as a teenager. He rose through the ranks to be chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff and for a while was spoken of as the first black man
who might be elected President.
In fact, integration of the races was taken so much for granted that the main
effort for the past decade has been devoted to integrating women. All the
public difficulties the armed forces faced in coming to terms with late
twentieth-century standards concerned sexual harassment of women or women's
struggles to meet standards set for pilots or soldiers.
Now the Army, in particular, has to face the fact that despite all its apparent
racial harmony, it has Nazis, skinheads, and white supremacists in its midst.
Two of the soldiers arrested for shooting the black couple last week lived off
the base, in a rented trailer which police found to be decorated with a Nazi
flag and large numbers of racist pamphlets.
Reporters interviewing other soldiers at the base easily discovered that the
suspects were known for their racist views, and now the Army is launching a
general investigation into the prevalence of racism in the ranks. The likely
answer, perhaps inevitably, is that the Army reflects the general society.
There has been an increase of extreme racism in American society, and it has
been reflected in the armed forces.
It's not all white racism, either. A particularly nasty case of black racism
has just exploded in Harlem, where black demonstrators, including some very
prominent demagogues, inciting violence against a Jewish shopkeeper, so
inflamed one man that he attacked the place and burnt it to the ground,
shooting four people (including himself) and burning four others to death.
There does not seem to be any organised Nazi infiltration of the services, any
more than there was an anti-Government organisation behind the Oklahoma City
bombing, and that makes it all the more difficult to deal with. Racism can pop
up anywhere.
So far, investigators have discovered about a dozen men at Fort Bragg who are
racist extremists. That is not very many, but there may well be more - and it
needs very few to cause trouble.
It is not clear at all what the Army could do about soldiers it determines to
be racists, if they do not undermine good order and military discipline by
their actions or words. This is a problem facing all free societies: what to do
with people who reject the bases of that freedom before they take up arms
against it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chancellor's little fashion statement</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897244</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell reports that Kenneth Clarke's small interest rate cut may not
change life as we know it, but it does seem to reflect the mood of the moment
INTEREST rates are down at last after two years, to their lowest level in
nearly 30 years. Can happy days be here again? The cut of 0.25% down to 6.5% is
the first since February 1994, and means the Chancellor is suddenly gambling
after a notably cautious Budget. Life is going to be wonderful again, we are
assured, though not like it was back then.
In 1966 a cheap car cost #500, a Rolls-Royce about #10,000, beer was under two
shillings a pint, a loaf of bread a shilling, and a packet of 20 cigarettes
about four shillings, while #8000 a year was a princely salary. Such happy days
will not be back.
But home loans will be cheaper, business confidence should soar, unemployment
may continue to fall, now the Chancellor has done the right thing at last. Or
has he?
He has not done exactly what Mr Eddie George, Governor of the Bank of England
wanted, but he seldom, if ever, does. Mr Clarke, who exudes boldness as much as
he does bonhomie, tends towards caution, although he is said in this instance
to have preferred a cut of 0.5%. Defending his Budget, Mr Clarke said the
forecast for economic growth next year was not contingent on an early cut in
interest rates.
``The one thing I am not going to do is start playing fast and loose with
interest rates in response to political pressures,'' he declared, hand on heart
and, no doubt, with the fingers crossed on the other one concealed behind his
back. Politicians saying they will not do something are always planning to do
it, as the financial markets believed at the time.
Given the disappointing size of the Budget tax cuts, the forecast glad morning
did not dawn, leaving Tory MPs despondent, clearly something else was needed
from Mr Clarke. Now that something has happened.
Interest rates have become something of a political football - the Opposition
can always call for action because they do not have to implement it, but by
doing so are seen to be suggesting something positive.
The important thing about being in Opposition is to say the Government is not
doing enough or doing too much, even when you know what you are suggesting is
wrong. This does not matter because it is not going to happen so nobody will
find your error out, and, while the Chancellor may mock, since he is not going
to do it either, he is not going to show your error up for what it is.
As for his mockery, it will be treated by the electorate as what they would
expect him to do, such is the combative nature of our politics.
But will the cut make any real difference to you, me and the man in the
Hillhead tram? Will we start spending again, boosting those sluggish high
street sales, up only 0.6% last month over the previous one?
Mind you, that 0.6% can be presented as good news. Our savings will certainly
earn less, but our mortgages will also cost less, although will it be enough
less to be noticed?
The housing market, artificially stimulated by the Government a decade ago, has
been stagnant for years and nothing that has been done, although not much has
been attempted, has rescued it from the doldrums.
This cut - the new rates will take effect from February 1 - probably too little
too late, should mean on a repayment mortgage the monthly repayment on a
#30,000 loan comes down by #4.01, and on a #60,000 loan by #8.93. Add the
Budget tax changes and there will be more money in people's pockets.
The building societies were not slow to react to the cut. A welcome Christmas
present for new and existing mortgage customers and good news for the housing
market, was how Abbey National described the news.
Then came the inevitable cacophony of agreement and dissent. The Building
Employers Confederation, while welcoming the cut, said it would have ``little
impact on the construction industry'' now back in serious recession.
The Institute of Directors said there was room for further reductions. This was
what was needed to help the economy, but business looked forward to further
reductions.
The British Chambers of Commerce, which welcomed the cut, said there had been
scope for a 0.5% reduction, while the Royal Bank of Scotland, which cut its
base rate by 0.25%, looked forward to a further reduction in the first quarter
of next year.
If ever a politician was deaved with advice, solicited and unsolicited, it is
the Chancellor. ``If I listened to all the short-term advice I get day by day,
I would have blown this recovery off course a long time ago,'' he said
yesterday.
Top of the advisory heap are the so-called Wise Men, originally seven, who were
set up in the autumn of 1992 by Mr Clarke's predecessor, Mr Norman Lamont,
following the ERM debacle. It seemed a good idea for views other than those of
the Treasury's legendarily inaccurate forecasters to be available to the
Chancellor and their appointment was also a way of opening up Whitehall, part
of the Government's commitment to less secrecy.
For various reasons - people have moved to new jobs - their numbers have been
cut to three, and although Mr Clarke, the Treasury insists, will be announcing
three additional names soon to bring them up to six, he seems in no great
hurry. Being more of a pragmatist than an economist himself, he may feel he has
little need of wise men to blind him with science.
In a letter to The Times yesterday the three called for a change in interest
rates on the grounds that, if unchanged, the output in growth in 1996 was
unlikely to reach the forecast 3%. The prudent course, they said, was to move
rates downwards to ensure a revival in demand.
Was the cut part, as Downing Street's resident spin doctor was boasting
yesterday, of a ``triple whammy'' for the Government? The other two parts are
the fall of 20,400 in unemployment last month, bringing it to a
four-and-a-half-year low of 2,244,500, and that 0.6% rise in high street sales.
Or was the cut, as the Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman Malcolm Bruce said,
to be welcomed in the same manner as the arrival of an ambulance at an accident
- one was grateful to see it, but it would be preferable if it wasn't necessary?
Was the cut, as the Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown said, being made not because
the economy was strong but because it was weak?
Initially the City was lukewarm. The 0.5% cut was too small to be greeted with
a cheer, but as the realisation dawned that what the Chancellor had been
signalling at his news conference was that he now favours a little-by-little
approach, and there will be more little cuts to come, the mood improved.
Using interest rates as a tool of economic management is currently the
fashionable thing to do, and what Mr Clarke has revealed is (ignore those Hush
Puppies) he is not totally blind to fashion.
</TEXT>
