<TEXT>
Alexander C D Small, school master and climber; born September 6, 1909, died
December 9, 1995
AT a glance, the frail, balding figure with that distinctive, awkward gait
might have passed, especially in later years, as one of life's victims. Alex
Small, however, was diminished only in name.
His eye was a hawk's, his intellect bright and far-reaching, and, though
stricken by poliomyelitis in his Springburn, Glasgow, childhood, the slight
physique had known exertions and triumphs not experienced by the less tenacious.
The aquiline look of Alexander Cunninghame Douglas Small, a former president of
the Scottish Mountaineering Club who died aged 86 in Crieff, Perthshire, on
Saturday after a lengthy illness, was all flannel.
It would have rattled a few miscreants at Tarbet or Kirkintilloch's Oxgang
primary schools where he was successively head teacher, but to friends the
glint in his eyes was a gleam.
An inveterate raconteur, Alex liked a dram and a laugh and many he inspired
among a wide hill fraternity with his inimitable, conspirational wit. He had
the warmest (most enduring) handshake I knew and a supernatural recall of
personal fact or foible you had so casually and long-since disclosed.
Quality memory, love of language, and a meticulous style made Alex Small the
right stuff for his term (1976-87) as general editor of what many still feel
were the SMC's best district climbing guides.
Despite a partly wasted thigh, Alex was no climbing slouch himself and like Tom
Weir (coincidentally reared in the same Adamswell Street tenements) heralded
the postwar working-class assault on the traditionally middle-class SMC. Sadly,
the club remainded misogynist.
Weir recalls his first meeting with Small near the Slack Dhu crag in the
Campsies. Climbs then for the impecunious had to be within city walking
distance: ``There a group of Creag Dhu climbers sitting around a fair. I
spotted a slim stranger. He had a sketching pad with him even then in 1932.''
Small sketched and painted in water colours all his adult life and after
retiral to Hollybush Road, Crieff, in 1974 often sold his works.
He climbed with the best of his era, including the similarly slight and balding
J H B Bell, whom W H Murray famously recalled making breakfast for his party in
the CIC hut on Ben Nevis: ``Porridge, sausage and kippers were all stirred into
one pot. As a practical chemist, he was imbued with the truth that a meal was a
fuel-intake, therefore, its separation into courses was an auld wife's nicety,
and not for climbers.''
Small's most memorable rock climb, of course, was as one of the redoubtable
trio (the others, salesman Hamish Hamilton and engineer Alex Anderson) who in
1936 made the first ascent of Agag's Groove on Buachaille Etive Mor in Glencoe.
It is reputedly Scotland's most popular rock climb. Alex once told me his
abiding memory of the 300ft route is that he set foot on it, ``resolutely
feart''.
Despite his physical handicap and background, Small gained a scholarship to
Allan Glen's School and largely self-financed his way through Glasgow
University, working with GEC installing the first sound systems in city cinemas.
His later ice and rock climbs were achieved after a long regime of self-imposed
prolonged walks aimed at overcoming his disability. Alex's wife Celia died in
1984. He leaves two sons, Hamish, a landscape gardener and wood carver in
Kinlochleven, and Drummond, a business consultant in Kilmaurs. The funeral is
to Perth Crematorium at 2.30pm tomorrow.
Appreciation
by ALAN THOMSON
</TEXT>
