<HEADLINE>Kluivert double takes Holland into Euro finals Dutchmen prove touch too masterful for Irish</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897246</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JACK the lad's reign looks over and done. The Irish Geordie's glorious decade
ended in defeat and failure to qualify for the European Championship finals at
Anfield last night, but his ageing side gave him their best shot in a finale to
an era that was memorable in its own right.
Paddy's Army didn't quite do enough to take the fairytale into extra-time but,
when Charlton sits down and decides his future, he won't have any trouble
recalling a marvellous past.
Nor could he complain about the way his men tried to give him another chance to
terrorise the elite in England next year with the up-and-at-'em football that
may not be the choice of the purists but does provide a bit of contrast at this
level.
The chances of it succeeding against the precocious young stars of Holland in
this play-off were always slim but the Dutch lived a little dangerously in the
second-half when they were only one goal to the good and the old Irish danders
were up.
They were never seriously in danger of losing but it was only in the last
minute that they scored the second goal which finally dumped their opponents.
Their lithe, brilliant young striker, Patrick Kluivert, did the damage on both
occasions.
In the end, they were the team that went through to the finals but, if the
Irish team will be missed a little, their fans will be missed a lot.
They were still singing in grand style as their weary players tropped off stage.
Charlton, exasperated at being asked the inevitable question, replied: ``For
the millionth time, I am going to speak to people after the New Year and then
see what to do.
``Holland are a great team and deserved to win. We have no complaints.
``I was disappointed with the result and our performance, but Holland could
even go on to win the championship.
``We have a lot of problems and a lot of work to do.''
Dutch coach Gws Hiddink said: ``The two goals came as the result of the way we
tried to play.
``I would like to praise the Irish for their high performance of
sportsmanship.''
Dennis Bergkamp said: ``It was a good game, people enjoyed it, and the Irish
and Dutch fans are all singing - that's what it's all about.
``In the end we made it look easy, but we had to work hard for it.''
There was a fantastic atmosphere inside the ground long before the teams
appeared, with the orange favours of the Dutch presenting a splendid contrast
to the green of the Irish.
The din was such that the singing drowned out the pre-match music, although the
Irish fans, in particular, were in such good voice that they were worth
listening to themselves.
The Irish contingent did not take kindly to a blatant dive inside their team's
area but they were hushed when a pass from Bergkamp found Davids and his shot
was parried by Alan Kelly.
They were alarmed further when Bergkamp hit a tremendous effort from the edge
of the box that struck a post with the keeper beaten.
The Irish hit back with a fine move involving McGrath, Townsend, and Phelan
before the cross came over which Aldridge could not get any power behind.
The Republic were going through a good spell and Sheridan might have done
better than shoot wide, admittedly from a distance. The need to take these
chances was hammered home painfully a minute later when the Dutch took the lead
with a brilliant piece of football.
Seedorf started it with a magnificent pass to Davids, whose quick touch inside
found Kluivert, and he sent a left-foot shot out of Kelly's reach.
The Irish went after an equaliser with a will in the minutes before half-time
but Townsend was hurt in a clash with Seedorf and looked in serious bother.
Townsend, somewhat surprisingly, was in place for the second half but did not
look at all comfortable. Indeed, five minutes into the period, he had to give
up the struggle and was replaced by Jason McAteer.
Nine minutes later, the Dutch replaced Bergkamp, who was limping slightly, with
Johan de Kock and continued to stand firm as the Republic forced the pace.
There was a real escape for the Republic, however, when Kluivert rose to head a
cross from Helder and saw it crash off the bar to Davids, whose fierce shot hit
McGrath and then was cleared.
When Sheridan gave the ball away to Kluivert, the Dutch seemed sure to go two
up. The striker laid the ball in front of Seedorf but his shot hit a defender's
foot and went over the bar.
With 16 minutes left Charlton tried another ploy, pushing on Alan Kernaghan for
Aldridge.
Then, Dutch captain Danny Blind was booked and, as a result, misses the first
game in the finals. His team-mates missed two good chances to finish the Irish
off. First, when Kelly did well to save from Overmars, and then when he did a
good job again to block a Davids effort close in.
The closing minutes were all about Irish desperation as they tried to grab the
goal that would have kept the show on the road but, inevitably, it was Holland
who landed the killer blow, through Kluivert with just seconds remaining. This
time the curtain really did come down.
HOLLAND - Van der Sar, Reiziger, Blind, Seedorf, Bogarde, De Boer, Overmars,
Davids, Kluivert, Bergkamp, Helder. Substitutes - Winter, De Kock, Mulder,
Numan, De Goey.
REPUBLIC OF IRELAND - A Kelly, G Kelly, Irwin, Babb, McGrath, Kenna, Townsend,
Aldridge, Cascarino, Sheridan, Phelan. Substitutes - Houghton, McLoughlin,
McAteer, Kernaghan, Bonner.
Referee - V Zhuk (Belarus).
</TEXT>
