<HEADLINE>Free and easy Dons as Miller hits a hat trick</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Graeme Smith</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Aberdeen 4, Kilmarnock 1
ABERDEEN fans proved during last season's relegation struggle that they will
turn out in large numbers in the face of adversity. Last night they proved
also
that they will turn out in numbers if the tickets are free.
They were rewarded with a resounding victory for the Dons as a result of Joe
Miller's first hat trick for the club and the first goal for Aberdeen for
#700,000 signing, Dean Windass.
Seven days earlier, with the sides level at a goal apiece, the match had to be
abandoned due to a power failure and the Dons' board decided that fans would
not have to pay for the replay, and the result was the second-biggest crowd of
the season.
Even heavy rain did not deter the support who snapped up every available
ticket
leaving the only gaps in the ground in the visitors' area.
Aberdeen dominated but when Kilmarnock pushed forward in the first half the
defence looked shaky. However, in the second half their defence was hardly
tested and they cruised to victory and three important points.
Captain Stewart McKimmie returned to the side after suspension, with Brian
Grant dropping to the bench. Also back on the bench was Theo Snelders just 24
hours after having played his first reserve match after injury.
Derek Anderson lined up for Kilmarnock in place of Tom Black who was suffering
from tonsillitis.
In four minutes, Bernard crossed a great ball to Billy Dodds as he advanced on
the goal, but the striker failed to control it and the danger was cleared.
Eight minutes later, Jess took a swift free kick which Shearer headed to
Bernard but his shot was pushed wide. From the corner by Miller, the ball was
nodded down by Irvine and keeper Lekovic only just managed to scramble clear.
However, a minute later Miller picked up a Windass pass, and after having
passed Mark Reilly unleashed a right-foot shoot from the edge of the box to
the
top left-hand corner of the net to give Aberdeen the lead.
Former Pittodrie player Bobby Connor tried a shot from outside the box after
15
minutes but it went harmlessly past, then in 18 minutes Jess back heeled to
Miller whose shot gave the keeper difficulty, and Shearer raced in to try to
score off the rebound, but Lekovic dived to force the shot wide.
Kilmarnock equalised after 21 minutes when the Aberdeen defence fell into
complete disarray. Twice the ball crossed the six-yard line untouched by any
home defender.
The first time McKimmie cleared it off the line but the ball fell to Reilly
who
sent it back in. Hendry missed completely but Wright was on hand to push it
across the line unchallenged.
Kilmarnock's joy was short-lived for in 28 minutes, Glass turned MacPherson
and
sent the ball across the Kilmarnock six-yard line from the left. The
visitor's
defence followed Aberdeen's example and it rolled through to Miller, who
blasted in his second goal to restore Aberdeen's lead.
Seven minutes into the second half, Jess fired a powerful drive from outside
the box as Aberdeen looked to extend their lead, and it deflected off a
defender but neither the protestations of the players nor a linesman's flag
could persuade referee McGilvray to award a corner.
In 57 minutes, Kilmarnock came close when Neil Whitworth headed down a
MacPherson free kick and Tom Brown, shot just over.
On the hour Aberdeen got a free kick when MacPherson fouled Glass and Shearer
got his head to the Jess cross but it skimmed over.
Two minutes later Wright was booked for a foul on Glass.
In 65 minutes Jess laid on Miller's hat trick by weaving his way past three
defenders and leaving the shot for him to drive low past Lekovic.
The keeper almost gave Aberdeen their fourth when he punched a Glass corner
towards his own goal, but Anderson cleared.
Grant replaced Dodds in 73 minutes, and with five minutes to go Miller was
replaced by Hugh Robertson. Many had left the ground content with three
Aberdeen goals but Windass made it worthwhile for those who stayed with just a
minute to go.
ABERDEEN - Watt, McKimmie, Glass, Bernard, Irvine, Smith, Miller, Shearer,
Windass, Dodds, Jess. Substitutes - Grant, Snelders, Robertson.
KILMARNOCK - Lekovic, MacPherson, Reilly, Hendry, Whitworth, Anderson,
Mitchell, Connor, Wright, Brown, Holt. Substitutes - Laughlan, Maskrey, Geddes.
Referee - J McGilvray, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
