<HEADLINE>Beware Latvia, warns Booth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WORLD CUP EXTRA
SCOTT Booth shuddered yesterday as he recalled two words which should strike
realism into Scotland's approach to the 1998 World Cup qualifying programme -
Skonto Riga.
The Latvian club side embarrassed Aberdeen in last season's UEFA Cup and now
their national team are rivals in the race to France.
But Booth, established as Scotland's No.1 striker, believes that for Craig
Brown's men being forewarned is forearmed.
Scotland have been given a 10-match qualifying programme for the 1998 finals
with Sweden, Austria, Latvia, Estonia, and Belarus barring their path.
Booth argues the hurdles drawn in Paris on Tuesday night are not unsurmountable
and the desire to prove themselves at the summit of world football will drive
on an ``unfashionable'' Scotland team.
``We qualified for five World Cup finals in a row from 1974 onwards and I
believe we became a bit blase about it,'' said Booth.
``We were taking it for granted but we missed out on America and we don't want
to do that again.
``We have made it to Euro '96, which for many of us is a career highlight so
far, but as a player you want to test yourself on a global stage and that is
the World Cup finals.''
q CHAMPIONS Brazil and host nation France have emerged among the early
favourites for the 1998 World Cup even though neither featured in Tuesday's
draw for the preliminary rounds.
Bookmakers William Hill installed Brazil as favourites at odds of 5-1, ahead of
Germany at 7-1, France at 8-1, and Italy and Spain both at 10-1.
The champions and hosts automatically qualify for the finals without playing in
the preliminaries.
q CROATIA has offered Bosnia the use of its stadiums after the two former
Yugoslav republics were grouped together alongside Slovenia in the qualifying
draw.
q TERRY Venables looks ready to accept the challenge of leading England's
daunting 1998 World Cup mission. The extension to the national coach's current
contract could be in place by the time he heads the New Year delegation to Rome
to map out the qualifying programme.
</TEXT>
