<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kendall happy to be back in the game at Sheffield</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>35</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOWARD Kendall will meet his Sheffield United players for the first time today.
The man who was instrumental in Everton's success during the 1980s took over as
Bramall Lane manager yesterday, 24 hours after the departure of Dave Bassett.
Kendall's immediate brief is to prepare United for the match at Ipswich on
Saturday, with the team second from bottom of the Endsleigh League's first
division. He has been out of the game for eight months after having left Notts
County.
``I didn't want to come back into the game with a club that was just happy to
survive. Sheffield United are an ambitious club and have an ambitious chairman,
who will allow me to manage.''
Kendall has installed a new management team with former Burnley player-coach
Adrian Heath his assistant, and Viv Busby the coach.
q CELTIC have handed their supporters a Christmas bonus by dropping prices for
Saturday's Scottish premier division clash with Falkirk to #10. Accompanied
children will pay only #4 to enter the family section at Parkhead. Managing
director Fergus McCann said: ``We want to encourage a family day at Celtic
Park.''
q EXPERIENCED striker Ken Eadie goes into hospital next week for an ankle
operation. It means the Clydebank striker will be on the sidelines over the
busy holiday programme, and not back until the end of January.
Among the games Eadie will miss is the first-division clash with Airdrie which
was postponed on Tuesday for the second time, and has been re-scheduled for
Saturday, December 23.
q ALBION Rovers striker Gordon Young has been caught in the fall-out of the
resignation of Dave Bassett as manager of Sheffield United. Young headed south
on Sunday for a week's training with the English club, but was back home by
Monday evening. Meanwhile, Albion have signed former East Stirling left-back,
Paul Friar.
q SECOND-DIVISION Bologna beat a nine-man AC Milan side 7-6 on penalties
yesterday to shock the Serie A leaders in front of their home fans and reach
the semi-finals of the Italian Cup.
Bologna, who had given away an injury-time penalty, then outgunned Milan in a
tense shoot-out - after missing their first spot-kick of the night. Regular
time had ended at 1-1 with the aggregate 2-2.
Milan played the last few minutes of extra time with just nine men after
striker Dejan Savicevic, in 91 minutes, and veteran captain Franco Baresi (116)
were both sent off.
Savicevic earlier had scored the last-minute penalty - with at least three
minutes of injury time already on the clock - after Bologna had taken the lead
in 76 minutes when a shot deflected off a Milan defender.
Milan and Bologna stayed level on penalties up to 6-6 but then defender
Francesco Coco, who scored in the first leg, hit wide and Bologna converted to
seal the victory.Bologna now play serie A sides Atalanta or Cagliari, who meet
today.
Fiorentina beat Palermo 2-1 and 3-1 on aggregate to set up a semi-final with
Inter. Serie B side Palermo had beaten holders Parma 3-0 in the first round.
</TEXT>
