<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Farry kicks out the speculation on manager's future Brown will lead Scotland in bid to reach World Cup finals</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHILE the SFA delegation should have been quietly congratulating themselves in
Paris following a World Cup draw which favoured the country's side, they found
themselves instead dealing with unfounded rumours surrounding the future of
manager, Craig Brown.
Immediately following the draw came suggestions that Brown would not be in
charge when the qualifying games commence in the autumn. But Jim Farry, SFA
chief executive, dismissed the rumours.
``Craig Brown is here,'' he said. ``He is preparing for the qualifying games
and he is happy following this draw. That should answer any questions about his
position.''
Brown, of course, wears two hats at the SFA, just as his close friend, Andy
Roxburgh, did before him. He is technical director as well as international
team manager, and Brown, with his strong coaching background, sees the less
glamourous, much less publicised role as of huge importance.
The SFA think likewise but the position of international manager is the one
seen by the footballing public as the No.1 job in the country.
Brown's position there will be re-confirmed by the SFA's international
committee when it is due for review in July.
``Craig Brown has taken the country to the finals of the European
Championship,'' said Farry. ``We could not ask for anything more from him. That
was his first mandate and he has been successful.''
Brown said: ``I have been employed by the SFA for nine years. I could not ask
for better people to work for. I am very happy and content in my job, both
jobs, in fact.''
Brown has earned the SFA around #2m by guiding his unfancied, often underrated
squad to the finals in England in the summer.
Now he has seen a draw for World Cup qualifying hand the Scots one of the
easier seeds in Sweden when England, for example, must face Italy and Northern
Ireland have Germany and Portugal in their section.
Naturally, Brown is cautious when he talks of Group 4. He is quick to stress
that Sweden finished third in the last World Cup finals, and points out that
Belarus were difficult opponents for Holland during the just completed European
Championship qualifying games.
``We lost to Sweden in Stockholm just last month,'' said Brown. ``But there is
no doubt that this is the kind of group we can be happy with. The major problem
will be arranging the fixtures because so many of our opponents have shutdowns
in the winter months, and they will not want to play us then.''
Brown will travel with Farry to Vienna next month and work out the dates for
the qualifying games.
He will take the team to play Denmark in March, will oversee the under-21
side's campaign in Europe, he will take the full squad to the USA for warm-up
games in May, and he will take them to the finals in England in June.
Brown is in charge. That is official. He will remain in charge for the World
Cup matches which now loom.
q.SWEDISH manager Tommy Svensson has labelled Scotland captain Gary McAllister
as the man who can upset his side's World Cup dream.
Scotland have been paired in a six-nation section in the qualifying process for
the 1998 finals in France, alongside Sweden, Austria, Latvia, Estonia, and
Belarus.
Now Elland Road, Leeds, will become a Group 4 spying location for managers
Svensson and Brown in the phoney-war before the campaign begins next autumn.
``I don't like picking out players from the opposition but Gary McAllister is a
play-maker of top international class,'' said Svensson of the Leeds midfielder.
``If I need a form check on him I can have a word with his new team-mate, Tomas
Brolin. Scotland look the biggest danger to us on paper but we will see what
happens.''
Only the winners of the nine European groups will automatically qualify for
France, with the best-placed runner-up.
The other eight second-placed sides face a home-and-away play-off, so Scotland
might have to cram 12 matches in between the end of the European Championships,
when the campaigns begin, and November 1997.
Scotland could do worse than face Sweden away in the first game - they went to
Stockholm in 1980, when a Gordon Strachan goal gave them victory en route to
the 1982 finals.
``I'd say we have a chance of winning the group - but Sweden are the main
dangers,'' added Brown.
``They finished third in the last World Cup after all and they will be hurting
after failing to make it to the European Championships next summer.''
Jim Farry admitted the pairings were not the most glamourous but expects full
houses at Hampden, where capacity will be cut to around 33,000 because of
building work on a new South Stand.
``It would be very nice to make it to the finals after missing out on America,
but this is quite a tough section,'' said Farry. ``All we will say is the
players and backroom staff will give it their best shot, and we hope the
Scottish nation will rally round.''
l.Latvia and Belarus have never played Scotland.
l.Latvia are ranked fifty-fourth in the world. Their club side, Skonto Riga,
beat Aberdeen in the UEFA Cup last season.
l.Belarus are ranked eighty-eighth and enter their first World Cup. ``They beat
Holland in the last Euro '96 qualifier so we under-estimate them at our
peril,'' said Brown. Belarus has a population of more than 10m.
l.Estonia, ranked 126th, were beaten home and away by Scotland in the
unsuccessful bid to reach America in 1994.
l.Austria, who faced both Irelands in the European Championship groups, lost
2-1 to Scotland in a friendly in Vienna last year.
l.Sweden beat Scotland 2-0 in a friendly in October but lost twice in the 1982
qualifying programme and a match in the 1990 finals in Italy.
</TEXT>
