<HEADLINE>Playing a hard game</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897251</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE World Cup qualifying draw was within minutes of not taking place on Tuesday
in Paris because of a diplomatic row.
It took a major gamble by FIFA's autocratic president, Joao Havelange, to face
down the French Government - and the 79-year-old Brazilian won.
If Havelange had lost, the draw - being beamed world-wide - would have been
postponed, until early next year, and would have taken place outside France.
The problem arose when visas for Nigerian delegates bound for Paris were
refused following the row over the execution of nine civil-rights activists in
that country. Part of the sanctions agreed by the EU, said the French.
Havelange - who has ruled FIFA for 21 years - demanded that the government
respect the accord it signed in 1991, when France made its successful bid to
stage the 1998 finals, guaranteeing visas to all delegations for functions
connected with the World Cup.
All night negotiations failed to find a solution, until Havelange was given
backing from his FIFA executive to tell the French Foreign Ministry that unless
written permission for the visas was guaranteed in writing by 1600 GMT on
Tuesday - only 80 minutes before the live broadcast was due to begin - the draw
would be cancelled.
The French, already embarrassed in Europe by disruption caused by strikes -
were cornered, and they conceded only minutes before the deadline was due to
expire.
Havelange's victory also is a blow to his critics, including UEFA leader
Lennart Johansson, who is a declared candidate for the presidency in 1998, when
the Brazilian's sixth, four-year term is due to end.
However, he recently hinted that he may carry on.
Booth's warning - Page 35
</TEXT>
