<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McGhee bids to revive Wolves</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897252</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARK McGhee was yesterday appointed manager of Wolves on a
three-and-a-half-year contract.
The 38-year-old Glaswegian brings with him Colin Lee as assistant manager and
Mike Hickman as coach - his old backroom team at Leicester.
Wolves moved in quickly after thrashing out a compensation package, believed to
be worth around #750,000, after the trio walked out on the Filbert Street club
six days ago.
Promotion-chasing Leicester had ``reluctantly'' granted permission to their
Endsleigh League first-division rivals - who lie fourth-bottom - to make an
approach, and Molineux chairman Jonathan Hayward entered into immediate talks
to appoint the club's twenty-second manager in time for Saturday's Midlands
derby at home to Port Vale.
McGhee admitted he was embarrassed by the furore surrounding his departure from
Leicester after just one year there but said: ``The size of this club and the
potential are irresistible, and would be to anyone with real ambition in the
game.
``I think it's understandable there is resentment that I left at the stage I
did. It was a very difficult decision for me and, in many ways, I am a bit
embarrassed by it all because I don't think it reflects the type of person I
am.''
With a wry smile McGhee added: ``I hope to be here for more than a year! We
need two points a game to see us into the play-offs and that is championship
form for the rest of the season.
``There has got to be a bit of a turn-around for that to happen but the squad
have been under-achieving and, in recent weeks, there has been an improvement.''
The Scot made it clear he would be picking the team for Saturday's home game
with Port Vale, albeit with the advice of Bobby Downes, who was praised by the
Molineux board for his work as caretaker-manager since the resignation of
former England manager Graham Taylor 30 days ago.
McGhee said he thought Wolves lacked quality in depth and in certain areas and
said he thought their professional squad was too big. But he added: ``Like
everyone else, I am surprised they are not up at the top of the table.''
First-team coach Steve Harrison resigned yesterday but the remainder of the
Wolves backroom staff will stay on to work with the new manager.
</TEXT>
