<HEADLINE>DRINKS Bulmer earnings bubble</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897254</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S biggest cider maker, HP Bulmer, is brimful of confidence after
half-time earnings up 12% to #16m helped by the excellent summer and a rising
market share.
The profits figure is struck before a #2.1m exceptional charge for efficiency
measures which should soon begin to pay off.
Year-on-year UK cider consumption rose 15% to 109.5 million gallons, of which
Bulmer produced about 46% - just ahead of the enlarged Matthew Clark after its
acquisition of Taunton Cider.
The consolidation of the industry into two major players and three smaller
operators with around 5% each should reduce the pressure on pricing if all are
sensible, although the supermarkets still allow only wafer-thin margins for
their suppliers.
However, the company has a higher exposure to the pub trade where margins tend
to be better, and even in the off-trade it has a substantial proportion of the
branded business with Strongbow and Scrumpy Jack gaining volume. New products
such as Strongbow Ice were launched just in time to benefit from both good
weather and some pick-up in consumer spending.
Although margins did improve from 12.1% to 12.7%, they were depressed by rising
costs of both apple juice, where European concentrate rose by half, and paper
and board for packaging.
There was also pressure from the continuing development costs of the Stassen
business in Belgium. It and the Australian operations now account for a fifth
of profits.
The interim dividend has been raised 7% to 4.55p. Bulmer shares rose 3p to 498p.
</TEXT>
