<HEADLINE>Scottish hopefuls set for a real winter challenge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897255</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SWIMMING
GRAEME Smith should have little difficulty defending the 1500 metres free-style
title and staying on course for Atlanta, but fellow Scots Fraser Walker, Kerry
Martin, and Kirsty Hope face more testing examinations of their Olympic
credentials in the Uncle Ben's Winter Challenge starting in Sheffield today.
Walker is confident he can make the British team in the 200m medley, but the
Commonwealth Games bronze medallist faces stiff opposition from English pair
James Hickman, who beat him at Cumbernauld last time, and David Warren, the
defending winter champion, as well as Canadian Russell Patrick.
Success in the butterfly sprint would be an ideal confidence-booster for
Martin, a Stirling University student, in the build-up to the Olympic trials
back in Sheffield in March. She begins defence of the 50m butterfly today, but
her main objective will be the 100m.
For Hope, the Olympics may be a year too soon, but the 17-year-old former
British youth cap is one of Scotland's genuine rising talents who could make
her mark in either sprint free-style or back-stroke.
The young Scot is fortunate that the Olympic season has coincided with a
relatively easy sixth year at Dundee High School, and she will be keen to prove
her form against established internationalists Susan Rolph and Kathy Osher.
</TEXT>
