<HEADLINE>No.3 position is England's No.1 problem Crawley must take chance to settle in</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897256</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRICKET: THIRD TEST
JOHN Crawley today faces his toughest challenge yet after forcing himself back
into England's Test team.
The Lancashire batsman is fitter than ever, having lost around a stone in
weight since last winter's Ashes tour of Australia. He is quicker and more
agile in the field after a rigorous training routine.
His technique at the crease also has improved, with a heavy emphasis on playing
straight, thereby eliminating as many risks as possible.
But now he is about to be given his sternest examination so far over the five
days at Kingsmead as England and South Africa meet in the third Test. After the
rain of Centurion Park and the Mike Atherton-inspired fightback at Wanderers,
it remains 0-0 with three to play.
The 24-year-old Crawley is likely to bat at No.3 - a position again made
available by Mark Ramprakash's failure to come good when the heat is on.
After nine Test appearances, Crawley averages only 22 but he did make a
half-century at No.3 in his last Test - against West Indies less than four
months ago.
``John has worked very hard on his fitness and his fielding since last
winter,'' said manager Ray Illingworth. ``It has been a tremendous effort. And,
as a batsman, when he gets in, he's got great concentration.''
Crawley knows this is his big opportunity. ``I've got to take it,'' he said.
``There will be younger players than me coming along over the next couple of
years and I must make my mark before then.''
England cannot afford a repeat of their first-innings collapse during the
second Test when they were dismissed for a paltry 200. For it is unlikely they
can dig themselves out of that much trouble again, no matter how well Atherton
and Jack Russell are batting.
In some ways, Russell's superb form in front of the stumps - he possesses a
first-class average of 94 on the trip to date - has added to the management's
dilemma. England would love to play five bowlers - but are nervous about going
in with only five front-line batsmen.
Just a few months ago, the solution would have been to drop Russell and give
Alec Stewart the gloves. There would seem little chance of that now after
Russell's heroics alongside Atherton in Johannesburg and his subsequent
career-best 129 not out against Boland.
England were so undecided about their final XI last night that they excluded
only Ramprakash and injured fast bowler Darren Gough from a list of possible
starters and were even toying with the idea of using Mike Watkinson in his
dual-purpose role of medium-pacer and off-spinner.
The pitch, green and damp only 24 hours earlier, has now turned into a much
friendlier looking strip.
South Africa, with 13 players in Durban, also were keeping their options open
last night. A scan on fast bowler Shaun Pollock's left foot revealed no
fracture but he still faced a lengthy pre-match fitness check after complaining
of soreness during yesterday's practice. Teams:
England (from): M A Atherton, captain, A J Stewart, J P Crawley, G P Thorpe, G
A Hick, R A Smith, R C Russell, D G Cork, R K Illingworth, A R C Fraser, D E
Malcolm, M C Ilott, P J Martin, M Watkinson.
South Africa (from): A C Hudson, G Kirsten, W J Cronje, captain, D J Cullinan,
J N Rhodes, J H Kallis, B M McMillan, D J Richardson, S M Pollock, C R
Matthews, A A Donald, M W Pringle, C E Eksteen.
q ENGLAND'S women have clinched the series by desperately hanging on for a draw
in the third and final Test against India in Hyderabad. After having drawn the
first Test and winning the second by two runs, England went into the final day
chasing an unlikely target of 302. They finished on 182 for nine.
</TEXT>
