<HEADLINE>Exiles set up a clean sweep</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897258</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Exiles set themselves up for a win in the Under-21 Championship after
defeating Glasgow 20-17 at Murrayfield last night. The Exiles, having already
beaten South and Edinburgh, have now won all three of their matches and only
North and Midlands stand in the way of a clean sweep.
Exiles must now feel that they will contribute players to the national under-21
side. One obvious candidate might be their captain and stand-off Jamie McKee
who was in top form last night. McKee, with a penalty, a conversion and a
brilliant solo try, amassed half his side's points.
Exiles other top man  behind the scrum was centre Jonathan Stuart, who scored a
try, with flanker James McIntosh getting a third, converted by McKee.
Glasgow hit back from 20-3 down with a try by flanker Rob Wylie converted by
full-back Tony Greenshields who had earlier kicked a penalty, and a penalty try
award after West of Scotland's James Craig had been held back. Greenshields
converted.
Earlier in the evening at the same venue, North and Midlands scored their first
win in this season's championship when they defeated South 19-17 thanks to a
try right on full-time by right wing Jon Goldie of Glenrothes. And a deserved
win it was for North and Midlands who showed character in coming back after
trailing 17-7.
South, despite the individual contribution of stand-off Gavin Dalgleish, who
scored all his side's points with four first half penalties and a fine second
half try, rarely looked like penetrating the North defence.
North pulled back from an initial 12-0 deficit with a try by their captain and
scrum half Philip Simpson, converted by Gerry Tosh. Then No.8 Gregor Hayter
scored a try from a charged-down kick, which Tosh also converted, to set up
Goldie's big finish.
U/21 DISTRICT CHAMPIONSHIP
</TEXT>
