<HEADLINE>Leaders favour single currency</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<FLAG>BUSINESS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897259</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Leaders favour
single currency
UK business leaders are strongly in favour of a single European currency, a
survey published yesterday showed.
Nearly two-thirds (62%) thought it would be beneficial and just 11% were
against the idea, according to the survey by Andersen Consulting.
Across Europe as a whole, the proportion in favour of a single currency rose to
70%.
Among specific industries, the most enthusiastic was the banking sector, where
79% of major European businesses thought it would be beneficial.
Tomkins boost
THE stock market welcomed overnight news from Tomkins that it is to buy Gates
Corporation, a privately owned US manufacturer of power transmission belting
and hose products mainly for the motor industry. Tomkins' shares rose 7p to
269p, with analysts generally giving the deal the thumbs-up. Details are still
awaited but a price tag of just over $1000m is expected plus the assumption of
$240m of debt.
Crime pays
CHUBB Security reported higher first-half profits despite lower demand from the
financial and construction sectors, particularly in the UK. Pre-tax profits
rose 13% to #44.4m in the six months to mid-October and the interim dividend
goes up 12% to 2.6p. There was strong growth in the Asia-Pacific region and in
Australia which offset duller conditions at home. Underlying sales were up 5%.
Deputy chairman
DANIEL Melin, chairman and chief executive of Arjo Wiggins Appleton's main
shareholder, St Louis, has joined the board as a director and deputy chairman.
Bemrose buys
PRINTER Bemrose Corporation has agreed to buy Wisconsin-based Nelson Marketing
Inc for #10.03m.
Ashley post
BASHA Cohen, currently vice president at Carole Little/California Fashion
Industries, has been appointed director of design and buying for Laura Ashley.
</TEXT>
