<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Festive food for thought</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patricia Goldie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<FLAG>inside line</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897260</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT seems unlikely that the Inland Revenue will reward employers with gifts this
yuletide season for their efforts in operating the PAYE system. It is more
likely that the Inland Revenue will be asking employers if they have correctly
reported gifts provided to their employees on their P11D forms.
Unfortunately the season of goodwill does not extend to the Inland Revenue's
treatment of gifts provided to employees. A taxable benefit arises on the cost
to the employer of providing the gift, regardless of whether the gift is a
luxury Christmas hamper or a miniature Christmas pudding.
The idea of a taxable benefit arising on Christmas gifts does not appeal to the
imagination of many employers as they do not want their employees to be
burdened with an additional tax liability. Consequently many employers agree to
meet the tax liabilities on behalf of their employees by way of an annual
settlement with the Inland Revenue.
It is important that employers do consider the tax implications of Christmas
gifts as PAYE Audit would seek to charge the employer with any amounts of tax
outstanding for the last six tax years.
With self-assessment approaching and the threat of penalties for incorrect P11D
returns looming, it is now essential that employers review this area and act
accordingly.
You might agree that the Revenue stance in respect of the benefit-in-kind
implications on Christmas gifts for employees mirrors that of a certain
Christmas character whose favourite phrase was ``Bah humbug''.
The corporation tax on Christmas gifts is not so gloomy as gifts for employees
would come under the heading of staff entertaining and would not be added back
in the corporation tax computation.
For Vat purposes the employer has a requirement to account for output tax where
the gift is standard-rated and exceeds #15 (excluding Vat).
The rules relating to staff Christmas parties are more favourable than that of
Christmas gifts. The Inland Revenue has bestowed concessionary treatment on
Christmas parties.
Before November 1 this year the concession exempted from tax one Christmas
party or similar function in the year which was open to staff generally and
where the cost did not exceed #50 a head.
The result was that where an employer held two parties a year, the cost of the
second was always held to be taxable even when the total cost of both functions
did not exceed #50 a head.
As with gifts, employers often choose to settle any costs on an annual basis
with the Revenue so as to remove any tax liability from their employees.
However, on November 1, the Revenue revised its concessionary treatment from
the tax year 1995-96 on-wards and has increased the concessionary cost of the
function to #75 a head.
Another change which will be welcomed by employers is that the total cost
figure may now be divided between more than one annual event, such as a
Christmas dinner and a summer outing, provided the total cost is no more than
#75 a head.
The revised concession also clarifies the Inland Revenue's practice on the
meaning of cost per head as the total Vat-inclusive price of the function,
including any associated benefits such as accommodation or transport, divided
by the number of people attending.
The cost per head does not refer to the cost per employee but to the cost per
individual attending the function.
Therefore the moral of the story could be not to provide gifts to employees but
to have a wonderful Christmas dinner instead. Is this food for thought?
Bah humbug might describe the taxman's attitude to Christmas gifts for staff so
Patricia Goldie, tax manager at KPMG in Glasgow, has come up with some food for
thought which might restore some festive cheer
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Money Games now a big deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897261</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Olympic TV rights first went on the market, for the London Games of 1948,
the BBC signed a cheque for $3000. Contemporary reports suggest the host
broadcasters pleaded poverty, and the organising committee never cashed the
cheque.
Now the Olympics command the world's biggest TV audience, and the largest fees,
explaining why the British Olympic Association yesterday was celebrating.
The biggest international sporting television agreement in history - #1500m -
has brought long-term security and a guarantee that UK sportsmen and women will
be better prepared.
NBC has agreed to buy from the International Olympic Committee the exclusive US
broadcast and cable TV rights for the 2004 (#529m), 2006 (#409m), and 2008
(#596m) Olympics - two Summer and one Winter Games. It is the first time a deal
has been struck without the venues being known.
US income represents roughly half of what the IOC can expect in global TV fees,
laying down a marker for those bidding for rights elsewhere.
The BOA receives a share of all these funds, each country negotiating
individually with the IOC. Paul Pruszynski, the BOA treasurer, said last night:
``This means we will have a guarantee of steady income. There will now be
increased pressure, not just from us, but from other national Olympic
committees, on how the IOC divides this money and from the Olympic programme
sponsorship. (TOPS)''
Pruszynski declined to say how much the BOA receives from the IOC. ``Each
country negotiates separately, exploiting its own opportunities, so that is
commercially sensitive information,'' he insisted.
However, the BOA budget in the current four-year Olympiad is some #12m. The two
sources for that are the UK appeal, and commercial sponsorship (TV and TOPS) of
which the latter is the greater.
``This will make some of our decision-making easier, reducing uncertainty,''
add Pruszynski. ``We will receive a larger share, guaranteeing a better service
for competitors. We are already the biggest single source of funds for sports
science and sports medicine in the UK - bigger than the Sports Council.''
The new deal means NBC will screen six of the next seven Olympics. Earlier this
year they paid #470m for the Sydney Olympics, and #365m for the 2002 Winter
Games in Salt Lake City. Coverage of the 1998 Winter Games, in Japan, went to
CBS for #250m.
NBC's pre-emptive strike shuts the US door, meantime, on satellite TV. It is
likely that UK rights, negotiated as part of a European Broadcasting Union
package, will go to terrestrial channels.
Michael Payne, the IOC's director of marketing, said their primary aim is the
widest public access, rather than income. In the past they have turned down
higher offers from other broadcasters.
The first televised Olympics, Berlin in 1936, reached just 162,000 viewers.
That, and the experience of the Beeb's cheque, perhaps, explains why Avery
Brundage, octogenarian former president of the IOC, could dismiss TV's
influence at the 1956 Winter Games in Cortina, Italy: ``We in the IOC have done
well without TV for 60 years and will do so certainly for the next 60.''
When the torch-bearer at Cortina's opening ceremony tripped over a television
cable, Brundage appeared to have got it right. Even the arrival of the global
Olympics - from Tokyo in 1964, with the first satellite relay - did not bring
security, and it was still a liability as recently as 1976, when the rights
fees of $32m for Montreal did not cover broadcast costs.
Just 15 years ago the Olympic movement was on the brink of bankruptcy. When Los
Angeles staged the Games in 1984, they were the sole bidders. Since then,
however, TV, and advertising has been the Games' saviour, and 10 cities are
bidding for the 2004 Summer Olympics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
