<HEADLINE>Goldie's late try clinches it</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897262</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORTH and Midlands scored their first win in this season's Under-21
championship with a performance that produced a try advantage over South at
Murrayfield last night of three to one.
The combined districts, however, left it late and achieved their win with a
dramatic try right on full-time by their right wing Jon Goldie. The Glenrothes
wing, one of North's successes last night, took his scoring pass from full-back
Steve Newlands before diving over in the corner for the match winner.
And a deserved win it was for North and Midlands who showed character in coming
back after trailing 17-7 to a South side that definitely had its tail up.
South, despite the individual contribution of stand-off Gavin Dalgleish, who
scored all his side's points with four first half penalties and a fine second
half try, never looked like penetrating the North defence.
North pulled back from an initial 12-0 deficit with a try by their captain and
scrum half Philip Simpson, converted by stand off Gerry Tosh. But it was No.8
Gregor Hayter who turned in another impressive performance for his side and
pulled North back into the game.
The former Elgin player was finally rewarded for his efforts with a try from a
charged down kick. Tosh converted to bring North within range of South's
scoreline and to set the stage for Goldie's theatrical finish.
