<HEADLINE>A major title would be icing on cake for Monty Reflections of past year in Jamaican sun</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>32</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897263</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS the date of another new year comes into view, leading professional golfers
become inclined to reflect philosophically and project optimistically. That was
certainly the way with three players yesterday on the eve of the fifth - and
last, according to their agreement - $2.3m Johnnie Walker World Championship at
the Tryall Club, Jamaica.
For Colin Montgomerie, a further year of progress inspires hopes of even better
times. However, Ernie Els, the holder, and Nick Faldo have more mixed feelings
about 1995, principally because neither was able to live up to his own
expectations, let alone those of the game at large, notably in the four major
championships.
Having won the European order of merit for a third successive year, Montgomerie
could legitimately claim it as ``the best of eight seasons which have all been
better than the previous one and I hope a major victory will make next year the
best again'' - a void in his record he is anxious, though not desperate, to
fill.
``For some time now I've been the player highest in the world rankings not to
have won a major,'' said Montgomerie, currently fifth before he set out in
sweltering sunshine for a practice round during which he intended to try out
two new putters and two No.3 woods which he arrived with from the Callaway
factory in California.
``I've been close three times,'' Montgomerie recalled of two US Opens and this
year's USPGA, ``but I must be patient and maybe in time someone will make a
mistake or I'll make something happen at the finish for a change.''
Then he went on to try to put his ambition in perspective in an increasingly
competitive environment.
He said: ``If you are playing almost 30 tournaments a year, as I intend to do
between the European and US Tours again in 1996, it won't work to concentrate
all your thoughts and energies on just four weeks out of 52, for the pressures
are high enough as it is.''
At least Montgomerie's left wrist injury seems to be on the mend. ``Hard
massage'' and regularly squeezing an over-size squash ball are helping to
restore the strength of the ligaments between the thumb and forefinger he tore
in Hong Kong four years ago and which began the problem. He may well maintain
his record of never having finished outside the first 12 here in four outings.
Although Faldo won at Doral, that was in the first week of March and the
achievement has been all but lost sight of by, as he put it, ``nothing clicking
in the majors'' and, more recently, by the break-up of his second marriage and
his highly publicised liaison with Brenna Cepelak, a student 18 years his
junior.
Although Faldo declined all comment on his private life he did say: ``The
off-course attention has been ridiculous, but I'm not in control of that. I
just have to live my own life.''
Little wonder that Europe's Ryder Cup victory over the United States, and his
own crucial part in it, represent his fondest memories of this year.
``I know Curtis Strange bogeyed the last two holes, but I had to make the 4s
when the pressure valve was turned right up and that 93-yard wedge shot to four
feet at the last was certainly the best I've played in the circumstances. It
was an unbelievably special moment,'' Faldo remarked.
Faldo also has substantially re-armed. He has a new ball, a new driver, and new
irons adjusted for the US Tour, where the tight pin positions determine clubs
with a little more loft.
A new sense of priorities, however, is the force behind Els' thoughts on the
upcoming season, although their opinion converges in one aspect.
John Daly, the Open champion, is the only reigning major title-holder in the
field of 20 vying for the $550,000 first prize and, in obvious reference to the
absence also of Greg Norman and Nick Price, first and second in the world
rankings, Faldo remarked: ``It's a shame they are all not here, but everyone
has the right to their own schedule.''
Having 12 months ago begun with two 64s, seven under the par of the 6767-yard
course, Els went on to complete his fifth victory of 1995, the US Open
included, and two more in European tournaments and one in America this year
must have seemed like short rations by comparison. But Els believes that in
1996 the pressure of expectation on him will be considerably less.
Moreover, Els intends to compete in the tournament immediately ahead of all
four majors, which will include the Scottish Open at Carnoustie - always
assuming, of course, that a sponsor or sponsors can be found before next July,
a New Year's resolution which should commend itself somewhere.
</TEXT>
