<HEADLINE>Richardson denies rift with Lara</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897264</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WEST Indies captain Richie Richardson yesterday played down reports of a rift
between himself and Brian Lara.
Richardson was responding to a report in Tuesday's edition of the Trinidad
Guardian, in which team manager Wes Hall was quoted as saying Lara had
complained that cricket was ruining his life and that he had threatened to
retire.
Hall's comments had been made in his report to the West Indies Cricket Board of
Control and referred to incidents which occurred during this summer's tour of
England.
Hall's report reveals that Lara was upset with the lack of discipline on the
team, which he blamed on Richardson.
But Richardson said yesterday: ``I know, and you know, that a lot of what you
read in the papers is not really true.
``I have not got a problem with Brian. People have their opinions on different
things and if Brian gives his opinion about something, that does not mean
there's something between us.''
q CRICKET chiefs are to recommend that the Test and County Cricket Board extend
the powers of England chairman of selectors Ray Illingworth at their winter
meeting today.
In line with the South African system, there is a proposal to give Illingworth
the power to over-rule a county's selection of an England player if he feels
the player needs a break.
Meanwhile, moves to launch the English Cricket Board as a replacement for the
TCCB has been put back a few months after the TCCB had set an initial deadline
of January 1, 1996 for its inception.
However, the meeting is likely to introduce some changes to the domestic game
and the county championship could see some fine tuning.
The championship is almost certain to remain an 18-team structure, as opposed
to a two-division competition many had called for.
Other items under consideration:
l Benson and Hedges Cup: recommendation to reduce from 55 to 50 overs with just
one interval between innings.
l Heavy rollers to be used during matches.
l Possibility of county championship losing its `Sunday sandwich' from 1997 by
starting on Wednesdays and ending on Saturdays.
CRICKET ROUND-UP
