<TEXT>
HOW about this for the impact professionalism is having on players' lives. John
Manson, newly married, had arranged with his employers not to work any overtime.
He was banking on the money he would receive as a member of the international
squad. Having been sent off, he has lost that now. Overtime is back on the
agenda. Makes you think, doesn't it? Ain't funny.
q THE Diary understands that Scotland is on the verge of a registration scheme
for rugby players. The Scottish Rugby Clubs' Association was asked in by the
SRU recently, and had a ``very sympathetic hearing and a constructive
discussion,'' according to Alan Irons, of Cartha Queen's Park, whose original
idea sparked the formation of the association. Representatives of the 46 clubs
met again last night.
The Association's members believe that provinces should play in Europe, and
that clubs who nurture young talent should register young players and be paid
when those players leave them to join bigger clubs. And so say all of us. The
SRU, apparently, aren't against the idea either.
q KENNY Logan, our very own columnist and friend of Kirsty Young, had a hard
time at the West of Scotland dinner where he was a speaker on Saturday night.
Introduced by Sean Lineen as a man ``with a finger in many parts of the
media,'' he had to suffer one of those balloons in the audience who knew all of
the punch lines, and wished to demonstrate that knowledge to the assembled
masses.
To his eternal credit Logan ploughed on until the end. Jokes that were ruined
were ``David Sole can't be here tonight because . . .'' to be interrupted by
``he's babysitting . . . ,'' and the famous one about the bloke going hunting
and having a hard time from a great big grizzly bear. Which is, by the way, a
belter. Logan alluded to having had some help in writing his speech, possibly
from Kirsty herself. ``That's my script writer sacked.'' said Logan.
The hassle, I'm afraid, is the price of being famous, Kenny, and you'll just
have to find a way to live with it. This is Scotland, whose people, for some
reason, don't like superstars.
q GHK will not take action, but one of the first blows suffered by wing forward
Andy Ness at Glasgow Southern on Saturday was, allege some of the GHK players,
a head butt from tough New Zealand wing forward Glen Remnant. The two players
were having a bit of a ding dong game.
During the second half, Ness left the field on a stretcher and later spent time
in hospital resulting from a Remnant tackle which damaged his neck.
I understand that Ness is now to meet with GHK director of rugby Andy Little.
``I am thinking of retiring now,'' said Ness, who has had a career littered
with injuries.
``There is more to life than rugby and that game put me off. I have to think of
my job, which I like, and I don't think you can have a job and play top level
rugby any more.'' Ness refused to confirm that he was butted, saying it was a
misunderstanding.
Little regrets that Ness is contemplating retirement. ``He's an excellent bloke
and it would be sad if that is what he is going to do.'' he said. ``I really
hope to talk him out of it.''
Ness was told he would require more x-rays after his first batch at the
hospital. The player took it he was a goner, a fair thought given the lack of
movement in his arm. What was meant was that the pictures hadn't come out and
needed retaken. He should be fine.
q SCOTTISH Rugby Magazine has an article this month all about what it calls the
``Natural Ball Killers,'' in other words Messrs Turnbull of Hawick, Ireland of
Stirling County, and McIvor of Edinburgh Accies. The three are depicted in '60s
style suits, just like the film. Veritas is the only possible defence.
q AND finally, congratulations to all at Stirling County, who are in receipt of
the Sports Diary's newly constituted No Foreigners award. The NF award is given
to teams that haven't fielded foreigners to get success in the Premier Leagues.
Stirling are the only team in the first division who can accept this award by
fielding no imports. And there they are going for the title, too.
</TEXT>
