<TEXT>
CURLING
IT TOOK a measure after an extra end, but eventually Scotland's women's team
kept their unbeaten record yesterday at the European Curling Championships in
Grindelwald, Switzerland, beating Norway by 8-7.
Kirsty Hay's team finished on top of their round-robin section with five
victories, and will face either Denmark or Russia in the quarter-finals.
Earlier, Hammy McMillan concluded his round-robin programme with an 8-2 win
over a three-man Finnish team for a 4-1 record and second place in their
section behind Norway. It pits the Scots against the England team of Alistair
Burns in today's quarters.
Against Norway, Hay began with two singles. Dordi Nordby brought Norway back
with a 2 at the third, but Hay drew with her last stone at the fourth for 3
only for Norway to score a 3 at the fifth to level it up again.
When Norway stole a single at the eighth, they led for the first time at 8-7
and, although trailing, Scotland blanked the ninth end to retain last-stone
advantage. They could not score the two shots needed for outright victory and
the teams went into an extra end. Edith Loudon was able to hide her second
stone behind guards to put Scotland in a strong position, although eventually a
measure was required.
With two players injured, Finland could field only three men to face Hammy
McMillan, who made short work of this game, scoring 2 at the first with a good
draw. He followed this up with a single at the fourth end and a 3 at the sixth
when he followed a clearing hit with a well-judged draw.
Scotland stole a 2 in the seventh and, after blanking the eighth end, Finland
conceded. Fifth-round results:
