<HEADLINE>Newtonmore have last chance to stop leaders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MacLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897267</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHINTY
THE last day of action before the fortnight-long festive break is marked with
derby matches in the premier league.
At Newtonmore, the home side will try to halt Kingussie's seemingly inevitable
charge towards the national league title.
Newtonmore have had a string of high-scoring wins against first-division sides
in cup competition, a draw with Fort William, and then a win against
Glenurquhart last weekend. They fancy their chances, for all that they lost 7-3
when the clubs first met in mid-October.
The Oban sides, unusually, are fighting out the bottom two places. Camanachd
have had a dismal first half of the season. They play Celtic, having captured
three of their players recently and secured Dougie MacIntyre's future with the
club. Celtic have by far the poorest strike rate in the league, with just five
goals in seven matches.
Glasgow Mid Argyll go to Inveraray, with whom they are contesting third place.
Inveraray will have Garry MacPherson back after suspension.
Fort William, chasing Kingussie, visit Glenurquhart, for whom striker Jamie
Bell could return after a broken arm.
Unbeaten at halfway, Kyles should continue towards the play-off for a place in
the league next season. They lead south division one by six points.
</TEXT>
