<HEADLINE>Oban mart to expand</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897268</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOARING numbers at Oban Livestock Centre have sparked expansion plans at the
#1m facility, opened just over a year ago by the Princess Royal.
There are also proposals to establish a visitor centre at the mart during the
quieter months, telling the story of West Highland agriculture to the hundreds
of thousands of tourists attracted to the area each year.
The plans have been prompted by a series of massive sales in the autumn when
numbers could not be accommodated within the complex itself.
``We are very, very happy with what's happening,'' said centre chairman Mull
farmer Donald MacGillivray.
Costings are now being taken for a covered extension accommodating an extra
3000 sheep along with penning elsewhere for a further 2000.
Mr MacGillivray said he was optimistic the mart would have the increased
capacity in place by next autumn's sales.
Stephen Aitken, managing director of operator Argyll Auction Company, said last
year's record of 6000 sheep on one sale day had been almost doubled to 11,000
this year, leading to temporary gates having to be erected and penning in the
market yard itself.
``So far, the market has gone beyond anyone's expectations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
