<HEADLINE>Clubs uneasy with SRU plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>34</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897269</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE likelihood of a challenge to the SRU's plan for districts, and not clubs,
to represent Scotland in next season's European competition appeared to move a
step closer last night after a meeting of the country's top 10 clubs.
The meeting, at Meggetland, agreed to seek further details from the Union on
the cash implications of European competition and, according to the clubs'
spokesman, Boroughmuir vice-president Ronnie Smith, there was general unease
about what he claimed had been the lack of consultation before the Union had
sent out its proposals at the weekend.
``They say they have consulted widely but club representatives here tonight are
very disturbed about what they see as lack of consultation.
``There is little doubt that we have the necessary six clubs in favour of club
participation that would mean an extraordinary meeting of the Union, but we
would prefer to take the issue forward, not by confrontation, but by means of a
forum for all clubs at which the arguments in favour of clubs participating
could be properly aired.
``For instance, we are not saying that all the money from the European Cup
should go just to the participating clubs,'' Smith said.
It seems that last night's meeting was split along 6-4 lines, with Hawick,
Gala, Jed-Forest and, perhaps, Heriot's FP, backing the SRU plan.
Against a backdrop of a threatened referees' boycott of Edinburgh Academicals
following assistant coach David Sole's ``tantamount to cheating'' comments
about referee Colin Henderson, the Edinburgh Referees' Society last night
agreed to take no action until the outcome of today's SRU disciplinary hearing
is known.
Internationl referee Ray Megson has said that he will not referee Academicals
until the matter is resolved.
</TEXT>
