<HEADLINE>Worried farmers ask police to cultivate the rural grasses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>VICTOR ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897271</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S countryside needs more police informers to stem the rising tide of
rural crime, a national farming conference in London heard yesterday.
Intelligence gathering and communications were two of the major weapons that
the police had against crime but this was more difficult to achieve in rural
areas, according to Superintendant Keith Akerman of Hampshire Constabulary.
He said the police were actively looking to recruit informants on rural crime.
This system had worked particularly well in urban burglary and drugs related
cases.
``Unless the public at large are prepared to become involved in this we might
as well pack up and go home,'' he told delegates to the conference on the
prevention and cure of rural crime staged by the English National Farmers Union.
Continuing the self help theme, he said that there was also an acute shortage
of special constables in rural areas. Many of those who did volunteer were not
the right people for the job and of those who were appointed few wanted to
police their own areas for fear of reprisals.
Few stayed very long either as patrolling a rural beat was not attractive to
them. They preferred an urban environment and the excitement of answering 999
emergency calls.
But the real bugbear of rural crime was the demand for scarce police facilities
in urban areas where most crimes were carried out.
Allied to this were the Home Office objectives which demanded a certain crime
clear-up rate.
``We have got to put police officers where the demand is. The public demands
that we do,'' said Superintendant Akerman.
In terms of sheer cost effectiveness, many rural police forces might be
eliminated but chief constables realised they had a duty to cover these areas.
This meant some police houses were being sold to realise assets and redirect
them. Some beats were also being cut or amalgamated.
Volunteers were being used to man some police stations. This was a
revolutionary concept but it was catching on, he said.
Outlining future strategy, he said the police were using a focused approach to
target crime and criminals and adopting more technology to help. More emphasis
was being put on police visibility but this needed the back-up of more
information to be effective.
Co-operation with local councils was being increased but the general public
also had to become more involved. Finally, he urged the media to help reduce
the fear of crime in their reporting. Tony Pexton, deputy president of the NFU
said he hoped the union would give a push to Farm Watch scheme.
``It's making people aware that they can be part of the solution. If we can get
that as part and parcel of some of the action as far as rural crime is
concerned, I think we will have made some progress.''
</TEXT>
