<TEXT>
Volleyball
MIZUNO Malory Lewisham, the English men's champions, have established a new
unbeaten record in British volleyball.
A victory over second-division Birmingham in the English Cup gave them their
seventy-ninth successive league and cup win - beating the previous record set
by Speedway Rucanor 10 years ago. Malory's last defeat was away to Liverpool
two-and-a-half years ago.
Showjumping
THREE of Britain's top showjumpers are looking for an early Christmas present
as they go into the Olympia international championships, starting in London
today.
Michael and John Whitaker, and national team-mate Nick Skelton, will not be
having their sponsorship contracts with Everest renewed when their current
deals expire at the end of the month. And although the company's decision to
end all links with a sport they have supported for 28 years has been known
since the start of the year, no new sponsors have come forward.
That means a trio of riders - who among them have picked up around #1m in
winnings this year and occupy the top positions in the domestic rankings - face
an uncertain Olympic year.
Tennis
SCOTLAND'S Alan Mackin continued his preparation for next week's Orange Bowl
world junior championship, when he reached the quarter-finals of the Sunshine
Cup in Florida.
The 14-year-old from Paisley received a walk-over from Russian Igor Lysoew then
beat Clint Skelwood (USA) 6-1, 6-1, Markus Polessnig (Austria) 7-6, 3-6, 7-6,
and Diego De Cecchis (Italy) 6-2, 6-3, before going down 6-4, 6-1 to Latvia's
Raimond Sproga in the last eight.
In the doubles event, Mackin and Cheshire's Mark Hilton lost 6-0, 5-7, 7-5 to
Canadian pair Paul Esmail and Darren Shaw in the first round.
Scottish No.1 Michele Mair beat Sarah Stanley 6-2, 6-4 before going down 6-2,
2-6, 6-4 to Nicole Oomens in the second qualifying round for the $25,000
Women's Challenger event in Nuriootpa, South Australia.
SPANISH officials are investigating whether Arantxa Sanchez Vicario has been
violating the country's tax laws by declaring herself a resident of the fiscal
paradise state of Andorra.
Tax officials were looking into Sanchez Vicario's case on the basis that she
appeared to violate two requirements of people declaring themselves
non-residents, namely that they must spend 183 days each year in another
country and that their native country should not be the centre for their
business operations.
Sanchez Vicario claimed her situation was perfectly legal. She said that like
other sporting figures, she paid taxes in every country where she takes part in
a tournament.
FORMER world No.1 Stefan Edberg has decided against playing in next year's
Olympics in Atlanta.
``Stefan told me he wants to give the younger Swedish players a chance to
qualify for Atlanta,'' said Davis Cup captain Carl-Axel Hageskog.
Edberg won the singles' title at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics when tennis was
an unofficial sport.
