<HEADLINE>De Beers' sales sparkle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897273</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROUGH diamond sales by De Beers' Central Selling Organisation rose 6.6% to
$4530m in 1995 from $4250m the previous year, De Beers said yesterday.
The group, which handles about threequarters of world rough diamond sales, said
figures reflected increased confidence and demand from retail markets.
Retail demand remained encouraging and current world trends indicated the
diamond jewellery market is up compared with 1994, the South African-based De
Beers said in a statement.
De Beers said its Central Selling Organisation (CSO) and its Russian partners
are still negotiating a vital marketing deal on Russian gems, with meetings
scheduled in Moscow next week. Both parties had agreed not to comment on the
talks.
The current deal, by which Russia sells 95% of its rough gems through the
London-based CSO, expires on December 31.
De Beers wanted to renegotiate the deal to keep a handle on Russian output,
which accounts for a quarter of the world total, and prevent the leakage on to
the market of hundreds of millions of dollars worth of small stockpiled Russian
stones.
Second-half sales by the CSO were a record $1990m against $1670m in the second
half of 1994. The CSO said the second-half performance was better than
expected, particularly in diamonds over two carats.
The statement said expectations for the Christmas sales season were good and,
if economic conditions remained as currently forecast, prospects for continued
growth in the retail sector were favourable.
Reports from cutting centres indicated a recent average price increase of 5%
for gem diamonds of two carats and larger had been ``well accepted and polished
prices in these catgories are firm''.
</TEXT>
