<HEADLINE>Volume and quality unlock doors</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Darren rodger</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897274</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Darren Rodger asks why homeowners should place their trust in professional
salesmen
IT'S the era of the specialist when it comes to selling houses, and in a
difficult market-place for estate agents it's quality that is the key, as the
Robb Agency can attest.
``We set our stall out on the basis of quality: gimmicks and freebies are
interesting but there's no substitute for quality these days,'' said managing
director Iain Robb.
``If you look at it in terms of the retail trade, we are the M&amp;S of estate
agents. We want to provide volume with quality because I believe that is what
they do.
``That's our company challenge to all personnel: our brief is to try to make
every single person we come into contact with believe that they are the only
person we are dealing with that day, whether buying, selling, or arranging
their mortgage. That's the challenge.''
The Robb Agency believes that in the current climate, unless an estate agency
can bring a property to the market quickly and efficiently, and promote it in
its target market - which these days is UK-wide - then it will not do well.
Consequently the Robb Agency combines traditional skills with the latest in new
technology.
``We believe in a people system rather than a purely computer system - which I
think is different. Basically we have people selling to people, and it works.
But we have complemented them with an ability to promote houses nationally via
a large number of blue-chip companies and their personnel and relocation
departments.
``We are, for example, a member of the Glasgow Association of Estate Agents;
sole agents for Glasgow for PHH Relocation, which is the world's largest
relocation organisation; and we are also appointed by Black Horse relocation
which is one of the UK market leaders.
``So it's really about promoting a house locally and nationally.
``We know where the target market is and instead of waiting for potential
buyers to come to us, we take the stock to them.''
It's known in the trade as proactive selling and that, as far as Iain Robb is
concerned, is the crux. He dismisses the efforts of the legal fraternity to
break into the house-sale sector as ``the supermaket approach''.
``I think a lot of house sellers are wrongly advised. The nineties, without
question, is the era of the specialist and we see ourselves as specialist house
sellers. We are not involved in conveyancing or criminal or legal defence work,
or whatever, we are house sales people.''
Iain Robb likened the situation to the sale of an expensive yacht or car - a
Daimler or Porsche. Anyone serious about selling one would go to a proper
broker or salesman; they wouldn't ask their lawyer.
``The supermarket approach is reactive selling. The buyer has got to go in and
discover it and pick it off the shelf. Nobody tells you about it. That's the
difference between reactive and proactive selling.''
As for anyone tempted to sell for themselves, Iain Robb concedes that if he
weren't    an estate agent he would    probably try to sell his house himself,
but adds: ``Being an estate agent gives me an insight into how haphazard
selling for yourself can be. It really is a shot in the dark and you are
relying on a tremendous amount of luck that the right person is out there at
the right time.''
An estate agent, on the other hand, has specialist knowledge, computer records
built up over many years, with people on the mailing   list waiting for a
particular property.
``It has taken us a long time to develop these systems and there's no way we
can rely on luck in professional selling.''
Iain Robb said he was proud of the sales culture within his company.
``Our organisation focuses on selling the customer's property at the best
possible price and we have a sales culture which says that we are hungrier than
our rivals.''
</TEXT>
