<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Professional ways pay dividends</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Darren rodger</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897275</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEFORE the estate agent came on the scene the public had no-one to turn to but
their family solicitor who would do little more than place an advertisement in
the press and await any calls, according to Mark Adams of G&amp;S Properties.
``There was no follow through, no detailed schedules, no valuation advice, no
local office, no tele-sales, no mailing systems, no separate negotiators, no
window displays, no feature advertising, no competition, and no late or weekend
opening - and little has changed in 30 years. In general, solicitors' offices
do not have professional sales people.''
Property however, like all commodities, needs to be professionally marketed,
and in the mid sixties the West of Scotland saw the birth of estate agents who
introduced some of the above services in response to demands from vendors who
increasingly wanted their properties sold into a competitive market, not lifted
off the shelf at fixed prices.
G&amp;S Properties, a member of the Glasgow Association of Estate Agents, offers a
sales-orientated, family-run business with over 25 years' experience.
One of the most important tasks of any good agent is to operate an effective
telephone sales system where tele-sales staff, every night of the week and on
weekends, glean information about the market by speaking with buyers, updating
their requirements into the system and letting them know of the latest
properties on their company's register that week, thus moving the property
though the market.
Mark Adams believes presentation is important to bring out       the best
features of the property, and agents have a high standard    of presentation,
often competing with each other with original, informative, high-quality
material all set up by the valuer and staff    in the local office handling the
sale.
``The purchaser also needs advice on their own property. For example, how
marketable is it; how fast will it sell; what price is it likely to bring; does
the agent have anyone on their books who may be suitable?
``We have a fully computerised data information system and we are open the
longest hours: from 9am to 9pm Monday to Friday, from 10am to 4pm Saturday and
Sunday, and a 24-hour answering serice.
``Our directors are also happy to provide personal advice seven days a week
from 7am to 10pm.''
The agency G&amp;S provides a full-colour schedule presentation, including internal
photographs, maps, and floor plans; free accompanied viewings; no sale no fee;
full mortgage advice; and a full property management service.
</TEXT>
