<HEADLINE>Russia's caMPAIGNERS master the POLITICAL art of mudslinging</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Miller and Tom Zaitsev</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897276</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n THE mind-boggling multitude of parties competing for seats in the parliament
aside, the Russian election campaign is becoming increasingly sophisticated:
candidates are mastering the art of mudslinging.
``We will tell scum that they are scum, liars that they are liars and fools
that they are fools,'' Boris Fyodorov, former Finance Minister, now leader of
the Forward Russia movement, declares in a television campaign slot, echoing
many of the political themes associated with Berlusconi's Forza Italia.
Not surprisingly, the list of bad guys compiled by Forward Russia includes most
of its rivals in the campaign.
``If you cannot get things done, get away,'' thunders Fyodorov at a cardboard
cutout of a smiling Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, head of Our House is
Russia. Chernomyrdin has himself jumped on the mudslinging bandwagon: at a
meeting with Russia's media chiefs he urged them to keep unsavoury candidates
off the air. ``We should not be under the thumbs of fools,'' he said, adding
that many seeking office were ``odious'' or ``simply insane''.
Yuri Vedeneyev, a leading lawyer and member of the election watchdog committee,
assessed Chernomyrdin's remarks as ``impermissible'' for a participant in the
election process, especially for one holding such a high position.
``Politicians of his stature should not stoop to making indecent remarks about
fellow candidates. It shows that our electoral process is far from perfect
yet.''
Many campaign tactics are aimed at discrediting opponents, not promoting a
party's own cause. Forward Russia has erected a large billboard on a major
Moscow highway which reads: ``Fifty million victims of the civil war,
collectivisation and repression would not vote for Zyuganov,'' in a reference
to Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Communist Party, one of the campaign
front-runners.
The perpetual troublemaker Vladimir Zhirinovsky, head of the Liberal Democratic
Party, confident that his party will grab one third of the seats in the Duma,
is looking further ahead - he wants the presidency for himself.
What about the presidential prospects of General Alexander Lebed, widely
considered a serious threat to Zhirinovsky's hold on the nationalist vote? ``He
would be better entrusted with running a large prison than a super-power,''
snaps Zhirinovsky.
He is by no means alone in his derogatory attitude to rivals. Konstantin
Borovoy, head of the Party of Economic Freedom, took the liveliest approach of
all the candidates participating in a televised campaign. Borovoy is filmed in
front of major Moscow landmarks, pointing out the cultural benefits which come
from private enterprise. He expresses hope, in a dig at Prime Minister
Chernomyrdin, that Moscow's White House, seat of the federal government, will
not become someone's private property. In the background, viewers can hear
voice-overs of ordinary Russian people singing politically suggestive
``chastushki'', or limericks, composed by Borovoy's campaigners.
These rhyming folk songs, often quite earthy, were collected from all over the
country and contained unflattering references to Borovoy's competitors.
``It was almost a bit too lively, bordering on indecent,'' commented Alexei
Pushkov, a TV company public relations director. Court chairman Anatoly
Vengerov was more rigorous, saying that ``Borovoy's chastushki'' violated the
civil code, which prohibits the distortion or use of a person's name in a form
that injures his honour, dignity or professional reputation.
Legal action, however, did not ensue: with hardly a candidate not guilty of the
offence, setting a precedent for further cases could have ground the election
to a halt.
Meanwhile, the print media has picked up the negative tone of much of the
campaigning. On its front page, a popular weekly featured a family sitting
around a TV set wearing gas masks. ``Danger: party political broadcast,'' the
caption reads.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000123</DOCNO>
