<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fall and rise of communism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>John Miller and Tom Zaitsev</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897277</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As Russians prepare to go to the polls in the parliamentary elections, John
Miller and Tom Zaitsev look at the issues and campaign tactics
LANGUISHING in a sanatorium outside Moscow where he is recovering from his
heart attack, President Boris Yeltsin cannot be the happiest of men. For this
weekend Russia holds its first routine elections, putting the country's
fledgling democracy to the test and dictating the pattern of Russian politics
for the next six months.
And all the signs indicate that the once-reviled communists and their allies
will emerge as the strongest political group in the State Duma, the lower
house, bent on doing their best to put the brake on Yeltsin's reforms if not on
turning back the clock to the bad old days of the USSR.
President Yeltsin has only himself to blame for the expected strong vote for
his opposition - communists as well as the nationalist right - who have made it
clear they will try to make life difficult for him if and when he gets back to
serious work in the Kremlin.
In the first post-communist parliamentary elections in 1993 the Kremlin, the
country's liberal intelligentsia, and the West were shaken by the success of
Vladimir Zhirinovsky's misleadingly named ultra-nationalist Liberal Democratic
Party, which promised to resolve the country's problems painlessly.
The big vote for Zhirinovsky was a protest against Yeltsin's economic policies
which had given rise to rapid inflation and unemployment. More than that, it
was a vote against the political establishment as a whole, against all the
``respectable'' political parties. But another reason was the absence of a
coherent political centre which would have also embraced a moderate and
organised opposition.
Two years on, Russia's disenchanted electorate is having to choose from a
bewildering array of 43 parties and blocs. For the 450 seats - half filled by
proportional representation from national party lists, half contested as
Westminster-style single-member constituencies - there are about 2700
candidates, on average 20 in each constituency.
Seven, perhaps eight, groups have emerged as the main contenders competing for
the votes of a population struggling to come to terms with the loss of both a
political and an economic system, as well as the end of an empire, and now
gripped by gloom and, especially in the case of the elderly, weary of declining
living standards.
Russia's opinion surveys are not especially reliable but they are all insisting
that Russia's Communist Party has made a comeback and that by promising to
restore much if not all of the old Soviet Union it may secure significant
support.
But just how communist is its leader, portly 51-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, a
fairly minor figure in the old Soviet Communist Party, remains to be seen. The
backbone of Zyuganov's support is the elderly, who long for an end to economic
chaos - although Russia's economy is now showing distinct signs of recovery -
and as a start have been promised their pensions on time and in full. They also
warm to his talk of generous universal welfare, especially cheap sausage, and
they share his nostalgia for the days of Russia's superpower status.
At the same time Zyuganov goes out of his way to hobnob with Western
businessmen and politicans espousing a new-style communism which would continue
with privatisation albeit at a slower pace, positively encourage foreign
investment, and unequivocally believes in a free press and freedom of worship.
There are no doubts that Russian politics are a shambles - typified by the
occasional fist fights in the Duma and frequent threats to impeach the
President - but the Communist Party is comparatively well organised with half a
million members and a network of voluntary party workers, and it says it will
be represented at each of the 95,000 polling stations.
Even if the communists do win most seats in the election they will want to
build a coalition with the Agrarian Party, the voice of the agro-industrial
lobby.
They may also try to form an alliance with the Congress of Russian Communities,
the nationalist-leaning militarist party whose main asset is Alexander Lebed, a
maverick paratroop general.
The party's leader is Yuri Skokov, once tipped to become Yeltsin's Prime
Minister, but Lebed's gruff patriotism and anti-Western stance has made him
arguably the most popular politician in the country.
Certainly Lebed seems now to have upstaged Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the flamboyant
mischief-maker whose nationalist rhetoric has since been widely copied and
whose ratings have plummeted since his stunning success two years ago when he
promised voters free vodka.
Zhirinovsky is by no means done for. He is a masterful campaigner - although
his recent vicious personal attack on the ailing Yeltsin could easily backfire
- and he has spent huge amounts on television advertising but he looks like
being eclipsed by a new generation of hardliners, and Lebed for one is sounding
and looking more convincing on the law-and-order issue.
Because the elections are also effectively the equivalent of a primary for the
presidential contest next June, Zyuganov, Zhirinovsky, and Lebed are
desperately hoping for their parties to do well to give momentum to their
campaigns.
Boris Yeltsin, meanwhile, would apparently still like to be thought of as a key
player and while he has not campaigned for anyone he has tried to boost support
for the Government-backed party, Our Home is Russia, headed by Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. The Government, in fact, has promised to pay
several months back pay owed to servicemen, pensions on time, and a fund has
been set up to compensate millions of Russian investors who have been victims
of financial swindles.
It may be too late for Chernomyrdin. His party is still marginally behind the
leading pro-Western reform party known as Yabloko and led by the
Harvard-educated economist Grigory Yavlinsky. A bad showing could well lead to
Yeltsin deciding to get rid of his Prime Minister but whether he is in a
position to do it is another thing.
On the other hand, it cannot be ruled out that if Yeltsin's health does not
significantly improve he may decide to stand down himself.
Yavlinsky does look as if he is one of the few politicans worth a vote by those
who fear a communist landslide or the rise of more ugly nationalists. The
Kremlin elite will be seriously embarrassed if Our Home is Russia flops in the
elections, but despite his bizarre behaviour, Yeltsin's tenacity and political
acumen should not be underestimated. He knows well enough that even if the
communists do come out on top in the election and manage to establish a
hard-left controlling coalition in the Duma - which is by no means a certainty
- he is still in a powerful position.
It is worth recalling that Zhirinovsky's party won the biggest share of the
vote last time, some 23%, but no real power, and for Zyuganov and his friends
to control Russia their coalition would have to hold a two-thirds majority in
parliament. Only then could they block Yeltsin's decrees and vetoes.
This is not out of the question but voting for the 225 first-past-the-post
constituency seats may well produce a very large number of independents. So
Yeltsin, even if he is in and out of hospital, will be able to tough it out for
a time with the Kremlin running on auto pilot, ironically just as it did during
the years of Leonid Brezhnev and the Soviet Communist Party. Sunday's election,
however, will establish the front-runners for his job.
</TEXT>
