<DOCNO>GH951214-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Further small cuts expected next year as Chancellor and Governor work hand in hand Base rates fall a quarter point</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By R E DUNDAS Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897278</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SERIES of quarter-point reductions in interest rates are expected in the
first half of next year after the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke,
ordered a cut in Minimum Lending Rate from 6.75% to 6.5% on the advice of the
Governor of the Bank of England, Eddie George.
The banks immediately followed the signal to the money markets and cut their
base rates by 0.25% to 6.5%, and the Halifax Building Society led the way to
lower mortgage rates with its second quarter-point reduction since the Budget
at the end of November. The Halifax's new variable rate of 7.49% is the lowest
for nearly 30 years.
It was the first cut in base rates since February 8 last year. Since then the
cost of borrowing has increased three times - on each occasion by 0.5% - to
contain inflationary pressures. Mr Clarke indicated that future changes in
rates would be in quarter-point steps in line with the practice of the German
Bundesbank and the US Federal Reserve Board.
The City had expected rates to be reduced by 0.5% either at the meeting between
the Chancellor and the Governor yesterday or early in the new year to boost the
economy which has slowed down sharply this year.
The big surprise was the Governor's decision to go along with the cut. The Bank
of England now believes the Government will meet its target of reducing
underlying inflation to 2.5% or less by the start of 1997. Adam Cole, UK
economist at City stockbroker James Capel, said he now expected good inflation
news when the figures were published this morning.
Sterling took the rate cut in its stride, and its trade weighted index edged up
from 82.8 to 83.0. A cut in German rates is still considered a possibility
after this morning's meeting of the Bundesbank Council. There are also hopes of
lower rates in the US after the Federal Open Market Committee meets on Tuesday.
Gilts took heart from the indication that the Chancellor and the Governor were
now working hand in hand after being at odds in the summer over the need for
higher rates. The response in the stock market was more muted with the FTSE-100
share index gaining 7.5 points to 3662.4.
The cut in UK rates followed encouraging economic news showing a stronger than
expected increase of 0.6% in retail sales last month and a fall of 20,400 in
seasonally adjusted unemployment.
Mr Clarke told a news conference that he and Mr George had agreed the quarter
point reduction in rates was a ``sensible and prudent move''.
He said that in the new low inflation environment, future changes in rates were
likely to be made in ``small steps''.
He said the only issue to be decided at yesterday's meeting was whether to go
for a quarter or half-point reduction in base rates.
They had agreed on a quarter because there were several factors giving rise to
caution on the inflation outlook, including the strength of the money supply,
the weakness of the pound and the strength of the figures yesterday morning
showing a 20,000 drop in unemployment, record job vacancies, and strong retail
sales in November.
``I was satisfied that 0.25% was right in all the circumstances. The thing that
finally decided me was particularly the fall in unemployment and the fact that
retail sales had picked up so sharply in November,'' Mr Clarke said.
``We are now becoming a low inflation economy. We must get used to the
behaviour that comes with that and it is sensible to move by quarter points at
this stage.''
Mr George said he was ``very happy'' to be in a situation to advise a cut of
0.25%.
``I am delighted we have been able to move to a situation where we will, I
hope, be able to move in smaller steps in the future. It puts us in the same
league as other countries which have had stable economies for much longer.''
Unlike at the time of its last inflation report in November, the Bank now
believes the odds have moved in favour of the Government achieving its
inflation target.
``It's on that basis that we have proposed the reduction in interest rates,''
he said.
The Chancellor later conceded to the House of Commons Treasury committee that
he no longer expected his Budget forecast of 2.75% growth to be achieved this
year. City analysts believe lower rates are needed to validate his forecast of
3% growth for next year.
Mr Cole said that, with rates likely to move in quarter-point steps from now
on, ``we expect three further reductions by the summer of next year, taking
base rates to a low of 5.75%''.
The Chancellor and the Governor next meet to discuss rates on January 17. Mr
Cole said: ``If, as we expect, both the Fed and the Bundesbank have cut rates
by then, there is little reason to think that UK rates cannot fall by another
0.25% then.''
He added that yesterday's quarter-point reduction ``seemed to mark a genuine
move to a more gradualist monetary policy, rather than the compromise that was
behind the last 0.25% move in February 1994''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897279</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIFE is a series of crushing blows. Just when you thought it was safe to relax
into sloth, because 'tis the season to be jolly, and not bother for at least a
fortnight to feel guilty about failing to join up for an exercise class, the
phone rings.
It was one of those perky voices. Would I like a free three-month subscription
to a health club? Frankly, dear, I'd rather eat my toenails. But you let her
twinkle on because she's probably trying to make money for Christmas, and what
a way to earn your corn, cold-calling people who are only de-fleaing the cat so
don't bother to hang up.
It might have been kinder to save her breathy breath, admit she has sadly,
randomly, called a woman whose aversion to exercise and sport is so deeply
rooted in early trauma she gags at the first whiff of Body Shop Coconut Sports
Shower Scrub; a woman who has a fantasy of a wedding service interrupted as a
bare, bandy-legged, horribly familiar, comes round a pew crying: ``There is one
just impediment. This woman cannot do a handstand.''
The gym stood apart from the rest of the school. It was here the gym master
came into his kingdom, a cold kingdom smelling of coconut matting and sweat. He
was a balding, wiry man with the strutting composure of a gang leader. He
directed the pack's attention to the clumsy and the weak, but most especially
to those girls and boys who, in their stupidity, had been assigned to the Latin
class. He only got them once a week, whereas he was allowed to be a vicious
berk three times a week or more to those who did not suffer from Mensa
pretensions.
This was his domain. It was as though he were exacting revenge on us for a
future in which handstands would no longer matter. But God they mattered then.
Those who failed were kept behind, trying and still failing, and nobody
questioned the lunacy of something which would have us there now, still,
flailing legs akimbo, crashing into the parallel bars whilst pursuing
professional lives in spare moments.
Public humiliation was too good for us, although it was his speciality. Pale
quivering figures stumbled at the horse, hung miserably entangled in wallbars
and Tarzan ropes. His gym lessons were an exercise in terror. You were unsure
who, the sports idols apart, would be picked on next.
Sometimes parents could be prevailed upon to write sick notes. He would read
them through, slowly, very slowly, like Stalin considering a stay of execution.
He would them crumple the letter, even more slowly, lift his square gaze to
stare, as if in one wall-eyed glare to impart to us that he knew, he was a man
but he knew, it was impossible to have five periods in one month......
Where were we again? Oh yes, the temptation to a free three-month spell of
torture, sorry, exercise in a sports club. She must have sensed my thoughts had
strayed to long ago and far away and feeding the goldfish in the here-and-now
because she saved her best offer for last. Her persuasive voice threw in the
clincher - a free health magazine.
Only the madly deluded could dream it up. Entire shelves in newsagents have
been taken over by fitness magazines flicking towels at What Next On The
Internet. They range from glossies for the cosmetically clued-up jogger to
hardcore muscle mags. At the soft end of the range is such as Healthy
Lifestyle, which despite its bungee jumping, blow-hole diving, heroic image is
actually more concerned with eyebrow plucking and following the country code
while hiking in brogues from Next. It's for men and women who talk big but want
to have nice hair.
Some are tougher, featuring men who spend all their spare time running,
jumping, shaving their bodies for major swimming contests, and wondering
whether you can pick up skin diseases in the scrum, and women whose figures
look less like humans and more like horses, albeit horses wearing tiny dayglo
microkinis.
It is a world where people are turned inside out with exertion, so that all
their veins appear on the outside, like the lifts on the outside of those big
American department stores.
What happens to all these people when they give up competing in grunting
contests? Do they grow wrinkly and shrink, like your gran, trailing skeins of
excess veins which snag in the exercise machines?
For those of us for whom running around a gym went out with scabby knees there
are many other ways to keep fit. And as soon as the season of sloth is over we
are going to investigate them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Docu-want</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Sinclair</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897280</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is a growing demand for people to be able to get copies of reference work
off the Internet in hard-copy format, once they have identified what they want.
DocuWeb, from Rank Xerox, is designed for library applications and offers users
global access to collections of important documents on the WWW.
It differs from current systems in that it creates digitised libraries of
formatted documents which are not only faithful to the text but also to the
layout and graphical elements of the material.
User are able to browse the electronic copy, which appears as screen-rendered
images. They then fill in a request sheet, with payment if applicable, and a
copy is dispatched from the WWW DocuWebhost organisation.
Requested print copies can be produced by any of the RX range of Docuprint
series Postscript printers and dispatched by mail.
Another system developed by Rank Xerox for Internet users is InterDoc. This is
designed to allow commercial printers or quick-print establishments to to set
up an electronic storefront on the Internet in the form of a home page, and
receive and produce electronic documents.
Subsequent forms allow customers to give approvals. The forms are displayed
using a standard WWW browser such as Mosaic or NetScape.
Rank Xerox believes this product will not only help commercial printers, but
also assist customers who transfer electronic copy between locations for
printing at point of need. This is particularly useful for manuals and
handbooks that accompany products.
</TEXT>
