<HEADLINE>First Technology drives earnings up</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897281</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
B
ALTHOUGH global car production in 1995 is likely to have proved flat, the
outlook for 1996 is much more positive with expectations of a 7% advance in
Europe, a recovery in Japan and a slight improvement in the US.
But for First Technology the critical factor should be its increasing success
in introducing crash fuel cut-off sensors and selling its crash test dummies.
It has found a new market for these in a somewhat unexpected area. US
regulations now demand carrycots are tested with dummies with 60 individual
information points, which can mean an individual sale equivalent to about
#50,000.
US safety requirements tend to be the world pace-setters except in cars, where
European tests are more realistic in that they are designed for the much more
frequent glancing crash than the head-on collision.
First's sensors are now being introduced into the Renault, Peugot and Citroen
ranges with likely additional sales in 1996 of about 4.8 million units at
perhaps #2.50 each.
Chairman Dr Fred Westlake is increasingly targeting the Far East too, with
contracts in Malaysia, Korea and further penetration of the Japanese market in
addition to Honda likely.
The advantage is that the UK is a cheap manufacturing base for First, making it
unlikely to want to build a plant in Asia.
In the six months to September, pre-tax profits rose 16.3% to #3.28m on
turnover 10.2% greater at #18.1m.
The current half will benefit from the start-up of the French factory -
although the full benefits will not come through until late next year - and new
contracts with Volkswagen Audi and for new US Ford models.
Full-year profits seem set to increase from #6.27m to about #7.5m to leave the
shares at 440p, down 18p because a broker confused the interim with full-year
figures, trading at 14 times likely earnings, which seems a little cheap.
The interim dividend has been raised 0.4p to 3.2p with an 8p total probable for
a 2.3% yield.
