<HEADLINE>Out of tune with season of goodwill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jimmy Reid</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897282</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is an argument for the rest of the world dumping its nuclear waste in
Britain; an argument for France testing its nuclear devices somewhere in Kent;
an argument for the fates to plot Britain's economic downfall, though why
bother when the Government is already doing so. There is even an argument for
the rest of the world denying Brits asylum or short-stay visas.
The argument is that top of the pops in Britain today is a song of wretched
yuckiness called ``I Believe''. Bad enough if sung by boy sopranos with
`orrible piping penetrating voices which would have justified Herod's
infanticide if only he had confined it to young boys with high pitched voices,
musical pretensions and over indulgent mothers.
However, the perpetrators of this crime aren't trilling and insufferable boy
sopranos but trilling and insufferable case-hardened actors trying to earn a
few extra bob over the festive period. In the name of Equity, why couldn't they
have done something with a bit more dignity, like picking pockets in the
Cristmas crush?
Any country which wallows in such bad taste deserves all that's coming to it,
forfeits any right to a place among civilised nations, and should be expelled
henceforth from the United Nations Security Council. Who would you rather your
daughter brought home for dinner: General Ratko Mladic, Bosnian Serb army
commander, or Robson and Jerome? Hard one, intit?
But think of the case against Robson and Jerome. ``I believe for every drop of
rain that falls,'' they gush, ``a flower grows.'' For starters that is
debatable. The rain can fall to earth, filter through the soil, gathering
poisonous residues of chemical fertilisers, and by the time it gets to the
burns and rivers be a toxic serial killer of flowers and other flora, not to
speak of fish and their fauna friends.
``Everytime I hear a new born baby cry,'' intone the dynamic duo, invoking
pictures of plump wee babies you see in television adverts, snug in their cots
in centrally heated suburbia - whereas the real cry babies in today's world
come from places like Rwanda, children with the distended stomachs of the
starving, and the glazed bewildered eyes of the very young, not long for this
world.
But shhh, don't spoil the party! Jesus wants them for a sunbeam. Come to church
and see wee Jesus in his crib, and, bayjasus, it looks and smells like a
Beverly Hills nursery. Not a whiff of dung or other odours of where animals
dwell. There must have been hot and cold running water in that stable for the
wee fella is spotless. Not a louse in sight. If you didn't know better, you
would think he was little Lord Fauntleroy.
It's amazing - the homeless in those days lived better than the homeless of
today. See those cardboard cities, they're pigstys.
Now there's nothing wrong with a festive season which allows us to forget, for
a moment, the tribulations of life. There's everything right with sentiments
such as peace on earth and goodwill to all men. The swapping of a few drinks, a
few stories, a few songs, a few tears for departed freens. Even the commercial
exploitation of Xmas doesn't bother me. It's part and parcel of festivals in a
market economy, so we may as well enjoy it.
Celebrations are good for the soul and we should enjoy each other's good times.
But for me the scandal of Christmas is the hypocrisy of the candy floss,
sanitised, thoroughly respectable and conformist image of Christ that is
projected and makes him out to be a Galilean Norman St John Stevas or Lord
Fawsley, as he is known to his friends.
Christ was nothing like this. In life he railed against man's inhumanity to
man, and still had a drink with publicans, which in a social sense is as low as
you can get. So let the baby Christ in his crib be black, for he was black, or
more black than white. Show the squalor of his birthplace to remind ourselves,
and our children, that this was, and is, the lot of the homeless, even unto
this day.
We can celebrate his birthday with a few haufs, even if it's not his actual
birthday. The Queen has an official birthday, so why not Him? But we have to
draw a line somewhere, and that line is Robson and Jerome singing ``I Believe''.
A song is a piece of music with a verbal text. Take the words away and a song
has no meaning, no raison d'etre. A singer is a storyteller. The music helps
set the mood, but can't be more precise. The words do the rest. The music of a
song is crafted to give the words a setting. Without words properly delivered
and understood, there is no song.
Louis Armstrong chewed over a lyric like a child savouring a toffee. His world
was woild, and you can't argue with that. Ella Fitzgerald had perfect diction,
each word had vowels and consonants evenly pronounced, but she really didn't
have a feel for words. She was into the melodic line, and phrased round it,
like a jazz instrumentalist. This is why her singing lacks verbal drama.
The singer supreme who instinctively understood the primacy of the lyric in
song and projected a lyric better than anyone I've ever heard, was Frank
Sinatra. He has had a life-long love affair with lyrics, and that ain't over
yet.
He savoured the flavour of a good lyric, probed the metre, searched for a new
accented placement that might add a new dimension or give a new insight to the
story. Sinatra had a great, expressive voice. Good pitch, never hit a bum note
in his life, and could swing like the great jazz musicians he revered. He had
also that most under-rated quality of all, good taste. I think he's a genius.
Whether the Scottish nation should be autonomously self-governing within the
United Kingdom or independently self-governing outwith the United Kingdom, is
an issue whose day is coming. It's a complex matter involving rights of self
determination and the relationship between large and small nations, within a
single unitary state.
History, culture, the principles of nationhood, differing philosophical and
moral values, should, you would think, come into play. It therefore takes some
doing to drag such a debate down to a squalid hypothetical squabble about three
pence more or less on tax. But somehow our politicians have managed.
</TEXT>
