<HEADLINE>East Midlands shareholders enjoy special half-time payout</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897283</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EAST Midlands Electricity, one of only three electricity companies not to have
been subject of a bid, aims to keep both its shareholders and customers happy.
The interim results for the six months to September 30 go some way towards this
although the shares fell 36p to 703p, partly on profit taking and also
reflecting market caution about some aspects of the package. This includes a
special dividend of 120p a share (worth #238m) as well as a 7% increase in the
normal interim payout to 9.2p.
As a result of the special payout, gearing, which had been eliminated, will
rise to 80%. Domestic customers are to receive a one-off #54.60 discount,
including VAT.
Pre-tax profits rose 12.4% from #86m to #96.7m which took in #8m gain arising
from the sale of non-core operation Ambassador Security but excluding the
interim dividend from the National Grid which contributed #5.7m last time.
The company has now completed the disposal of its non core activities and its
electricity business restructuring continues.
Underlying earnings per share was up 18.9% from 28.1p to 33.4p.
Chairman Nigel Rudd says that the ``excellent results'' demonstrate continuing
success founded on the company's strategy of of focusing on its core
electricity business.
The next phase, announced last month, provides the opportunity for ongoing cost
reductions and a focus for future investment in East Midlands Electricity's
network. This in turn is expected to enable the group to maintain downward
pressure on electricity prices, improve customer service and continue to
release value as reflected in the special payout (the second following 85p in
November 1994) and distribution to shareholders of the company's National Grid
shares.
The chairman also points out that with a further reduction of electricity
prices of 1.4% in April 1995, the company's domestic customers are now paying
12% less in real terms than three years ago.
In July, the director-general of Electricity Supply announced new proposals
which, combined with the results of the earlier distribution review announced
in August 1994, will reduce revenue from this business by 29% by the year 2000.
This reinforces the need to continue to invest if the group is to be able to
achieve sustained reductions in operating costs.
Group employee numbers have also fallen 8500 to 4680 since September 1992 and
in the core electricity business from just under 5000 to 3885 over the period,
a process which is likely to continue.
As for the prospect of a takeover, shareholders have certainly been sweetened.
But in any event, chief executive Norman Askew takes a robust view, stating
that a takeover either happens or it doesn't and it is no good sitting there
sucking ones thumbs and wondering what is going to happen. ``We have to get on
with running the business and that is what we are doing,'' he says.
A buying spree of the RECs has seen eight of them taken over or under offer.
