<HEADLINE>War breaks out among mortgage lenders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian McConnell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897284</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEWS of the quarter-point reduction in base rates sparked a mortgage war
yesterday, after Halifax Building Society cut its home loan rate for the second
time in only two weeks.
The decision to ease UK monetary policy was generally viewed as positive for
the housing market and retailers, although the response from the construction
industry was mixed.
Nationwide, the second-largest building society behind Halifax, looked to have
been caught on the hop by its arch-rival.
Immediately after the base rate cut, Nationwide said it did not expect to
reduce its rate again in the wake of it, having taken 0.3% off at the end of
November.
A spokesman said: ``It was the cut we had been anticipating. It is the sort of
cut we would have expected from a prudent Chancellor.''
However, after Halifax announced it was shaving another quarter-point off its
variable mortgage rate, Nationwide said it would cut again to keep its lending
rate below that of Britain's biggest building society.
Later in the day, it announced a 0.21% cut in its standard variable mortgage
rate to 7.44%, matching Northern Rock.
Halifax's quarter-point reduction to 7.49% was followed by Abbey National,
which charges the same interest rate on loans of between #60,000 and #99,999,
Woolwich, Bradford &amp; Bingley, and Britannia. National &amp; Provincial cut its rate
by a quarter-point to 7.54%.
New Halifax customers will benefit immediately from the rate reduction, which
comes into effect for existing borrowers on February 1. Monthly repayments on a
standard #50,000 mortgage will be #14.65 lower as a result of the two
quarter-point cuts, which will produce Halifax's lowest basic home loan rate
since 1966.
Of the major players, Alliance &amp; Leicester was the only one not to announce a
cut in its 7.74% mortgage rate yesterday but it is expected to make a statement
today.
Northern Rock, which cut its standard variable mortgage rate by 0.4% last
month, reduced it by another 0.15% to 7.44%.
Royal Bank of Scotland chief economist Jeremy Peat believes UK interest rates
could be cut by as much as another half-point in the first quarter of next
year, if economic data continues to disappoint.
Geoff Ball, executive chairman of Edinburgh-based housebuilder Cala, welcomed
the quarter-point cut in base rates.
He said: ``In terms of the housing market, I think it is good news and it can
only help.''
CALA is hoping the fall in interest rates will boost business in the south of
England, where it has been selling only about half the number of houses it
would like to during the last couple of months.
Wimpey Homes, Britain's largest housebuilder, also welcomed the cut.
Douglas Symington, who heads up the West of Scotland operations of Wimpey
Homes, said: ``The combination of lower interest rates plus the prospect of a
real increase in disposable income for the first time in four years should add
a little Christmas cheer to the housing market.''
The British Retail Consortium (BRC), which represents about 90% of UK
retailers, welcomed both the base rate cut and further reductions in the cost
of mortgages.
Although he would have liked to have seen a half-point cut, Tom Muir, BRC's
director for professional services, said: ``It is a useful first step in
bringing interest rates down and we will be looking for more in the New Year.''
Mr Muir hoped the rate cut would have a positive impact on High Street sales in
the run-up to Christmas.
But Balfour Beatty, Scotland's leading contractor with a 7% market share,
believed the rate cut would have little, if any, impact.
Mike Peasland, an Edinburgh-based director of Balfour Beatty Construction,
said: ``I can't see, for the construction industry or Balfour Beatty, that it
is going to make any significant difference at all.
``Perhaps half-a-percent would have given a better signal to the industry -
that might have helped fuel things.''
Mr Peasland's views were echoed by Ian Deslandes, director-general of the
Building Employers Confederation.
Although thankful for ``small mercies'', Bill Anderson, Scottish secretary of
the Federation of Small Businesses, said: ``This is a bit like a nod to a blind
man. We'll wait for the full one per cent before we put out the flags.''
The base rate cut, however, was welcomed wholeheartedly by the Scottish CBI.
Assistant director Alan Mitchell said: ``We are pleased that a prudent Budget
has been followed by this quarter-point cut.''
n THE UK's largest credit card company, Barclaycard, cut its annual rate of
interest by 0.3% to 22.6%.
</TEXT>
