<HEADLINE>Focus on town centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Andrew Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<FLAG>Advertising Feature</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897285</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Andrew Douglas discovers a visible path to a secure future for a shopping area
THERE was a time when Paisley was seen as a handy place to live, only 10
minutes by train to Glasgow's Central Station; but today Paisley is quickly
re-establishing its identity as one of the best places to shop in the West of
Scotland. The one-way traffic that flowed from the country's biggest town had
to be halted otherwise the town centre, the heart of the community, would go
into rapid decline.
But change does not come without the careful preparation of a plan of action
and it has been largely due to the efforts of the Paisley Town Centre
Management Trust, established one year ago, that plans were put into operation
to make Paisley one of the best and safest places to shop in Scotland.
Forerunner to the Trust was the town centre steering group who appointed a town
centre manager in John McLaren. That was in 1990 and McLaren, whose previous
occupation had seen him in the role of Divisional Police Chief, was given the
task of assessing the town's commercial heart and in partnership with
Strathclyde region, Renfrew district, Renfrewshire Enterprise and Scottish
Homes jointly produced a plan that would see the regeneration of the town
centre.
Throughout Britain there were moves for safer cities and towns and one strategy
that had proved successful was the installation of CCTV (closed circuit
television). When Airdrie installed CCTV its crime figures immediately dropped
and a huge reduction in senseless vandalism created a fresh perspective in its
town centre. And when CCTV became operational in King's Lynn, in Norfolk, there
was an astonishing 97% reduction in thefts from cars.
However, such schemes cost money and John McLaren found himself requiring to
raise around #300,000 to purchase and install the 12 cameras needed to cover
the town centre. Months of discussion followed, with a satisfactory conclusion
realising the funding required.
Finance for the project was raised through contributions from Renfrew District
Council, #45,000; Strathclyde Regional Council, #45,000; Renfrewshire
Enterprise, #45,000; Strathclyde Passenger Transport, #25,000 with the rest of
the money being raised among local traders. The local telephone company
CableTel has supplied the cable infrastructure within Paisley, which
represented a considerable contribution to the private sector share of the
funding.
The Trust's main objective is to create a safer town and not to provide the
Police with a tool in CCTV. And although one bonus for the Trust has been that
the Police have agreed to manage the cameras, a first in Scotland, it has been
the case that they have remained very much in the background.
There is little doubt that shoppers will have a greater feel for safety once
the cameras are installed. John McLaren, said: ``In the long-run businesses
will be helped during the day and then in the evening the pubs, clubs and
restaurants - once people are aware that security has their safety in mind.''
John McLachlan owns two shops in the town and he is convinced that the
installation of the cameras will not only be of great benefit to the trader but
also to the general public: ``The installation of the cameras is a first-class
move. It can only be good for the general public, in particular senior
citizens. They can shop in the knowledge that they have nothing to fear and
that those people who are up to no good are being watched.
``The raising of the money by the town centre management group has been a
tremendous achievement. Not only will the public and traders benefit but the
cameras will allow policemen on the beat to operate more effectively.''
Another benefit to traders in town centres where CCTV has been installed is the
reduction in insurance premiums which follows, making the economic atmosphere
more beneficial for shops to trade in.
A major strategy in place over the next two to three years will improve the
overall quality of the town centre. Plans for extensive pedestrianisation will
take in the High Street and Gilmour Street, and areas such as Abbey Close and
Forbes Place will be returned to a quality status to enhance the whole retail
market master plan.
Further to these developments, the building of a multi-storey car park with 500
spaces in the town's centrally located Storie Street will commence in January
and should be completed by Christmas 1996.
But perhaps Sheila Laidlaw, chairman of the Trust, who has a shop in the town's
New Street which has had its windows broken six times summarises the picture
best: ``Being part of the business community, I am looking forward to the
installation of the CCTV. It is important to me that the public feels safe and
secure when they come into town and if troublemakers are identified on camera
there is a very good chance that vandalism will cease. I would like to see
Paisley become the town it once was, a good place to shop and where we can all
get on like Buddies, which we are.''
PLACED in strategic positions, the 12 cameras that make up Paisley's CCTV
system will operate within the town's heart. From the Sneddon, south to almost
Canal Street, and from Lawn Street in the east to the museum in the High
Street, they will pan over an area that is almost one square mile.
Within the control room at Mill Street Police Station the video images are
displayed on 12 dedicated monitors allowing all cameras to be viewed
simultaneously. In addition to these monitors, larger spot monitors are
provided to display the video signal of the camera under control and to allow
playback of any incident.
</TEXT>
