<HEADLINE>Pique over paper mountains</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Sinclair</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897286</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Whatever happened to technology's promise of the paperless office? Bill
Sinclair looks at the increasing use of printers
REMEMBER all that talk back in the early eighties about the imminent onset of
the paperless office? Well, now.......how many people do you know whose desks
are a paper-free zone, never mind their filing cabinet? Your own, perhaps? I
thought not. In fact, it is likely that if you are a typical white-collar
worker - or, to be politically correct, a knowledge worker - you may be
handling more paper than ever before.
Not convinced? Well, here`s what George Peacock, integrated document specialist
with Rank Xerox in Edinburgh, has to report.
``It is true that in some areas paper is decreasing. Printout from UK computer
datacentres is expected to drop from almost 24 billion prints in 1991 to 17.3
billion prints in 1997. However, output from office laser printers is on an
upward path, from 17.5 billion in 1991 to a projected 36.5 billion next year.''
It seems there is more print being produced in the average office than ever
before.
If you are still not convinced, I suggest a trip to your nearest computer store
may help. Look how much shelf space is devoted to printers of all sorts of
types - dot matrix, inkjet, bubblejet, printjet, laser, LED, thermal,
dye-sublimation, et al.
The clue to understanding why the paperless office has not become a reality
lies in what we use paper for. The vast majority of print in the office
consists of documents: the memos, letters, reports, invoices, schedules,
training materials, manuals and a hundred and one other pieces of paper-based
communication that we come into contact with each working day.
``Documents are pervasive throughout any organisation,'' is how George Peacock
puts it. ``They carry instructions, decisions and information between
individuals, functions and departments. Crucially they act as both inputs to,
and outputs from, almost all work processes.
``Documents, often thought of as existing only in paper form, often exist in
electronic form as well. In fact, the information they contain can flow back
and forth between paper and electronic media as it moves between people,
processes and technology.
``For example, information that was created in a word-processor may be printed
for sending to a recipient. He or she incorporates some of it in a report
prepared on a PC to E-mail to a line manager, who circulates it on the network
to a working group. Then they all print it and bring it to the next meeting.''
Sound familiar? This example of information being transferred between different
documents is typical. What is also typical is that the documents either exist
in paper form in the first place, or will at times be printed to paper.
Why, with all the electronic tools at our disposal, do we still print
information? There are two answers to this, says the man from Rank Xerox, one
practical the other emotional.
``In practical terms, how do you fancy reading even a 10-page document entirely
from a screen? ``For a start, on today`s systems the quality of screen
resolution simply is not up to that of most print on paper. Reading from a
screen is also more stressful in that you are looking at transmitted light from
a light source at close range, and even with today's screens that can cause eye
strain.
Screens also suffer from glare created by overhead lights which adds to the
problem.
``Paper, on the other hand, doesn't itself radiate light. In reading from paper
you are looking at light that is reflected off the surface, which is easier on
the eye.''
``As well as the practicalities, emotions also play a role. Information needs
to be understood. People seem to find it easier to take in and absorb the
printed word when it is held in their hands.'' My own experience of creating
documents on screen, which goes back to the late seventies, bears out what
George Peacock says. Printing out a hard copy to proof-read, rather than
reading a document directly from the screen, is not only the norm in the
newspaper industry but a widespread practice in all offices.
Print has the additional advantage that comprehension is increased through
activities that directly interact with the copy itself; such as highlighting,
and appending notes. These acts increase concentration and focus the mind on
what is being communicated.
So what of the future? Is the concept of the paperless office a fantasy? Not
quite, says the integrated document specialist.
``Although in some areas paper documents are increasing, electronic documents
are increasing currently at a much faster rate.
``Electronic documents can contain voice and video, as on multimedia systems,
and in the future these will become far more common. It is hard to see how such
documents can be fully represented on paper.
``Similarly, hypertext documents, like those on the World Wide Web, do not lend
themselves to print. With their numerous possible connections between items,
either in the same document or in others stored elsewhere, they are not meant
to be read line-by-line, as with the traditional page layout. ``Their value
lies in being able to jump between related items of text with a click of a
mouse. In such areas the electronic media has a significant edge over paper.''
However, to most of us, and for most uses, paper is a comfortable medium.
It is simple, it is versatile. It can be easily copied and sent either by mail
or fax. It can also be used by anyone who can read the language of the
originator, without requiring additional technology.
It is interesting to note the current interest by suppliers of print, such as
publishers and libraries, in selling printed copy via the Web. New products
like Xerox Interdoc and Docuweb enable such organisations to market and
interface their print facilities with the Internet community.
All of which goes to show that it's horses for courses.
You are already able to browse an abbreviated electronic copy of The Herald and
other newspapers on the Web, if you want to.
However, George Peacock suspects that most people will prefer flicking through
the printed pages of their Herald till the electronic world offers a comparable
alternative - a full breadth of editorial, news and adverts in an easy-to-use,
portable and accessible format with a familiar look and feel, and all for 45p.
</TEXT>
