<HEADLINE>Some red noses are not to be sniffed at</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897287</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT WAS Christmas Eve in the off-licence and the doorbell tinkle harmonised well
with the Rudolph the Red-nosed Reindeer tape which had been playing
continuously since October. Sammy, the red-nosed server, was puzzled as he
could see no customer across the counter.
Suddenly, a little, sweet voice piped up: ``Two bottles of Buckie, please, a
dozen cans of Carlsberg Special Brew, a bottle of Thunderbird Red, three spiked
lemonades and a slimline tonic for maself.''
Sammy leaned over and was astonished to see Tim, the lad from No 34, who, it
had to be said, was tiny, proferring a #50 note. ``Hurry the XXXX up,''
demanded the young un, ``ma mammy's dyin' for a wet and the bidie-in has just
arrived''.
``But Tim,'' chided the server, ``I cannot serve you with strong drink; why you
are but four-years-old. And anyway, how are you going to carry all this booze?''
``We'll stick it in my pram, dummy!'' And Sammy's old heart melted; it was,
after all, Christmas, the season of good cheer and the kid was hardly likely to
be driving. He reached up for the Buckie when......
There was a flash of blinding light, and a middle-aged man in a red cape and
tights, with the blackest hair since Ronald Reagan left the set, leapt from
behind a mountain of Jacob's Creek and a couple of Blue Nuns, shouting: ``Hold
it right there, kid-corrupter.
``My name is Griffiths, Nigel Griffiths, and I am Labour's consumer affairs
spokesman. This child is a ``sting'', sent to expose evil wrongdoers like
yourself. You will be sentenced to write ten new poems extolling the virtues of
John Prescott.
``Well done, young Tim, here is the lap-top Tony promised you. Now off you go
and kick a Conservative for Christmas.''
Daft? Far-fetched? Couldn't possibly happen in our country? I am not so sure.
In the last few weeks, led, I am sad to say, by HM Government, the nanny
industry has been working overtime. It started with the Mad Cow hysteria -
after all those pies I have scoffed at rugby matches I should be a basket case
by now - but it has moved into overdrive at the mention of the demon drink.
For reasons which I fail to fathom, the Government has sought to establish
``safe'' drinking levels. It has just announced - very smart politics this I
must say - the original levels announced were wrong; we can all scoff more and
be the better for it. Which, of course, is errant nonsense.
There are people for whom one drink would be damned near fatal. I remember
seeing Tony Hancock near the end of his career, indeed his life, and being told
by his manager: ``If you interview him, don't offer him alcohol of any kind.
One beer is enough to set him off - once he starts he simply will not stop.''
And there are others, and let us be brutally honest about this, who can operate
successfully, indeed brilliantly, on vast quantities of booze.
Almost all our great actors were topers. Larry, Ralphie, Johnny, Michael, Sir
Robert Stephens of recent memory, had bouts with the bottle that are the stuff
of legend. Read Stephens' wonderfully bitchy autobiography if you doubt me.
The actor Simon Cadell was talking of Richardson on radio recently. ``At the
end of the play I went back to see him and his dresser poured two tumblerfuls
of gin over which a tonic might just have been waved. Ralph sank his in one and
I felt obliged to do the same.
``Another two drinks of the same measurement were poured. Ralph sipped his
demurely. `And now,' he said, `to enjoy!'.''
If I am speaking at a dinner, any more than a single glass of wine will ruin
any timing I ever had; yet I sat next to dear Chic Murray who downed everything
in sight, slept through the sweet, coffee, and interval and awoke to send the
audience into tears of mirth.
To be sure, Dylan Thomas and Brendan Behan might have lived considerably longer
if they had stayed off the sauce. Would the quality of their work been any
better?
There are no safe limits and the Government should not pretend there are. But,
frankly, what we do with our lives, provided it does not harm others, is for
ourselves to decide. Personal responsibility rules, OK? Life is not safe.
Dr Sandy Macara, chairman of the British Medical Association rather pompously
exclaimed the other day: ``Whatever the intention of the Government, relaxing
the sensible drinking limits the week after the launch of the Christmas
drink-driving campaign is both irresponsible and badly timed. The confusing
message about daily, rather than weekly, limits is unhelpful and will be
misunderstood and misintepreted by the public.''
Oh yes, the daft old public again, wouldn't know their apple juice from their
Eldorado. Sorry, Doc, I know you are a very learned fellow and we are just
plebs, but most folk realise only too well when they are hitting it too hard.
In all my life I have never heard anyone exclaim: ``Not for me, I am trying to
keep within the Government's sensible limits this week.''
Any time would have been bad for this absurd sort of announcement. I am
unconvinced, by the way, that there is more drink-driving over the Festive
period; there is just more attention paid to it. Perhaps some smartie-pants
could exlain to me the morality of that position.
We are no doubt just around the corner from health warnings on whisky bottles,
breathalisers for pedestrians, blowing into bags when we arrive at work in the
morning.
We may live longer. It will certainly feel like it.
</TEXT>
