<HEADLINE>Retail sector enjoys upturn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E Dundas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897288</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIGNS emerged yesterday that the robust consumer spending of recent months was
at last beginning to benefit the retail sector as well as leisure and other
services, writes R E DUNDAS.
The volume of retail sales increased by a seasonally adjusted 0.6% last month
to a record level, well ahead of the consensus in the City. There were
significant revisions to the historic data.
In particular the October figures were revised from a decline of 0.1% to an
increase of 0.1%.
The year-on-year rate picked up from 0.3% in October to 1.1%, but in the latest
three months sales were just 0.1% higher than in the previous three, and 0.4%
above the level of the same three months last year.
In November sales of textiles, clothing, and footwear rose by 2.7% as the
Indian summer came to an abrupt end. This added 0.4% to total sales.
Household goods sales increased by 1.2%, helped by sharp reductions in prices.
The pick-up in sales was foreshadowed by the CBI distributive trades survey,
the British Retail Consortium's retail sales monitor, and strong growth in the
notes and coins component of the money supply.
James Capel's Adam Cole said: ``Undoubtedly the impact of the cold weather on
clothing and footwear sales helped to push up volumes in November.
``But firm monthly increases in most other sectors suggest that this is not a
full explanation.''
In the latest three months household goods sales were 3.8% higher than in the
previous three and 4.9% above the level of the same period last year.
Clothing sales fell 0.6%, but were 0.6% higher than in the same three months a
year ago.
The food sector suffered from the impact of price increases blamed on the
drought. Sales declined by 0.9% in the latest three months, but were 0.7%
higher than in the same three months last year.
The 20,400 drop in seasonally adjusted unemployment last month taking the rate
down from 8.1% to 8% was also above expectations, but the figures were marred
by a 22,000 decline in the workforce in third quarter.
October's figures were revised from a rise of 200 to a fall of 400.
Average earnings growth held steady at 3.25% in October, the same as in the
previous three months.
This is an historic low and is a major factor in the improved inflation profile
perceived by the Bank of England.
</TEXT>
