<HEADLINE>Expansion indicates growth of companies</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897289</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN indication of the rate of growth of the information technology industry in
Scotland comes from two leading companies who see opportunities here for
expansion.
Simmons Magee, a provider of open IT solutions and technical services, launched
its Scottish office in Glasgow in June last year and is already looking to
increase its office capacity in the city. And Brunel IT Services, a Dutch-based
specialist recruitment agency, is planning a presence in Edinburgh and Glasgow,
kicking off with open evenings in both cities in January.
Simmons Magee is one of the UK's top ten resellers specialising in providing a
range of desktop IT services to large organisations. Since it began 15 years
ago it has grown steadily year by year, offering a portfolio of services
ranging from hardware and software supply through strategic consultancy,
cabling design, installation and maintenance.
It has a particular appeal to companies looking for someone to take the
technology, put it together and make it work for them. It believes it also has
a great deal to offer companies looking to downsize their IT operation through
out-sourcing or what Simmons Magee prefer to call co-sourcing.
Simmons Magee now has more than 160 staff spread over sites in London,
Basingstoke and Scotland, with a Manchester office opening in the near future.
The company has always had a strong presence in Scotland, and the Scottish
office has grown month by month since its opening last year to become one of
its most successful and profitable divisions. With a permanent staff of 18, and
a technical to sales ratio of 4:1, it is able to provide heavyweight technical
muscle for any IT project. Expansion is expected to continue through 1996, says
Scottish regional manager Richard Kenny.
Simmons Magee says its success in Scotland is due in part to the recognition by
its staff that customers north of the Border have slightly different
requirements than their English counterparts, demanding a higher level of
technical ability twinned with an understanding of their particular problem -
two abilities which Simmons Magee prides itself on having.
Another factor has been the company's innovative supply chain management
system. This enables customers to pick and choose from the Simmons Magee core
services on offer, ranging from consultancy through to actual installation,
building a solution dependent on the customer needs.
Within these core services Simmons Magee is able to offer unbiased advice
regarding software and hardware selection through its partnership agreements
with over 16 major hardware and software manufacturers, including Bay Networks,
Cisco, Compaq, Digital, Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Lotus, Microsoft, Novell, Oracle,
Sun and Toshiba.
The growth of IT in Scotland has persuaded Brunel, which has been operating for
20 years in Holland, and four years in the UK with offices in London,
Birmingham and Bristol, that there is room for another specialist recruitment
agency.
Trish Gittins, newly appointed Scottish regional manager, says: ``When I came
up and talked to people in the industry I found that contracting is really
growing in Scotland, and at the moment there are more opportunities than
staff.''
It is particularly suited to smaller companies, as a cost-effective way to
organise staffing levels to meet peaks and troughs. From the staff's point of
view, contracting provides an interesting and well-paid way of earning a
living.
Brunel says that all of its staff are ex-IT workers, and 90% of them have
personal experience of contracting. And Trish Gittins points out that with
offices in Houston, Holland and Belgium, Brunel has scope to offer positions to
Scots looking to work outside the United Kingdom.
</TEXT>
