<HEADLINE>Fast formula for a treat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by David Coulter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897290</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE roar of acceleration, the smell of burning rubber as tyres squeal out of a
bend and the screech of breaks locking at speeds of up to 40mph as machine and
driver lurch forward into another savage turn, it's all music to the ears of
SuperKart owner James Campbell.
Boasting the largest track in Scotland with over 60,000 square feet of indoor,
heated space to career about in, SuperKart opened its doors in Cameron Street,
Coatbridge, last week to the ever growing hordes of go-karting enthusiasts.
Equipped with 14 Kawasaki Scorpion 170cc karts, this is indoor racing at its
best, and not for the faint-hearted.
Torque and acceleration are impressive (try putting the foot down and holding
the kart on a straight line), ably assisted by the fact that the driver is less
than a couple of inches off the ground. For the average citizen, this is as
close as you would want to get to being David Coulthard.
For #10, a beginner gets 15 minutes practice. For #30 a head, a full Grand Prix
race session is organised, (for as many as half-a-dozen at a time) including
instruction, heats, semis, grand final, winners' podium and the obligatory
bubbly (non alcoholic, of course) thrown in.
Tiny transponders fitted under the karts ensure there's no dubiety about the
winner, even in the tightest photo finish.
All races are marshalled, and two black flags in a row signal the end of a race
for anyone stupid enough to attempt to bully their way round the course.
That said, the pit engineers are kept busy repairing bent axles and bumpers -
though the majority of accidents are the result of over ambitious, rather than
malicious, drivers.
With first-class dining facilities planned and a large conference hall, owner
James Campbell is confident businessmen will jump at the chance of letting off
steam on the track against any captain of industry who overstayed his welcome
at the lectern.
The public, however, will always be welcome. And judging by last week's
turnout, it is off to a flying start.
Open seven days a week, SuperKart supplies driving suit, crash helmet and
racing gloves for all-comers wanting to burn off that road rage in a pleasant
and, more importantly, tightly-controlled environment.
So if you fancy taking the winner's rostrum get the foot down for SuperKart and
really go for it on that first bend.
It's a great way to spin out of the pressures of the working day.
</TEXT>
