<DOCID>GH951214-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Child's play can be too close to virtual reality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897292</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU know how it is with children and computer games. What better excuse is
there for duffing up the old man (metaphorically speaking), exposing the frayed
condition of his reflexes, and demonstrating his absolute lack of mental
agility in a domestic setting?
There are those who allege, of course, that some games are little better than
vicious fantasies whose effect on the development of children is deeply
pernicious. Here at the Diary we know this to be a calumny.
True, we are not quite certain what to make of Primal Rage (``Freeze Breath,
Snout Gouge, and Power Puke your way to the ultimate Battle Royale in this
smash-hit fighting game.......'') or Syndicate Wars (``Control cyborgs, biker
gangs or groups of religious fanatics in an ultra violent rampage around the
urban wasteland''). Nevertheless, we won't hear a word against the
heart-warming Theme Hospital.
``The sequel to Bullfrog's `smash hit' Theme Park,'' says the brochure. ``As a
hospital manager every decision affects the profitability of your hospital.
Design and run your own hospital through different eras - from the Middle Ages
to Victorian times and the modern day.''
Just the thing, don't you think, for preparing the health trust managers of the
future?
Design your own plague victims; run a state-of-the-art Victorian slum; take the
entire NHS back to the Middle Ages. But, above all, make a profit.
Back to basics
ON the Shetland Islands, meanwhile, they are leaving nothing to chance when it
comes to rearing the money-makers of the next century.
For reasons best known to itself, Shetland Islands Council's education
department has agreed to second a teacher for the equivalent of one day per
week to ``co-ordinate the teaching of entrepreneurship to primary and secondary
pupils''.
Highlands and Islands Enterprise is funding this worthy project to the tune of
#8000 in its first year, but not everyone is enthusiastic.
Councillor Maisie Colligan has observed laconically that ``a primary two
entrepreneur needs to be taught to read first''. Or perhaps they only have to
learn how to count.
Food for thought
THOSE in need of something new for the Christmas table need look no further
than the cookery page of the Highland News. Tired of turkey? Browned off with
goose? Why not try Honey and Lemon Rollocked Gobbleduck?
And what is a gobbleduck? The Diary isn't entirely sure, not least when the
chef writing for the News points out that ``there are some very important
points concerning Gobbleduck and the proper treatment of the bandit'' and
instructs readers to ``turn the bandit pointy end skyward before dribbling
honey over its breasts and laying doobri lemon on top of it''. But of course.
A rollocked gobbleduck, as best as our dictionary knows, would be a gobbleduck
that has been severely scolded. Gobble might be a golfing term, a description
of eating habits, or (it says here) the practice of fellatio. Pretty hard to
swallow either way, we can't help but feel.
Sympathy vote
POLITICS now. Aside from the question of what, precisely, the tartan is that
adorns a leaflet called the ``Tartan Tax Guide'' issued by the Tories (three
fetching shades of blue with red and yellow threads - Clan McMarginal?) you
can't help but wonder if the folk at Edinburgh's Links Place have got the hang
of this propaganda business.
After all, on the reverse of the sheet there is a table purporting to show how
much extra tax various folk would pay under the tyranny of a devolved assembly.
Shop assistant, policeman, school teacher: fair enough. But how many tears will
be shed - or votes lost - over the claim that a humble council chief executive
would be two grand a year worse off?
Family business
AND the latest news from Japan, Land of Innovation, where a ``convenience
agency'' now exists to supply guests for weddings and funerals so that families
will not lose face if attendance is sparse.
Just imagine: hire your very own uncle who no-one remembers apart from the fact
he picked a fight with the groom's father the last time he was invited. Then
again, perhaps not.
Match of the day
A MISPRINT, perchance, in a notice in the Edinburgh Evening News announcing the
engagement of Mark and ``Wenday''. Wenday my prince will come?
Yes, it figures
IT is not for us to say if the National Lottery is addictive (don't bet against
it though), but we do notice the splendid journal Competitors World is offering
the chance for six lucky readers to win something called a Lottery Selector.
``Having trouble deciding which numbers to choose for your lottery card,
finding that the birthdays and anniversary dates are not just bringing any
rewards.....?'' it asks.
Well, the Selector ``solves the problem of choosing those elusive numbers'' -
presumably for the real dummies who can't even think of six numbers.
It may say something about the state of the nation, however, that we are
invited to enter a competition simply to help us enter another competition. For
our part we intend to despatch a valuable Lottery Selector to Edinburgh
District Council, which has just     established something called   a ``Lottery
Task Force''.
Brilliant ..... council tax money spent in pursuit of a slice of all that
``free money''.
Hip socialism
Class War, that balanced and responsible journal, would have no part in such
nonsense, of course.
Dedicated to hunting down scroungers, it has a large photograph of a dear old
lady on the front page of its latest issue and the words: ``Queen Mum: 95 years
of `actively avoiding work'.''
Knighthoods are out of the question, one presumes.
Early first-footer
SCOTRAIL staff in Inverness are stumped, so to speak, according to reports from
their lost property people that have just reached us.
A glass eye left in the sleeping compartment of the London-Inverness train was
not overlooked, happily, but a wooden leg left in the station concourse is
still unclaimed. Staff are keen for the owner to step forward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
