<HEADLINE>Kvaerner poised for legal action Battle for control of Amec escalates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897342</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE battle for control of Amec took several new twists yesterday with Kvaerner
chairman Erik Tonseth threatening legal action if the 100p a share bid failed.
In a formal statement before returning to Oslo for a board meeting, he said
Kvaerner's solicitors had been asked to make it clear to the Amec board that
the company reserved its rights. He added that he believed the Takeover Panel
statement on Tuesday might be ``the first chapter in a grim saga''.
The panel criticised Amec's financial adviser Financial Dynamics (FD) for
making unauthorised comments relating to Amec's profits for the calendar year
1996, which found their way into press reports on December 2 and 3. FD was
subsequently sacked and replaced by Dewe Rogerson. The former refused to
comment last night.
Kvaerner, which owns the Govan shipbuilder, is demanding to know whether an
attempt was made to create a false market in Amec shares and if certain
investors were encouraged to buy in advance of the formal defence document
being issued.
Brian Keelan at advisor SBC Warburg observed that people were under very
serious pressure to perform in a bid situation. ``It is unusual for a highly
experienced guy like Tony Knox (head of FD) to dream up a tax charge of 21% for
the financial year to December 1996,'' he said.
In fact, Amec has forecast profits for 1995 and only turnover for next year.
A spokesman for Amec replied that the panel had instituted an inquiry in which
parties were required to give written assurances and were then confronted with
tape recordings of conversations.
Kvaerner has bought a further chunk of Amec shares to push its holding up 0.9%
to 23.49%.
Amec has sent another letter to shareholders asking them to reject ``Kvaerner's
cheap offer'', which closes on Monday.
One suggestion is that, as the outcome may be very close, some shareholders
could be tempted to stay with Amec for a year. Kvaerner will, in any event, end
up with a substantial stake which has been underwritten at 100p and will be
able to resume hostilities after a year has elapsed.
That will give enough time to see whether Amec can deliver what it has promised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Challenge of cultural apartheid</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MURTAGH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897343</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BERTRAND Russell believed: ``There is an artist imprisoned within each of us.
Let him loose to spread joy everywhere.'' That thought has been an inspiration
to people who maintain that access to the tools of creativity should be
available to the whole community rather than the exclusive property of a
cultural elite.
We are addressing the challenge of cultural apartheid. So rather than talking
about theatre in the community, perhaps the emphasis could be changed and the
problem described as a movement towards an integrated theatre. This is a
theatrical dream which has been around for some time.
Things have changed through the splendid work of 7.84, Clyde Unity, and
Wildcat. But admirable though that work has been, it is still usually theatre
for the people and not theatre by the people.
Integrated theatre should be both by and for the people. Artistic excellence
need not be sacrificed. The cross-fertilisation which is the result of having
writers, musicians, and actors from the community as an integral part of a
professional theatre company is energising and enriching. Borderline was on the
verge of achieving such a synthesis and it is a source of regret that the
experiment was never completed.
At Craigmillar Festival Society in Edinburgh I saw scores of people have their
lives transformed through the arts. Superficially, this was a community locked
in a cycle of cultural and economic deprivation, yet I watched young people
turn from a variety of substance abuses to find self esteem through music and
the theatre. Older people who felt alienated and redundant were also able to
find a sense of purpose and meaning through artistic expression.
I am not saying then that arts practitioners should become social workers, or
that standards be reduced to fit whatever is available. The Arts Council was
founded to enfranchise the culturally disenfranchised and if we desert the
people who need the joy of the arts almost as much as they need a job, then it
is we who are the poorer.
THERE is a popular misconception that community theatre is well-meaning
individuals who meet in draughty halls and fit a show around issues of
parish-pump significance. This has never been my experience, but community
theatre will always have different standards from the centres of excellence so
long as they are denied access to the best directors, actors, writers, and
technicians.
And it is easy to assume that socially deprived areas are the only places which
are culturally deprived. When theatre reaches out to the middle class it does
so in a way other groups would find wholly condescending: we seek to placate
rather than challenge and all too often suggest social ills are happening
elsewhere.
When I joined Borderline, the company did three productions a year. I leave
them with a community group of around 40 actors, 16 writers, two youth theatre
groups, an enviable reputation for special needs work, and a single-mothers'
group. So part of the dream has been achieved, and this is in no small measure
due to the support of drama workers and progressive board members.
To them and the companies I offer my heartfelt thanks for what they have
gained. We have squared our consciences with our intellects and done the right
things for the right reason.
n-The discussion, What are the possibilities of Community Theatre? is at
Glasgow's Tramway at 6pm tonight. It precedes 7:84's production of The War in
Heaven.
Tonight the possibilities of community theatre will be the topic of a
Herald/Tramway discussion. Here JOHN MURTAGH, ex-director of Borderline Theatre
Company, puts his view
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clarke gets balance right Cut in interest rates signals caution</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897344</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
W.C FIELDS insisted we should never trust a bank manager who kept his hat on,
presumably on the grounds he was thereby perpetually ready to disappear with
the cash. Similarly, a doleful Chancellor of the Exchequer is not a good sign.
Mr Lawson smiled rarely and when Mr Lamont smiled his mirthless smile we wished
he had not.
Chancellor Clarke appeared in excellent humour yesterday as he announced a cut
in interest rates which brought them, and mortgage rates, to their lowest point
for nearly thirty years. The argument over whether interest rates should be cut
or not has swayed back and forth for months. It was always finely balanced, but
Mr Clarke probably has made the correct decision for the moment, especially in
the light of the slowdown in the economy. There is a danger this slowdown could
persist well into next year and, while it is unlikely to become a recession
once more, there is no doubt some sectors of British industry are suffering
heavily and that the building industry in particular is undoubtedly in the grip
of recession.
Other worrying signs include the reports of many companies holding stocks of
products which are well above normal. In order that these may be moved, it
seems certain cuts in production must take place in several sectors. Industrial
investment, that bugbear of the British economy, is far from satisfactory and
the evidence of short-term weakness is worrying, particularly when it is
combined with adverse trends in the economies of our trading partners in
Europe.
In these circumstances a modest cut in interest rates can be expected to be
mildly beneficial. Mr Clarke was wise not to go too far, and equally wise not
to appear to publicly rebuff the Governor of the Bank of England yet again. The
clear signs he gave that further small interest rate reductions will follow are
also welcome, particularly as they appear to signal a new and suitably cautious
way of manipulating this particular element in the economic equation.
The Government also enjoyed good unemployment figures yesterday, which is good
news, and healthier signs within the retail trade, which may be good news but
is just as likely to be misleading. Retail sales are notoriously difficult to
judge, particularly as it is difficult to disentangle the huge swings in
spending, be they seasonal or affected by other factors, from more sober
assessments of the underlying trends. High Street spending is up a little and
we are now in the middle of the Christmas spending swing, but it will be well
into the new year before that statistic, and the effect of the interest rate
cuts, is clear.
</TEXT>
