<DOCNO>GH951214-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Opera   La Belle Vivette, Coliseum, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Benedict Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897345</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MICHAEL Frayn has rewritten Offenbach's story of Helen of Troy and recast it as
a Second Empire folly, an opera within an opera in which bankers and
impresarios struggle to make the most of Vivette, the greatest soprano Paris
has ever seen in silk knickers. The result is operetta, not opera, but it's
Christmas, so who cares.
Ian Judge's production is a laugh. He uses the stage revolve with verve,
whizzing sets, singers and props past us with gay abandon. The proscenium arch
on stage turns to reveal backstage, or foyer, or Vivette's luxurious apartment.
The gags are frequent, some clever. The running send-up of Wagner as Vivette's
company prepare to stage ``the horn of the norns'' is perfect, while the
classical statues that come to life when someone inadvertently strokes their
bums are just plain daft.
Lesley Garett - Miss ENO - as Vivette has the cleavage and flash of thigh for
the role, a personality as dangerous as Joan Collins, and a supremely confident
voice. This woman was born to trill. Neill Archer as the bumpkin composer who
pursues her through an improbable series of disguises is easy listening. And,
in a packed cast, gold stars to Andrew Shore as the calculating M Calcul and
Fiona Kimm as a fiery Froufrou.
Problems? A few. Offenbach is a bit too syrupy for my taste, like eating a
whole bar of Toblerone. The music is bitty, if excellently directed by James
Holmes, and the story line completely silly. But with a bit of editing and an
undemanding audience, it should run and run.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Catalyst for creativity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897346</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Mark Fisher talks to the man behind a quiet revolution aimed at enhancing
Glasgow's cultural life
LIFE after 1990 was never going to be as glamorous for Glaswegians as it had
been in their Year of Culture. The city had invested so much in its European
accolade, so big were its ambitions, so great its achievements, that a thumping
cultural hangover was pretty much inevitable.
Glasgow since 1991 has crept softly and tried not to make too much noise. There
were of course hairs of the dog. Tramway in particular kept on programming the
Peter Brooks and the Dogtroeps and all those other grand international seasons
in its big industrial spaces. And for all the disillusionment among the
artistic community, there was a perception that the political establishment had
taken to heart the message about the arts being good for the city.
But it only took the departure of Tramway programmer Neil Wallace in 1994 (when
he moved to Amsterdam and set up his own company, Offshore Cultural Projects)
for the whole masterplan to appear, at least from the outside, to be more
insecure than ever.
It's not that Tramway was Glasgow's only arts venue, nor even that it was its
most popular, but it achieved a prestige, a cultural cachet, that made it the
envy of Europe and the symbol of everything the city had achieved in 1990.
As deputy director of the Cultural Capital dream since 1987, Wallace had put
his stamp so firmly on the South Side's former Museum of Transport that it was
impossible to imagine anyone else running the place with such commitment, such
vision, and such passion. A lull in activity after his departure only seemed to
confirm this. But another part of the equation was being overlooked.
Bob Palmer, the soft-spoken, ex-pat Canadian, Wallace's immediate superior and
his partner in the cultural double-act that swept the city off its feet in
1990, was still on the scene and had been quietly revolutionising the way the
arts were organised in the city. As director of the department of performing
arts and venues, a body responsible for every council-owned property from the
King's Theatre down to the smallest community hall, Palmer had been steadily
putting together the pieces of a long-term plan that was as radical as it was
unique.
Even before Palmer's rethink, the department of performing arts was a one-off
in Britain. Of all local authorities, Glasgow City Council is the only one with
a department specifically dedicated to the arts - the others tuck them away
under the blanket headings of education or recreation. It's a mark of the
department's success that the unitary authority which takes power in April is
already committed to keeping it on.
From this unique position, Palmer has rethought the city's arts system from top
to bottom, as arts leaders throughout Britain and across the Continent watch to
see just how well his experiment will work. Rather than having a large number
of council-owned venues, each with its own management, each with its own
artistic or cultural remit, Palmer's plan is that Glasgow will now put those
same venues under the jurisdiction of a centralised team responsible for
programming across the city.
No longer competing with each other, the venues have become part of a single
unit able to develop in the same direction at the same speed.
What this means in practice is that any available piece of art - be that an
exhibition, a play, or a piece of music - should be able to find the home most
appropriate to it. Recent research suggests that audiences are already becoming
less fixed in their ways, more prepared to seek out the things they like rather
than what their local venue chooses to give them, and Palmer believes his
policy will extend that flexibility even further. One dance production might
suit the classical elegance of the King's Theatre, another might be ideal for
the rough-and-ready ambience of the Old Fruitmarket, another still might need
the intimacy of one of the Tramway studios.
With its new structure, the department of performing arts and venues can ensure
that each production gets the performance conditions it requires, while
audiences can start acting on instinct, not out of habit.
``When I came into this job, the department wasn't particularly interested in
the arts or arts development,'' says Palmer. ``Even the King's Theatre was more
of a commercial operation, working on a self-financing basis. The first change
was to create a new set of objectives for the department which centred on
enhancing Glasgow's cultural life.''
To do this, Palmer set up an arts development team which began to talk to
artists across the city - whether council-funded or not - to organise
discussions and initiate debate. He set up the Arts Development Fund to support
innovative, high-risk ventures, international work, and new community projects
that would improve accessibility to the arts. He began, in other words, to
extend the department's remit from a manager of venues to a catalyst for
creativity.
``I began to recognise how cohesive the arts community was in Glasgow,'' he
says. ``There was a sense of co-operation and collaboration that I have never
experienced anywhere else. For that reason the department began to prod and
push in an attempt to influence the direction of the performing arts in the
city.''
That was the fun bit. Palmer was still responsible for three theatres and 13
halls, all of which were acting efficiently enough in their own way, but all
acting autonomously. ``Each one was functioning on a self-standing basis with
an enormous amount of duplication,'' he says. Frustrated by the inability to
take the creative skills of one venue and transplant them in another, and keen
to free artistic directors from their day-to-day management tasks, he began a
process that initially sounds like old-style Soviet centralisation, but that is
better described, he argues, as a shift from a building-based structure to a
function-based one.
First he brought the city's various technical crews together, creating a single
team able to move to whichever site - established or new - that it was needed.
Instantly, it was possible to make a performance space out of the Old
Fruitmarket, then in use as a council car park, simply by redeploying the
central reserve of technicians. Once you would have had to turn the building
into a permanently staffed arts centre, or at least issue a small rain-forest
of short-term job contracts, now it was possible to use it as and when the need
arose. A similar process followed for the front-of-house, property management
and finance staff - no jobs were lost, as is council policy, but considerable
effort was saved now that resources were no longer being duplicated.
The final piece of the jigsaw was the establishment of a centralised
programming team - around six people with a mixed bag of interests but with no
fixed allegiance to any one venue.
``In the traditional model when an artistic director departs, it leaves that
structure exceedingly vulnerable,'' says Palmer. ``I thought it would be far
stronger to look at it as a team whose collective energies would enable them to
do what they're good at, but would prevent the high level of burn-out.''
Having installed the core of the programming team as recently as July, the
process of change within the department is still taking place. This autumn's
Dark Lights series of new Scottish work at Tramway was just the first early
fruit of its labour, and it will be well into the new year before things really
get into gear.
ONE of the advantages of a single authority running several venues is that it
can present a clear and coherent profile - not to say near comprehensive
information - to the public. As far as the Internet is concerned, it's meant
that the department of performing arts and venues has been able to leap
straight ahead with a Worldwide Web site that not only draws together the
city's five main council venues, but also provides citywide listings
information and a detailed database of every arts organisation in town.
Located at http:www.glasgow.gv.uk/dpav.htm and administered by Keith Moore,
editor of the City Live! monthly listings guide, the Web site is nearing the
end of the first stage of its development. Featuring a database search engine,
the pages enable you to request a listing of all events happening on a
particular day within the current two months or to specify your preferred
artform - theatre, music, visual art - and sift through the information
accordingly. The system stops short of selling you tickets on-line - you have
to make do with an old-fashioned TicketLink phone number for that - but the
technology is surely not far away for that to happen soon.
Currently in progress is a site for the city's Hogmanay events, a Tramway
gallery site, listings for January's Celtic Connections and Tramway's spring
season, and an advanced system of links that will move you swiftly between
listings and venue information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cameras do combat crime Traders should focus on benefits</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897347</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CRIME fighting is a field which has always been susceptible to fashion. When
closed circuit television cameras first made an appearance on city centre
streets a few years ago there was a feeling that here was yet another Home
Office-backed ``magic bullet'' solution which would die a death.
That has not happened. CCTV has proved to be not only acceptable to a very high
percentage of the population but is now, thanks to Scottish Office-sponsored
research, being shown to work. In the past, there was a dearth of reliable
research to back up what most people instinctively felt - that the presence of
cameras was bound to deter the thugs and thieves and, where deterrence failed,
to assist in catching and convicting them. There have already been spectacular
successes in this field in Glasgow where the CCTV scheme is still young.
Early evaluations suggest it is working, that city centre crime is declining,
that people are regaining the confidence to use the city centre even at night
and the feelgood factor is leading to increased sales and profits. In the
Paisley context, Lord James Douglas-Hamilton mentioned some insurance companies
are already offering businesses discounts if their premises are within range of
the cameras.
It is all the more reprehensible that there are still some traders in Glasgow
city centre who are not contributing. They appear to be taking the benefits
while dodging the costs.
The research by the Scottish Centre for Criminology for the Scottish Office
covers a sufficiently lengthy period to give it credibility, so their finding
of real benefits and no displacement should be taken to heart by the
recalcitrant minority. The initial misgivings about invasion of privacy, about
the undermining of civil liberties through the advent of Big Brother, have
proved to be illusory. The liberty of the majority to go about their business
unmolested by criminal thugs appears to be a more persuasive force.
CCTV is not in itself the whole answer to crime but is one more useful tool in
what will be a long, uphill fight. The good thing about it, which Dr Leslie
Sharp, Strathclyde`s chief constable, keeps emphasising, is that the impetus
for camera schemes comes from communities themselves. More used as they are to
kicks, the Scottish Office should take a bow for putting up #4m of new money to
stimulate participation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Time to sell as customers fail to buy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897348</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHILE some retailers, notably Marks &amp; Spencer, will be enjoying strong trading
in the run-up to Christmas, it is traditionally a quiet period for MFI.
For it, the post-Christmas sale is the most important time. The financial
performance during it will be closely analysed both by the company and external
observers to assess how successfully the 27 new format Homeworks stores have
traded. If the current 10% improvement over existing MFIs is continued, further
branches will be rolled out from April.
The Homeworks outlets are smaller than traditional MFIs but the selling space
is the same. Improvements in warehousing have reduced the need for such large
retail sites, thereby saving on rent. Maximising returns from existing floor
space is a priority for all successful retailers faced as they are,
irrespective of sector, with continued consumer caution.
MFI's board is not expecting the quarter-point cut in interest rates to have
much impact on the housing market. In any case, as it points out, it has done
well during the past five years when the housing market has been in the
doldrums.
Rather than waiting for the external environment to improve, MFI is busy trying
to improve its own operations. It is confident the investments it is making in
the more attractive Homeworks stores, product development and increased
capability to manufacture products in-house will drive future growth.
Any decrease in own-manufacture sales was a significant factor in the decline
in gross margin. Own manufactured goods are thought to earn 70% gross against
40% on externally manufactured lines.
MFI's short-term future looks decidedly difficult against a background of weak
sales and rising costs. There is better value to be had elsewhere in the retail
sector and so the shares should be sold.
Great strides
PEARSON has made great strides this year with its strategy of becoming a purely
international media group, and it was inevitable there would be costs involved
before the pay-off came through.
The reorganisation has been extensive, replacing the decentralised structure of
a conglomerate with a more tightly controlled and focused company exploiting
synergies between the media interests and gaining from economies of scale.
Reorganisation costs jumped almost fourfold to #45m this year. More will come
in 1996, though not on the same scale.
There is also a shake-up in top management in progress with John Makinson,
managing director of the Financial Times, becoming finance director, in
succession to another one-time FT journalist, James Joll, at the end of 1996.
Group managing director Frank Barlow is fast approaching the age of 65, though
does not look it, and will stay on until May 1997. There must be a chance that
television expert Greg Dyke will be groomed for the post. He is to join the
main board, along with David Bell, currently chief executive of the Financial
Times Group, which includes business information as well as the newspaper.
The bald but bearded Mr Dyke came in with the takeover of LWT and has a
formidable reputation in commercial television. His elevation would mark the
transition of the group into a fully-fledged media empire.
Pearson has a good spread of media interests taking in newspapers, television
production and broadcasting, book and electronic publishing, and computer
software, and it will have the resources for more acquisitions next year. But
it is not all going swimmingly.
There have been disappointments as well as successes and Pearson still has to
prove it can pull it all together and deliver superior earnings growth. For the
time being the shares are high enough.
Getting fitter
EAST Midlands Electricity has yet to spot any potential predator on the
horizon, which makes it one of a small number of regional electricity companies
which have not attracted a bidder of one kind or another.
It is, though, making sure it keeps its shareholders happy and under chairman
Nigel Rudd is becoming fitter and leaner all the time.
True, the 120p special bonus to shareholders costing #238m will put gearing up
to 80%, which is high for the sector. But it should be borne in mind that last
year, after payment of a special dividend of 85p costing some #186m, gearing
stood at 30%. Since then the company has generated #192m, eliminating
borrowings.
There is no reason to believe that the board under its present strategy will
not be able to continue to generate cash and cut gearing in the coming year.
Of course, cost reductions will continue to play an important part in the
group's progress, and it will have to face the impact of July's new
distribution price review which, as has been admitted, will make the going
tougher.
However, East Midlands Electricity is full of confidence and, on its record so
far, this should not be misplaced, though given the happenings among RECs this
year, a certain amount of market caution is understandable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>China betrays its fears Treatment of dissident is self-destruct ive</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897349</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was not their intention, but by their unforgiveable mistreatment of the
dissident Wei Jingsheng the closed minds who run the Chinese regime have shown
the depths of their fears. Wei Jingsheng's alleged crime was to campaign for
democracy. Now democracy is a dangerous thing, especially when it is applied to
the actions of despots. It has a way of illuminating their dingy corners and
laying bare the operation of force which masquerades as legitimate order.
Despots do not like this and that is why Wei Jingsheng, despite the manifest
non-violence of his campaigning, has to suffer a sentence of 14 years in jail.
The actions of this mild if persistent man are hardly recognisable in the
propaganda of the Chinese authorities. He was drafting an action plan, whatever
that might mean, with the express purpose of stirring up a storm sufficient to
shake the current political power. That was the allegation. Having testified to
the impact which democracy can have, we can hardly deny the ultimate
possibilities of Wei's lonely stand for freedom, but the absurdity of the
charges against him are a negation of justice.
The Chinese authorities are clearly in a state of nervous tension, otherwise
they would have treated Wei in a more sane manner. Their tensions are caused by
the contest which is clearly under way within the regime to succeed to the
leadership of Mr Deng. As he is obviously in a state of advanced ill-health the
question is acute, and in circumstances like these the behaviour of the
claimants tends towards the extreme.
The perception within the leadership will be that the strongest man will win;
therefore a dissident, any dissident, must be treated with manifest brutality.
It will, of course, be counter-productive. China's reputation, rarely a pretty
thing, has been damaged yet again by extremism born of fear. China has changed
and will change a good deal more. But if the change is to mean anything it must
be accompanied by humanity and justice for all, including Wei Jingsheng.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hillsdown swoops for Hobson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HILLSDOWN, the UK food group is expanding its base with an agreed bid for the
Hobson food company worth #121m. The offer values each Hobson share at 31p.
The acquisition is not expected to be completed during 1995. Hobson is the
largest supplier of own-label packaged groceries and drinks products to the
Co-op, its major customer, and also supplies own-label products to other UK
multiple retailers.
The major product categories supplied by Hobson include tea, coffee, biscuits,
cereals, wines, soft drinks and sauces. Hobson's sales to the Co-op are
supplied under an agreement with the Co-operative Wholesale Society which
confers certain exclusive rights until November 1999 to supply products under
the Co-op label and other Co-op brands. The Co-operative Wholesale Society has
agreed to enter into a contract on the same terms with Hillsdown upon the offer
becoming wholly unconditional.
Hobson's sales to other major UK multiple retailers grew by some 20% in the six
months to 30 June 1995 compared with the same period in 1994 and represented
around 42% of Hobson's turnover before excise duty in that period.
In the six months to 30 June 1995, Hobson reported pre-tax profits of #7.1m on
sales of #112.8m. Earnings per share were 1.22p.
Hillsdown believes that there are considerable savings to be made in merging
the two businesses in areas such as packaging, raw materials and head office
costs.
Hillsdown's directors believe that the acquisition will, before taking account
of reorganisation costs, be positive for earnings per share. This acquisition
has not dampened Hillsdown's enthusiasm for other potential purchases.
Sir John Nott, chairman of Hillsdown, said the acquisition was in line with the
strategy of consolidating its existing product areas in European foods and
provided an excellent opportunity to expand its UK food and beverages
businesses.
News of the acquisition saw Hillsdown shares up 8p at 160p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theatre   The Caretaker, Tron Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897351</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REACHING the end of an exhaustive three-month tour has double-edged
implications for this production of Harold Pinter's most celebrated play by
Compass Theatre Company. On the one hand the bonds between the already
close-knit cast are intensified, giving an added frisson to Pinter's edgy work;
on the other hand a slight fatigue can be discerned in the performances and
there is an occasional tardiness with the lighting cues.
However, the pluses definitely outweigh the minuses, with the respected
company, who visited the Tron earlier this year with repertory performances of
A Midsummer Night's Dream and Woyzeck, presenting an evening of thrilling drama.
The tale of Davies, the shifty, jibbering vagrant taken in and offered the job
of caretaker in a ramshackle house by Aston, a mentally retarded oddbod and
Mick, his psychotic brother, ripples with ambiguity and charactertistic
non-sequiturs but that very inarticulateness clearly delineates an arena of
fractured relationships, of a longing for companionship which is continually
confounded.
Nick Chadwick's Davies is a study in grotesquerie which fully exploits the
nasty humour of the character, if occasionally overplaying the picaresque
elements. Richard Heap's Mick, revelling in deliberate misunderstanding in
order to further intimidate the tramp, is convincingly intimidating, emanating
tangible menace. However, it is David Westbrook's tour-de-force performance as
Aston which fully realises the nascent horror of the play. His monotone
monologue, when he describes the harrowing effects of compulsory ECT in the
asylum to which he was he was confined as a young man is both chilling and
redolent with eerie pathos.
The production values are excellent with Katie Wilson's design reinforcing the
omnipresent precariousness, with teetering mountains of junk hanging over the
characters.
Edgy study in
grotesquerie
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No justification for hysteria</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897352</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I AM writing to express my concern about the many unsubstantiated observations
currently being made about bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) and about the
possibility of its being transmitted to humans as Creutzfeldt-Jacob Disease
(CJD).
I am particularly distressed about the remarks made by my erstwhile colleagues,
Sir Bernard Tomlinson and Dr Wendy Grant, because there is no definite evidence
that such transmission can take place.
I shall continue to eat beef, sausages, and occasional ``burgers'' and I shall
not even attempt to persuade my family, including my delightful grandchildren,
to reduce their intake of such foods.
There was a particularly informative series of seven short articles published
in the British Medical Journal on November 25, 1995, the gist of which will be
readily understood by lay people.
The first case of BSE in Britain was confirmed in 1986, four years after a
change in the processing of offal for cattle food. It is accepted that this
offal contained the infectious agent that causes a disease in sheep very
similar to BSE in cattle and that transmission of this agent to cattle was the
cause of BSE.
It was not until 1988 that controls (legislation followed in 1989) were
introduced and this means that beef containing the BSE agent must have been in
the food chain for probably at least seven years before these controls came
into operation.
To get things into perspective, it has to be stressed that CJD is a rare
disease - there were around 30 confirmed cases per year in Britain in the
1980s. In 1994 there were 54 cases.
Thus their number is increasing but during this period, because of the
increasing awareness of and research on these interesting transmissible
diseases in man, doctors have become more aware of the condition and are more
likely to consider the diagnosis.
This, I believe, is sufficient to account for the increasing incidence of CJD -
there is certainly no evidence of a vast number of new cases that might be
expected if a large proportion of the population had been exposed to an
infectious agent that might cause CJD. And, for the reasons I have given, there
must have been widespread exposure to the BSE agent in the 1980s.
A personal experience may be of some interest. I encountered my first case of
CJD in the 1960s when I undertook a post-mortem examination on a patient who
had died as a result of a puzzling neurological disease.
Subsequent microscopical examination of the brain established that the patient
had died of advanced CJD yet the diagnosis had never been considered during
life. I am convinced that the diagnosis would have been made today.
Other relevant factors appear to have been underplayed by those who believe
that there is a high risk of BSE being transmitted to humans.
First, in cattle known to have BSE, the infectious agent is not found in
muscle, fat, or body fluids such as milk. Infectivity is concentrated in the
brain, spinal cord, and eye, and I understand that there are now strict
controls in abattoirs in dealing with such tissues.
Secondly, it takes a considerable amount of infectious brain tissue to transmit
BSE even to another cow by the oral route.
I therefore find it very difficult to believe that contamination of meat by a
small misplaced fragment of spinal cord could be a major hazard.
I am aware of the recent reports of CJD in four farmers and in two teenagers in
Britain but this does not mean that they have contracted the BSE agent.
I would be the last person to suggest that there should be any relaxation of
the stringent controls currently being implemented and I strongly support
further experimental work in appropriate veterinary establishments because
no-one can state with certainty that BSE cannot be transmitted to humans.
On the basis of all of the relevant information currently available, however, I
am of the opinion that there is no justification for the near hysteria being
displayed by some people who believe that there is a serious risk of BSE being
transmitted to man in the form of CJD by contaminated beef.
Professor J Hume Adams,
Emeritus Professor of Neuropathology,
University of Glasgow,
31 Burnhead Road, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kwik Save warning</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897353</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES in the near 1000-strong Kwik Save discount stores chain tumbled 39p to
519p and just 1p above the year's low after a warning trading statement.
Chairman Simon Keswick told the annual meeting that sales had risen 10% in the
first 15 weeks of the current financial year but growth has slowed in recent
weeks as a result of the intensification of the supermarket war.
This, combined with the short-term costs associated with small store
conversions and last year's major investment programme, has put further
pressure on margins.
He added that 1996 would be a year of consolidation.
</TEXT>
