<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>RETAILING Weak demand  and rising costs push MFI profits down by 31%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897354</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MFI had warned the City that its sales were weak so analysts were not surprised
when the flat-pack furniture group reported a 31% drop in interim pre-tax
profit to #20.1m, writes NICOLA REEVES. MFI shares dipped a ha'penny to 153.5p.
Weak consumer confidence coupled with the prolonged hot summer weather reduced
demand for its products. This coincided with a sharp rise in costs, notably for
raw materials such as chipboard which rose by 30%. There are signs though that
raw material price increases may have peaked, with it securing its latest
supplies for 5% less than previous contracts.
Chairman Derek Hunt said that while short-term factors had affected profits, he
was confident investments in the business would contribute to future growth.
Operating margins dropped from 8.4% to 5.7% and retail sales per square foot
were flat. However, MFI managed to increase its market share in kitchens and
bedroom furniture.
Gross margins declined from 52.9% to 51.2%. Higher costs including an 8%
payroll increase were offset by more products being manufactured in-house -
these attract higher margins.
MFI remains committed to giving customers value for money and continues to
offer its 20% price advantage guarantee on kitchens and bedrooms. Managing
director John Randall said the group was ``determined to grow market share by
offering unbeatable value for money''.
MFI's 27 Homeworks stores out-performed the existing outlets. The board hopes
eventually to convert all its stores to the new format, although this is
expected to take around three years. Space released from the conversion
programme may be sub-let to other out-of-town retailers. MFI already earns
around #12m a year in rental income.
Four new branches were opened in the period and one relocated, taking the total
to 184. A new venture for the group are its Howden Joinery stores which sell
kitchen and joinery products primarily to small builders. There are just 14 of
these, 10 in London, and initial customer reaction is said to be encouraging.
The French kitchens business continues to expand although trading has been
affected by domestic economic problems. A total of 15 new French stores were
opened bringing the chain to 76. MFI remains determined to increase is share of
the French kitchens market.
Capital expenditure in the first-half totalled #20.4m compared with #15.1m in
the corresponding period last year. By the year-end this is expected to have
grown to around #50m. Despite all the investment, MFI's balance sheet remains
strong with gearing rising from 4.4% to 15.5%. Mr Randall said there was a lot
of headroom in the gearing and borrowing capability ``to allow us to do the
things we want to do''.
Sales have continued to be flat in the first four weeks of the second half. The
winter sale begins on Boxing Day and the group is to make a further trading
statement in early March.
</TEXT>
