<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nature's time</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897355</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN I wrote of Astronomical Time I really meant Sun Time, that is to say, the
time indicated by a sundial, which shows midday when the sun is due south at
its highest in the sky. This is what many old-fashioned people, working out of
doors, might call nature's time.
Mr Parton's description of the various time sytems (December 5) reinforces my
simple point that on the one hand social co-operation over long east-to-west
distances requires a broad convention of timekeeping while, more to the point
for purely local co-operation, the number of strokes Big Ben puts out from
London in the morning is of less importance in the Highlands than is the
convenience to the workforce there of having daylight on the job.
But I wonder if a new convention of time with an extra hour here or there were
introduced, would the employers or the unions try to gain some advantage by
spurious uses of innumerate arguments fit only for the astrologers and the
writers who go on about an extra hour of daylight?
John Little,
17 Marchmont Gardens,
Bishopbriggs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
