<DOCNO>GH951214-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Project opens doors to women</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897357</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEWER women in Glasgow run their own businesses than anywhere else in the UK
because of cultural attitudes and difficulties in getting finance, umbrella
organisation the Glasgow Women's Network has revealed, writes ALISON DANIELS.
Yesterday women from a number of business and training organisations met in the
city to launch a year-long programme of initiatives designed to offer women
advice on setting up their own businesses and overcoming some of the obstacles
most commonly encountered.
The network, which includes women from local government and enterprise
organisations, said only 2.5% of working women in Glasgow were self-employed
compared with the Scottish average of 5% and the male average of 7%. The
network's Fiona Forsyth pointed out that this contrasted sharply with
continental European countries such as Germany where 40% of new firms were set
up by women.
The #139,000 initiative, funded by Strathclyde Regional Council, Glasgow City
Council, the Glasgow Development Agency and the European Regional Development
Fund, will include a series of roadshows providing information about
self-employment, the formation of nine projects across the city offering
detailed advice on business development and a schools education programme.
Ms Forsyth said the projects involved a number of key business agencies in the
city which had never targeted women before. ``These projects are ambitious and
innovative solutions to problems which prevent women from setting up successful
businesses,'' she said.
According to Elaine Rodger, assistant director of Glasgow Opportunities
Enterprise Trust, one of the biggest problems women face is overcoming the
macho culture of the West of Scotland. She said they also had to view
self-employment as a positive option rather than a last resort in the face of
unemployment.
Speaking at the launch, Councillor Susan Baird added that it was important to
encourage women because research had shown small businesses run by them had a
better chance of survival than those run by men.
``Women are an untapped resource. With encouragement women can add a great deal
to Glasgow's economy by the creation of successful businesses which in turn
create jobs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
