<HEADLINE>Orange lodges in community</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE wish to respond to the article by James Freeman (Evil method behind gun
madness, December 7). he refers to the Unity Orange Hall. This is wrong. The
name  is Redding and Westquarter Social Club. It is not owned by either of the
Orange Lodges in the area nor is it registered with the Grand Orange Lodge of
Scotland as an Orange hall.
The social club serves a need in the community and is used by several
organisations.
The Orange Lodges in Redding and Westquarter are part of that community and
have been established there for many years. It is the case in many areas
throughout Scotland, where no Orange halls exist, that lodges negotiate with
the owners of premises within their community, concerning availability and
rental charges, to allow them to hold their regular monthly meetings.
James Freeman then makes reference to ``other venues, including the Orange
Lodge in Slamannan''. We assume the use of the word ``Lodge'', in the context
he has presented this part of his article, is to be taken to mean premises
belonging to the Orange Order in the village.
There are no premises in Slamannan which belong to the Orange Order. The Male
Orange Lodge in the village have met in the church hall since 1986 and the
Ladies Lodge meet in Slamannan Primary School.
Jack Ramsay,
Grand Secretary, Grand Orange Lodge of Scotland,
1 Southpark Terrace,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
