<DOCNO>GH951214-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Union card may prove to be ace in Labour's pack</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PETER LYNCH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>open forum</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974897359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Herald's recent interview with Labour leader Tony Blair revealed signs of
new thinking on the party's position on constitutional change. The headline of
December 8 about New Labour and the New Union may only have been a soundbite,
but it won't be long before the Labour leadership attempts to replace the
rhetoric with substance and produce the grounds for Labour's ``thinking
Unionism'' to compete with the Conservatives' ``unthinking Unionism''.
To a certain extent, George Robertson has already pointed the way towards the
New Union. In a recent interview on BBC's On The Record, he adopted language
and concepts more often associated with the European Union to describe the
British constitution. What Robertson sought to do was place Labour's devolution
reforms within the context of a British constitution that was anything but tidy
and characterised by variable geometry - with diverse government structures
across the UK rather than constitutional uniformity.
Such arguments pick up the point made by academics such as Richard Rose and
James Mitchell that Britain is not a unitary state but a ``Union state'' which
already accommodates diverse governmental structures and can, through
devolution, accommodate more.
For many years Labour has been discontented with appearing as the party of
Scotland, Wales, and the North of England. In the 1990s, the party's
territorial strategy is very much focused on winning support in middle England.
However, competition with the Conservatives in middle England is likely to be
intense, especially as a consequence of the Tories' decision to place
constitutional change and the Union at the forefront of its attacks on New
Labour.
In the area of constitutional politics Labour faces a difficult time. Due to a
variety of pressures and political motives, Labour has four different
devolution policies for different parts of the UK. It proposes Scottish
devolution within the first year of its government, the creation of a Welsh
assembly, a mechanism for regional assemblies to develop in some parts of
England, and also supports the Government's position on Northern Ireland which
involves the creation of a Northern Irish assembly.
With the exception of Northern Ireland, these are all concessions to areas of
traditional support and they do not address the need to gain votes in middle
England. Indeed, such proposals may cause problems in middle England if the
Conservatives manage to whip up English hostility to devolution.
Talk of the New Union is a direct response to Conservative efforts to
monopolise the Union and British nationalism and present Labour's proposals for
constitutional change in the worst possible light. Devolution has allowed
Labour to play the Scottish card against the SNP. The New Union provides an
opportunity for Labour to play the British card against the Tories or at least
challenge the Conservatives over the issue of constitutional change. By
stressing its Britishness and commitment to a New Union, Labour has the
potential to present a new vision which will promote constitutional change as
the best means of defeating separatism and democratising British government
through reversing the centralising policies of the 1980s.
The New Union isn't merely a theme to allow Labour to play the British card as
effectively as it has played the Scottish card - it is also envisaged as a
mechanism to address the role of Scotland within the UK. Labour will make its
case for a new, diverse Union as an answer to the West Lothian question and the
level of Scottish representation at Westminster. However, it is doubtful
whether the concept can be stretched far enough to get Labour out of the West
Lothian conundrum, particularly because Labour has come up with ``solutions''
to the problem before which were less than convincing.
More optimistically, casting Scottish devolution within a new and diverse Union
may offer some response to the ``slippery slope'' argument put forward by
opponents of a Scottish parliament and is certainly a good way of demonstrating
devolution is not about breaking up the United Kingdom.
How will the other parties respond to the idea of the New Union? The
Nationalists will no doubt scorn Labour's support for the Union and point out
that it proves it really is a Unionist party North and South of the Border.
However, Labour shouldn't worry about such attacks too much. Most voters in
Scotland hold a dual identity as Scottish and British and Labour's New Union
will prove attractive to them even if it is too Unionist for some of the
party's more nationalist supporters.
The Conservatives face a real challenge. They may have lost out in Scotland
because of Labour's ability to play the Scottish card, but Labour is now moving
quickly to embrace a new conception of the Union that will enable it to cast
itself as the defenders of the British and Scottish nations from within and
without - the big idea that undermines current Conservative strategy on the
Union and could place Labour in a winning position in both middle England and
mainstream Scotland on constitutional issues.
n.Dr Peter Lynch is a lecturer in politics at the University of Stirling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
