<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plenty progress</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALF Young and Benedict Brogan's exclusive interview with Tony Blair; Douglas
Thompson's homage to Sinatra: James McKillop reminding us of the missing jigsaw
piece in the Oxford murder of Michael Meenaghan; David Belcher's telephone
conversation with Marianne Faithfull; Julie Davidson taking a swipe at our
inability to recognise commonsense when it comes to eating cows; and Jim
Traynor sighing deeply, attempting for the umpteenth time to analyse the
unfathomable Paul Gascoigne.
All made Friday's Herald (December 8) an excellent read, and underlined the
feeling that Friday was indeed Friday, and not a Monday.
And then there was Jack McLean, with his wee gem of an article still trying
valiantly to come to terms with modern technology, using I assume, Humphy
Gogart black'n'white movie typewriter, and a ``bad word'' to get across the
point that there's no such thing as technological progress.
Unfortunately for Jack that same Herald proved to be a virtual nightmare for
his future. For it revealed that at midnight on Thursday last a probe from the
spacecraft Galileo entered the atmosphere of Jupiter after a journey of 2.3
billion miles and at times reached speeds of more than 100,000 miles an hour.
This man-made cone-shaped probe had to hit the outer layer of Jupiter at the
absolutely correct angle, otherwise to be destroyed or lost in space forever.
After a six-year journey, and with the help of computers and other
technological bric--brac, they got it right.
I don't know about Jack McLean but it impresses me.
No more can he skite with the back of his hand anything that smacks of progress
beyond the ballpoint pen. no more can he boast to his friends of his admiration
of William Tell and his gifted eye for hitting targets at a distance.
I have a feeling Jack McLean thinks the last great technological innovation was
the bow.'n'.arra.'
Tom Gill,
51 Mains River,
Park Mains, Erskine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
