<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Report reveals unseen influence of institutional investor at work</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897362</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INSTITUTIONAL investors are now exercising significant behind-the-scenes
influence on the corporate governance of the companies in which they invest,
according to research by the Chartered Association of Certified Accountants
(CACA).
The findings precede the launch next month of the Hampel Committee, successor
to the Cadbury Committee on Corporate Governance.
Research author John Holland, Professor of International Banking and Finance at
the University of Glasgow, said such influence often went beyond the approach
recommended by the Cadbury Committee by pursuing shareholder accountability
issues through direct dialogue with managers and the board.
The Cadbury Report called on institutional investors to play a more important
role in securing better corporate governance; to take a positive interest in
the composition of the board; to make positive use of their voting rights and
to disclose their policies on the use of voting rights.
Professor Holland's research, based on in-depth interviews with 27 fund
directors/managers chosen from the top 35 UK equity investing financial
institutions, shows institutional investors regularly intervene and influence
governance issues, usually with the aim of improving corporate financial
performance, rather than ensuring compliance with corporate governance
principles as such. The approach goes beyond shareholder vote wielding.
According to Professor Holland, financial institutions consider a close working
relationship based on honesty, integrity, stable stakeholding and regular
contact to be one of the most effective means by which their influence can be
exercised. Indeed, they make extensive use of these links to influence a
company before it makes decisions on issues such as remuneration, perks, length
of contracts, succession and separation of the roles of chairman and chief
executive.
``Financial institutions often use new proposals by a company, for example a
new executive pay scheme, as an opportunity to raise corporate governance
compliance issues. However, they also use the opportunity to probe whether the
proposals are going to improve the financial performance of the company,'' said
Professor Holland.
Much of this influence and intervention is conducted away from the public gaze.
Fund directors identified the reasons for this as being the libel and slander
laws in the UK, a culture of secrecy and politeness, the speed and efficiency
of the process, the ``clubby'' nature of the City and a preference on all sides
for a private process rather than public disputes.
Professor Holland's research concludes: ``The overall effectiveness of the
monitoring process adopted by financial institutions should not be ignored,
when future corporate governance regulation is being considered.''
Copies of the report are available from CACA's Glasgow office, telephone 0141
309 399, priced at #9.95.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
