<HEADLINE>Pearson shares slide as charges rise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974897363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REORGANISATION costs will lead to Pearson's results for 1995 coming in below
market estimates, the media group said yesterday and promptly saw its shares
slide 49p to 618p, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
Earnings per share are expected to be ``modestly below'' analysts' estimates of
between 29.3p and 34.1p, according to director of public affairs Duncan
Campbell-Smith. Pearson's reshaping exercise will result in reorganisation
expenses of #45m and will also affect operating profits. Changes have been made
at the Financial Times and Westminster Press which should benefit margins;
educational publishers Addison Wesley and Longman have been merged; and savings
have been identified in back-office functions and distribution. Pearson is
confident it will achieve a good return on its cost-cutting expenditure.
Chairman Lord Blakenham said it has made excellent headway with its plans to
build a global television business. Results from the programme maker Grundy
Worldwide, acquired in May, will exceed expectations.
The Financial Times marked time as a result of higher newsprint prices and a
difficult advertising climate, while Westminster Press benefited from doubled
margins. Recoletos, the Spanish newspaper acquired in 1994, is trading strongly.
FT Information is seeing results ahead of expectations from the merger of
Interactive Data Corporation and Extel, which is ahead of schedule.
</TEXT>
