<DOCID>GH951214-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theatre The Simpleton of the Unexpected Isles, Orange Tree, Richmond</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WELL, this is an odd dish to set before the king for Christmas. The Simpleton,
one of the last plays Shaw wrote satirising the uselessness of human utopias
certainly shows Shaw's intellectual energy remarkably undiminished at 70-odd.
Despite this and Walter's clever, in-the-round production, the play itself,
with its gunboats, descending angels, and reports of uproar on the streets of
London devices feels dramatically inert. Maybe that's because though the ideas
themselves still bubble with life, the plot is, to say the least, limp.
Set on a mythical island, somewhere in the Indian empire, its central theme -
one of renewal, eugenics and the mixing of races - is topical not to say
thought-provoking about how to create better, more morally responsible people.
But it lapses into preposterousness as Shaw shows a quartet of Brits and an
Indian god and goddess polygamously experimenting with love and upbringing, and
scandalising a young Church of England clergyman - the simpleton of the title.
In reality, it becomes no more than an excuse for Shaw to blast off against
Western, particularly English, assumed superiority and complacency.
``Let life come to you,'' declares Constance Barrie's brisk young northerner at
the beginning - a sentiment repeated like a refrain throughout. Life, Shaw
suggests, is full of the unexpected. We should welcome it. Paradoxically, the
play also suggests the impossibility of human perfectness. After all the
experiments, what's left, as in the Garden of Eden, is man and woman, to work
out their salvations - together - a somewhat overworked and familiar Shavian
conclusion. A bauble with teeth you might say, but neither sparkling nor sharp
enough.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000163</DOCNO>
