<HEADLINE>Real tartan tax in Skye</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE on Skye are observing the antics of Mr Michael Forsyth with some incredulity
as he runs around warning us about the ``Tartan Tax'' and tries to manipulate
the Scottish CBI into joining him.
The right for some future Scottish Parliament to raise taxes, or for that
matter a Westminster Parliament to do so, does not constitute a tax, as any
schoolchild would tell him.
If Mr Forsyth is really telling us that he doesn't trust the Scots with
tax-raising powers why does he not say so?
This Government is in fact introducing a new major tax, and as usual is
experimenting with it on the Scots by introducing a toll on the new Skye Bridge
which far exceeds any such toll in Britain or in Europe.
I wonder if Mr Forsyth would like to venture an opinion on what effect this
massive Government tariff will have on the fragile rural economy of our island.
Were Mr Forsyth to come up and meet the people who are trying to run businesses
on Skye he would find we are more concerned with real tariffs currently
affecting us than any imagined tartan tax.
Andy Anderson,
22 Earlais,
Isle of Skye.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
