<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quadrupalised surnames</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE no sympathy for either the Doughertys or the Hendersons (December 9).
Having the same first names in a family should be illegal. Never mind the minor
problems it causes within the family; you should see the misinformation turmoil
it creates in officialdom, particularly in medical records.
But there is a far more serious problem with surnames on the horizon. It is
becoming increasingly popular for partners to bestow both surnames on their
children. At first this seems a very sensible idea - why should only the male
surname be passed on?
But what happens when one double-barrelled name marries another? Where will it
all end?
Most record systems would explode when fed quadrupalised surnames, and just
think of the size and complexity of the resulting telephone directory.
Could I therefore propose a random allocation of either partner's surname to
the first child with the next child switching, and so on? Another idea would be
the composition of a sort of computer-generated anagram based on a selection of
some letters from both surnames. Any other ideas?
Or is all of this just our society in the throes of a transition where the
female partner's name will inevitably prevail? Would it just be better for us
men to give way gracefully?
Dr Colin Guthrie,
1448 Dumbarton Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951214-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951214-000166</DOCID>
