<HEADLINE>The whisky trail in London</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974897369</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENING the New York Times Magazine one sees a beautiful colour photograph of a
rustic whisky distillery. In elegant type style it carries the headings,
Trekking Scotland's Whisky Trails, and Memorable Excursions in Scotch Whisky
Country. Very attractive.
Under it are seven column-inches of text on Scotch and how well it is doing in
the US. Then it says: Step one - crossing the pond: ``Getting to Scotland and
England from metropolitan New York is simple''. It lists the main airlines that
fly to London, Birmingham, and Manchester.
I had never heard of Scotch distilleries in England.d
Undaunted, the text goes on, ``Spend a few days enjoying London's seemingly
infinite roster of activities''.
The usual sights and attractions are mentioned, and, after pointing out that
British Airways tours are the best in the business, readers are told to contact
our old friends the British Tourist Authority at 551 Fifth Avenue, New York:
``Ask specifically for the London Planner, the London Guide, and the London
White Card Pass to selected museums and galleries''.
The glories of England took up 12!s  column-inches.
My mouth was a bit dry by this time. At last, the text informs that British
Airways flies direct to Glasgow, and that Northwest Airlines flies direct from
Boston to Glasgow.
Many of the best known distilleries are mentioned. The text ends with a panel
explaining, ``What is Scotch whisky?'' I was glad that they remembered to
include it before the space ran out.
The British Tourist Authority is always ready to promote London and England. I
do not recall ever seeing an exhortation to visit beautiful and cultural
Scotland and drop in on us in London if you still have the time and inclination.
This goes on year after year. No-one in Scotland ever does anything about it.
Daniel Clark,
38 Panda Lane, Whiting,
New Jersey, USA.
</TEXT>
