<DATE>951214</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New retail park project poses rental challenge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>27</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commercial and industrial property</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974897374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S most successful retail park is facing some intense competition.
Recently opened on a prominent site on the city bypass, Edinburgh's 151,000 sq
ft Hermiston Gait retail park has achieved rentals of #22 per sq ft - a
Scottish record. But that record is already under threat from a #25m rival
which has not yet been built.
Construction is poised to begin at Craigleith in Edinburgh's north western
suburbs where a new scheme has just gained an `open use' consent for 107,270
sq.ft of non-food shopping. The development is adjacent to the existing
Sainsbury supermarket on Craigleith Road.
The Craigleith scheme will be carried out by Retail Parks (Scotland) Ltd, a
joint venture between Miller Developments and Stannifer Ltd. The new scheme
will be anchored by UK retailer Homebase, which will operate from a 38,480
sq.ft unit with a garden centre of 11,500 sq.ft. Open consents are a common
feature of retail parks in the East of Scotland, but are almost unknown in the
West. Such consents allow traditional high street retailers to locate on the
parks instead of the DIY, carpet, and furnishing specialists to which retail
parks in the West of Scotland are largely restricted.
As a result, Hermiston Gait has attracted high street chains such as Olympus,
Shoe City, Children's World, and Byte Computers. Craigleith will be aiming to
attract the same type of retailer, a factor which could push rentals to new
records. Market rumour has it that would-be tenants at Craigleith are having to
start negotiations at over #20 per sq ft. But joint letting agents, Peter
Campbell &amp; Co and Jones Lang Wootton, are coy about admitting the level of
rentals being demanded.
``We have only just started our marketing campaign and at this stage we're not
prepared to announce the kind of rentals we are after,'' says Peter Campbell.
But he was quick to point out that Craigleith's catchment area is more
prosperous than Hermiston Gait's, another factor which could boost rents at
Craigleith. Since the Scottish Office announced earlier this year that the
development of out-of-town shopping centres is likely to be restricted in
future, retailers have been scrambling to gain access to schemes which still
have unoccupied units, adding further upward impetus to rentals. Meanwhile, the
traditional DIY and flatpack operators who occupy the sheds on retail parks
have got used to paying rentals of around #10 per sq ft.
It remains to be seen whether they are prepared to compete with high street
retailers at #20 per sq ft or more for access to the more prestigious schemes.
The ultimate winner of Edinburgh's out-of-town store wars will be the Miller
Group. The company is a joint venture partner at both Hermiston Gait and
Craigleith.
</TEXT>
